Description: Pull on slopey holds and work your way up a large flake feature. Traverse left and up though large holds to the anchor.
Location: Directly left of Don't Mess With The Bull

Description: On the outside of the tower, 18' left of the hallway entrance
A classic as far as I know.  Solid Rock!!!
Location: Step outside of the intial entrance to the Mr. Jimmy Hallway. The route starts in the crack on the right side of the arete on E.M.J. Wall opposite of "Big Wall Greg's Chicken Shack".
Protection: Mixed gear- varied sizes, 3 QD + anchor.

Description: This route starts on Which Side Are You On? but after the third bolt use the left line to stay off of Big Wall Greg's Chicken Shack.
This route works up the Arete to the left of Big Wall Greg's Chicken Shack.  Cut right back onto Greg's after the fourth bolt to keep it at .10c.
Relatively low angle route with good hands and feet.
Location: The leftmost route on the main face of the Mr. Jimmy boulder. It will be the first route you see on the Mr. Jimmy boulder if approaching from the dog walk.    It is on the right side of the arete (Piss Ant is the route on the left). Immediately to its right are "Spiders from Mars 10b" and then "Venom 10a."

Description: This route is located between Big Wall Greg's Chicken Shack and Venom.  Go straight up through the slab.
FirstAscent: (TR) Graham Beecher-Bailey, Chris Schmick, 2001 1st Free Lead Jeff Frizzell, Dave Downy, 2003

Description: The physical crux is down low, but the mental crux is the upper slab.  Pull a couple easy moves to the crux.  Pull over the lip to super thin and technical slab climbing at it's finest.
Location: twenty feet right of Big Wall Greg's Chicken Shack

Description: Right of Venom.  Start on rock and climb straight up.
Location: Mr. Jimmy, right of Venom.

Description: Climbs the far Right arete of the Jimmy block. Awesome pocket climbing on an exposed arete. Super technical climbing.
Location: Far right arete on the jimmy block.

Description: This route is located on the backside of the Jimmy boulder. Scramble up the large boulder by Chimichonga to reach the start of the route.
Location: The back side of the Mr. Jimmy boulder, the start of the route is about 25 ft off the ground.

Description: Easy start lay backing to an off width crux about 2/3s of the way up. Probably doesn't see a lot of traffic.
Location: In the Mr. Jimmy hallway about 20ft to the right of Luscious Babes. It's a clean climb, no boulders or trees in the climb. Top out, or set a top rope and then rap down.
Protection: Big gear if you lead it, we tied off to trees to set up a top rope anchor on the left side (right facing) corner of the off width dihedral.

Description: Scramble up the lower angle corner slab.    An ok diversion and a reasonable way to set a TR on an adjacent route, providing one is solid at the grade.    Nice rock.
Location: In the corner directly behind Mr. Jimmy.
Protection: Trad route, most likely soloed or TR'd.

Description: Still in the main hallway, it's the long clean slab down the slope and left of Screamery.  Fun route.

Old school top rope route. Continuing through the hallway past Luscious Babes, turn right into a narrower hallway. On the boulder to your left, climb just to the right of the center of the face. You'll be below Spirit
Location: Between spirit and Luscious Babes

Description: Good jam crack that climbs a corner through a short wider section and then traverses out underneath a roof. A bit burly for the grade but a fun trad route.
Location: This route is the corner about 12 feet right of Chimichonga. It is in the L shaped hallway just past Luscious Babes.
Protection: Cams .4-3 would suffice. A .75 protects off the ground very well. Protect the end of the roof traverse well or else you'll be taking a large fall if you fall going to the chimichonga bolt (either .75 above the lip or a 3 in the roof). Bring two quickdraws as you merge with the last two bolts on Chimichonga

Description: About 12' left of Lucky, stem the hallway, commit to the main wall and follow the sport line.
Fun and steep 5.9 climbing pulling over multiple bulges. Very similar in character to the next 5.9 to the right, and that route could easily be toproped from the same anchor as this one.
Location: The first route to the right of "Spits of Swallows" on the main Beaver Wall. Leftmost route of Beaver Wall right.

Description: More fun, steep 5.9 climbing, starts of with some steep jug hauling then pull over some more bulges.
Location: Just to the right of the first unknown 5.9. This is the second route around right from "Spits or Swallows" on the main Beaver Wall. It is the second route from the left on Beaver Wall Right.

Description: Time to drop that brush and those Solutions and lace up your TC pros because what your lucky gym rat ass has just stumbled upon is a sport bolted chimney. Very forgiving for chimney climbing, and surprisingly quite enjoyable.  Crux is likely getting off the ground, otherwise things seem to get progressively easier the higher you get...depending on your body size of course.  --  Can also be led on gear by squeezing farther in, which would make it almost an entirely separate route...
Location: The obvious bolted chimney to the right of two steep 5.9s. The third route to the right of "Spits or Swallows" 12a (The last route on the right side of the main Beaver Wall)
Protection: 6 bolts to a 2 bolt anchor. Or gear if you want an extra challenge.

Description: Climb bulge and pockets to a bulge with great pocket with a shallow crack above,(crux) a very tricky  crux,
Location: Between Beaver Wall and Mr Jimmy Boulder,  Just to the right of Beaver Wall, on the next buttress, 1st bolted line to the right of dirty chimney,

Description: Start with some fun pocket pulling, reach a burly, reachy stand-up single move crux, that seemed to me to be somewhat improbable for 5.11, and continue romping up to the anchors.
Location: The second route to the right of the obvious bolted chimney. The third route to the left of Chimichonga 5.8. Start by a 2 foot tall tree stump.
Protection: 5 bolts to 2 bolt anchor. Easy to set on toprope from either of the 5.10s to the right, if one were so inclined.

Description: Pull down on the holds, and go up. Another classic pocket-pulling adventure.
Location: Second route around to the left from Chimichonga, route to the right of Cougar Love 11b.
Protection: 5 bolts, 2 bolt anchor. Anchor is very easy to reach from the 10a to the right, if one were so inclined.

Description: A good introductory 5.10, with a single move that might be 10a mixed in with a lot of fun, juggy 5.8/5.9 climbing.
Location: Rightmost route on Beaver wall Right. First route to the left of Chimichonga. Immediately right of Cats in the Cradle.

Description: Easy route left of "Flingin' the Hog", warm up for the area. Fun moves, I did alot of palming.
Location: Just left of "Flingin' the Hog"

Description: New route between Mod Squad and Flinging the Hog.  The start is pretty easy, so it’s easy to mistake for Mod if you don’t know the area/have a guidebook.  Felt a bit harder than Mod, maybe 9+/10-.  Tricky crux pulling the bulge.
Location: First route on the face around the corner from the obvious, chalked 10d around the corner.  Mod Squad is to the left.
Protection: Bolted like a gym - 10+ 2 for the anchors.

Description: Climb is in the corner left of the Beaver Wall.  Fun moves to the top!  A good route to warm up on for the rest of the hard routes.
Location: Between corner and arete, left of the Beaver Wall.

Description: Fun climbing until the last bolt, then things go south. No idea what you're supposed to do here, but whatever you do you're gonna need a wire brush because everything up above the last bolt is filthy and covered in moss and dirt (as of 10/12/15). But its only for about two moves. Have fun.
Location: Next route right of Flingin Hog, first and leftmost route on the main beaver wall. Left of "Legends of the Fall"

Description: Another hard route to finish of this pumpy wall.  Left most climb on wall.  Climb left of the big tree.
Location: Left of the big tree.

Description: A great hard route for someone who wants to sample the goods.  Climb starts in grey streak 20ft left of crack, and climbs right of the big tree.
Location: 20ft. left of obvious crack.

Description: Overhung the whole way.  Make awkward hard moves to full body rest 20' feet up.  Take a deep breath and climb the steep crack using jams and face holds to a pumpy and slightly run-out finish above bomber gear.   The route is called "Who Needs Friends" because it was bolted.  IMHO I think it climbs nicely as a trad route.
Protection: Bring a large piece (#4 or #5 camalot) for the beginning and then varied sizes the rest of the way (yellow alien through #3 camalot) or just clip the 6 bolts to 2 bolt anchor.
FirstAscent: Chris Schmick and Greg Thomas (sport) Andy Boone and Dan Caldwell (trad)

Description: Climb is just right of the crack.  Move right on to the face.  Hard would be a good way to explain it.
Location: Right of obvious crack.

Description: Start halfway between the crack and the corner.  Good climb.
Location: Left of Everybody Needs Friends.

Description: Same start as Tasmania Devil, but climb left at 3rd bolt.  Great route, with fun pumpy moves.
Location: Same start as Tasmania Devil.  First bolted lines on right side of wall.

Description: Start 6 ft. right of corner and go right at the 3rd bolt.  Fun!
Location: Same start as Everybody needs friends.  First route on right side of wall.

Description: Easy 5.11 climbing to mantle...should have ended at the lip for a better route.
Location: New route to the right of Tasmanian Devil.

Description: This is the line bolted to the left of Alaska.  Use the same entrance.
This route is located just to the left of Express Checkout Line and use the same entrance.  Has a low and balancy crux.
A very reach dependent low crux.  This route is just to the left of Cocoa Rae.  Traverse in on the ledge or climb up through the slab to access the first bolt on the bulge.
This route is the first bolted line to the left of Birthday Route.
FirstAscent: Keith Adams, Dave Downey, 1998  1st Free Lead David Kessler, Jeff Frizzell, 2004

Description: Somewhat featured and remarkably straightforward chimney climbing, I thought this was really pretty fun. Would be a great route to put beginner rock climbers on.
Location: This is the obvious chimney just left of "Birthday Route" and right of "Cocoa Rae."
Protection: TR off of "Birthday Route" anchors (chains hang right over this chimney), or lead with finger size to about a BD #3 for a maybe PG13 lead, but would be well protected for chimney climbing

Description: This is a tricky little climb that is located on the semi-pillar towards the end of Big Star.
This route is located just to the right of Birthday Route and features a low crux.
Start at the right end of an obvious rounded ledge.  Route angles slightly left at start.
Fairly sustained route with a distinct crux about half way up
Location: Approx 15' left of Mr. Allison's Cookies

Description: High quality with interesting movement
Location: Left of "Free Day" and Sun Ra

Description: Obvious vertical crack in the center of Big Star Wall.
Protection: Larger cams at the bottom, smaller at the top. Build an anchor using two trees.

Description: Battle through the first 20 feet to an easier section. Balance and finesse right then up through a shollow corner, (sexy/cruxy), to easier ground.    Four stars compared to most of the Falls but not quiet as good as Wishbone and Big Star
Location: Left of Big Star

Description: A little more continous than Glaxay 500 and Sun Ra. We travel the spaceways bad and beautiful
Location: Between Sun Ra and Galaxy

Description: 20ft left of Mary's Cookies.  Technical pocket start to the right-leaning crack 15ft up.  Pockets to horizontals to a halfway jug that starts the techy slab to the anchors.
Amazing slab/face on the right side of the big star wall.  The one with the spacy bolts.  The cruxes are well protected.  Movement is technical folowing the diagonal seam.
Location: Right side of the Big Star wall.
Protection: place a tcu between 1st and 2nd bolt if you want.

Description: Past Beaver wall, a sweet dihedral crack in the corner.
Left ward arching crack that leads into Chit Chat.
Climb this mixed route and clip bolts when you can. Keep looking for good gear placements as you go up.
Location: Only bolted route to the right of Chit Chat and Get Out Of My Kitchen

Description: Begin in a broken, right-facing dihedral system. Climb 20 feet up, 20 feet to the left, and 20 more feet up. Mantle on to the upper ramp and belay on small gear. The second pitch consists of a scramble up the ramp, past a bolt to the anchors.
Location: A few hundred feet left of the main Raging Intensity wall, look for an unappealing, broken, right facing dihedral with a ledge at 20 feet, a roof at 40 feet, and a ramp above that.
Protection: standard rack, small to medium gear primarily. bolted anchor at the top of the second pitch.

Description: Roughly 60' left of Tear Stained Eye. Bulgy route.You'll need at least a 50m rope to get back to the ground.
It is noted that the first bolt should be stick clipped.   Beginning off a small boulder, reach over left and grab the starting hold and follow bolts to the top.
Location: 15 feet left of Tear Stained Eye

Description: Tricky Techy at the bottom
Location: Left of Train in Vain

Description: Dirty bottom, fun top.
Location: 10ft left of prominent alcove, just left of "Pita" 5.10a

Description: Meander up the beautiful face left of No Paynes in Heaven.
Location: Left of No Paynes
FirstAscent: Ray Whaley Jeff Frizzell Matt Queen

Description: Climb the dihedral crack until it ends. Stem your way to the anchor after that.
Location: The dihedral crack directly right of PITA

Description: GREAT arete route, very technical.
Location: Obvious arete in the center of the wall.

Description: Climb up and through the weirdly shaped hueco in the center of the face. A few cruxes on this one, its not over till its over.
Location: 30ish feet to the right of Raging Intensity

Description: Route begins on poor underclings and trends right after the start, finishing on the slab headwall. Have fun figuring out the sequence.
Location: Starts under the small overhang about 50 feet left of Primrose Path.

Description: Climb the red face through blank sections.
Location: 30ish feet left of Jones'n In Jacksonville
FirstAscent: Equipped by Chris Loesch, First Ascent Brian Capps

Description: Hard crimpy holds and a few pockets. Stay strong on this one.
Location: To the right of the dihedral and Blazed Of Glory Project

Description: Climb up the overhanging flake and finish on the headway all. Watch out for the pump!
Location: First route to the left of Working Class.

Description: This route begins climbing up a right angling seam. Before getting into the overhang, you encounter a low crux on thin holds. After battling the overhang, you gain the face to encounter an even more challenging finish on more thin holds till the top. It's not over till it's over!
Location: The first route to the left of Zen Arcade/Manufacturing Consent.

Description: Shares the first few bolts with Manufacturing consent and moves up through the overhang with a difficult sequence at the lip. Mantel after the roof to bigger holds. Several difficults sections.
Location: The out standing prow on 5 star wall.

Description: It's the next route on the rounded corner, 30' left of Ladybug Lynn.  Veer right at the 2nd clip.
Start matched on horn and go straight up through face.
Location: North side of boulder, west side of trail, near the creek

Description: Short and fat and fun. Use just the offwidth crack to get up to the lip of the boulder and top out.
Location: East side of boulder on east side of trail.

Description: Start by walking your feet up the obvious ramp feature. At 10' there is a large ledge. Choose a final move to get over the lip. Fun and varied.
Location: On the large boulder facing the route Working Class. Walk off the backside of the boulder.

Description: Start matched on ledge at edge of roof. Campus, dyno, or foot jump your way to the lip.    Potential low start looks quite hard and holds look friable.
Location: East side of boulder, west side of trail

Description: Sit start in the pit and squeeze and shift your way up the prow. Cool and challenging.
Location: North side of boulder, east side of trail.

Description: Start matched on flake at chest height, head straight up to topout.
Location: Located on the main hiking trail. Sloped landing. Down climb back of boulder (V-Easy)

Description: Sit start on flake low and right, follow juggy flake holds slightly left then straight up. Choose holds carefully, holds on the left side of feature are delicate.
Location: North side of boulder, visible from trail.

Description: Use your head, shoulders, knees, and toes to overcome gravity on this one. Maybe pack a booster rocket or two!    Start matched on the right side of the big ledge under the boulder and work straight up the sloping pockets until you're standing on the small ledge at head height.
Location: South side of boulder, west side of trail down by the creek. This problem roughly faces Both Sides of the Story.

Description: Sit start at left end of ledge, work straight up nice pockets to crux at top out
Location: North side of boulder

Description: Start matched in hole to the right.
Location: East side of boulder, just west of trail

Description: Sit start in hole on left side of face. Work up to horizontal and finish same as problem 1. Don't fall in the water.
Location: East side of boulder, just on west side of the trail

Description: Work straight up the slabby face on nice holds.
Location: South face of Knock First boulder, east side of trail

Description: Start at the bottom left side of the boulder on right hand iron flake crimp gaston and left hand edge. Follow the lip up and right using a combination of slopers pockets and edges eventually topping out on the tallest point of the boulder.
Location: Downhill from zen arcade. It is the shorter of the two triangular shaped boulders that are next to each other.

Description: Climb up this steep face using hold that get smaller as you climb higher. Move up and left near the 5th bolt.
Location: Around the corner from Fluffy Fly

Description: Climb The Big Easy, and move up and right at the 5th bolt
Location: Shares the start with The Big Easy

Description: Climb the tall face next to an obvious water groove.
Location: Directly under the overhang of Hobo Cave

Description: Go to ledge, tram right, pull roof.
Location: Start 45 feet left of Animal Husbandry/Belching Fiance.
FirstAscent: Mika Balossi, Darrell Sauer, Jeff Stockton 2003

Description: P1:Climb up the right most crack in the three crack system, get behind large flake and traverse left to a semi spacious belay ledge and build anchor. Very very easy climbing the first pitch is simply to avoid the choss and rope drag. 5.5 P2:The fun climbing begins. Climb the corner crack which starts at small hands and slowly turns into fists of glory.
Location: 10 feet from base of belching fiancé.
Protection: Standard rack. One number six is convenient for first pitch. Anchor and rap off nearby tree at top.

Description: P1: same as fists of glory P2: a fun squeeze takes you to an easy mantle and then fun juggy liebacking. Big gear.
Location: To the right of fists of glory.

Description: Left top-out of Animal Husbandry.
Location: Left top-out of Animal Husbandry.

Description: Take the right top-out.
Location: First route on the left wall of Hobo Cave.

Description: This is an aid line that follows the dihedral feature that follows the roof up and left.
Location: In the corner of Hobo Cave

Description: Climb the obvious crack in the corner of hobo cave. Utilize really good hand jams and the occasional face hold till you reach the very fun, thin lie-back crux. Take advantage of three really good rests on your way up. Then make the final traverse to the anchors on "Animal Husbandry". The cave can also be topped out although it would have to be done in two pitches.
Location: In the corner of hobo cave; under the roof.
Protection: Big hands to finger sized cams.

Description: Easier climbing leads to a stopper crux.
Location: The line to the left of "Living on the Edge".

Description: Rightmost route.
Location: Rightmost line in Hobo Cave.

Description: Moving right and around the corner from Hobo Cave, the first sport route you will find is Y TY N. Its short, but thuggy.
Location: First sport route to the right of Hobo Cave

Description: Climb the arete
Location: The arete to the right of Y TY N

Description: Climb arete/face just to the left of of "Ego Tripping".   Leftmost bolted route/closest to tracks on southwest face.    May be in the low 5.9 range?   Avoid power lines (or grab them for the crux of your life)!

This route climbs the face behind the large tree in between "Electrocutioner" and "Into the Sun". Great face climbing on great holds. One of the more sustained 10a's at the falls, this one will test your patience if you're at your limit.     "The crux is pretty hard if you don't see it. I happened to see it the first time thus the 10a grade. Jack it and its definately harder. Sweet finish huh?"   -Jeff Frizzell (FA)
Location: The start is located just behind a large tree. Look for the line of bolts up the face between "Electrocutioner" and "Into The Sun".

Description: This is a really cool and reletively long pockety line.  With a neat undercling-y and pocket-y crux right near the top, it is really fun.  Maybe a little hard for the grade but uber cool.
Location: As you turn into the area from the railroad tracks it is on the right hand side of the free standing tower on your left.  As usual rap, don't lower, from the anchors on top.

Description: Back to back boulder problems on pockets lead into fun, long moves between good crimps. Surpisingly powerful and dynamic compared to other routes at railroad rock, especially if you happen to find many of the holds just out of reach.
Back to back cruxes down low lead to easier terrain above.
Location: This route is located on the right side of the wall, directly to the right of "Barbarians at the Gate", and to the left, around the arete of "Where's My Bourbon".

Description: Goes up the rightward arching arete. 5 stars in the guidebook!
Location: Right of "Fragile Egos" it takes the arete heading towards "Blue Velvet". "Damn Yankees" is to the left 5.12b

Description: It was a fine day when Rich and Rob decided to equip this amazing line.  Beautiful pockets up the center of the corridor wall.  Right of Where's My Bourbon.  Not to be missed.
Location: Railroad area, inside corridor, center of the wall, right of Where's my bourbon

Description: Nice movement to a crux 3/4 the way up. Classic.
Location: Just right of "Blue Velvet." Start on ledge then left to first bolt.

Description: An amazing climb using a wide variety of holds. Keep it together for the crux near the top!
Location: This route begins on top of the pile of large boulders at the base of Railroad Rock, and is found between "Wild at Heart" to the left, and "The Drifter" on the right.

Description: Another amazing route at railroad rock. Begin much like the other routes with easier climbing through mostly good pockets, before pulling the crux which involves monos, thin crimps, and maybe some deadpoints. A great route to do for those who have climbed Wild at Heart a few too many times and are looking for a little more of a challenge.
Location: Face left of "Astological".

Description: Technical with hidden holds around the right corner.
Location: Arete far right from "Wild at Heart"

Description: Climb up and eventually through a small gulley
Location: 15ish feet left of Procrastination

Description: The crux is the last move before the anchors.  Most of the hand and foot placements are on large iron flakes.
Location: The routes is near the end of the railroad area.  It is about 170 feet from the 2nd class walk up gully.  It is between Mother's day special and Cheap fame.

Description: Fun slab/small pocket traverse. Avoid using jugs on 'Procrastination'.
Location: Starts by large slanted crack 20 feet right of 'Procrastination'. Move up and traverse upwards left to anchors.
FirstAscent: Jeff Allison, Jim Schneider, Mother's Day 1994

Description: Climb surprisingly fun offwidth/squeeze in the corner.  Jam in while you jam out to whatever song is stuck in your head at the time. A good warm-up for Feeding the Rat around the corner.    This was probably FA'ed sometime in the 80s, but I haven't found a record of it.  If you did, let me know and I'll update it.
Location: It's the crack left around the corner from Feeding the Rat.
Protection: A single rack of cams. I brought big gear (read: a #5, #6, and Valley Giant 12" cam) and used them, but there seemed to be sufficient smaller pro deep back in the chimney.    (Small) tree anchor at the top.
FirstAscent: Nick Tripp 2018, or probably some guy in the 80s

RouteName: Top Of The Morning To You
Description: Climb the Lighter Colored "White" face to the right of a gully that zig zags.
Location: Left and around the corner from Bottom Feeder

Description: Fight you way to the to the slab at the start to find yourself on a technical slab, making use of pockets and the arete.
Location: In the center of the back wall. Located between "Slab Stick Comedy" on the right, and "Top to the Mourning to You" on the left.

Description: Wide, offwidth, squeeze, grovelling fun!!!!
Location: Obvious wide crack left of Slab Stick Comedy, right of Bottom Feeder
Protection: Two #6 would be nice, Big bro's, anchor on tree

Description: A really wild and, as the name implies, hard slab.  A wacky thumb mantel crux on often moss covered rock often proves interesting.
Location: If you enter the Railroad area from the railroad it is directly across from the railroad about a hundred feet away.  the furthest right route on the slabby wall.

Description: Nice looking dihedral.
Location: Obvious dihedral in RR hallway.

Description: A super technical climb that goes up the wall perpindicual to Slab Stick Comedy.  Way hard and way cool.
Location: It is a thinly pocketed line on the middle of the wall perpindicular to Slab Stick comedy.  To date the only line on the wall.

Description: Climb the face between the tree on the left side, and the right arete.
Location: The face around the arete, to the left from IN/Access Granted.

Description: Start on the large block and climb up the left leaning crack, then proceed to climb the face and arete.
Location: on the front wall, facing the tracks. Shares the same start as Access Granted.

Description: Begin on the large block (same start as "IN"), but break off right.
Location: On the front wall facing the railroad tracks. Shares the same start as "IN".

Description: A totally cool crack in a right facing dihedral.
Location: As you face the area from the railroad it is a dihedral crack slightly to the rigt.

Description: It is the sweeping crack (get it?) with the same start as Creeper.  Start as Creeper, but cut right and ascend the sweeping slabby dihedral.
Location: just to the right of Creeper.

Description: Alternating right and left facing crack.    "5.9ish" in Eric Ulner's "Vertical Heartland".
Location: Right of the Sweeper/Creeper ramp system

Description: A WAAAYYY hard overhung and seemingly featureless face near the arete on the lefthand side of the face.
Location: If you look from the railroad tracks it is the area you are looking directly at through the trees.

Description: The bad is the decent.  ****The rap tree is dead and decayed.  *****
Protection: 4 bolts.  The rap tree is so dead, I would say there is no anchors at the top.   The last bolt does have a quick link, so you can lower off the bolt.

Description: Big holds, relatively long-ish moves, slightly overhanging, mossy/dirty finish.
Location: The left bolted route on the right half of the graduation formation.
FirstAscent: Lance Lippert, Matt Jockers, Scott Paynton 1997

Description: Crack formation in an inside corner shaped like like the state. Ascend where the Mississippi River would be.
Location: 150 ft past the 2nd class
FirstAscent: John Hein, Dan McMillan, Mark Wilson

Description: Short but good, beginner-friendly for sure. Start at the bottom, climb to the top. Use the holds.
Location: Furtherest left route at the gallery. It's the one with 3 bolts.

Description: Low crux. One move wonder. Fun first clip.
Location: 5 feet left of the large crack near Group Therapy.

Description: Overhung crack to the left of Group Therapy.  When crack ends, climb to the left or right (your choice) and top out on either Group Therapy or King's Jester.
Location: Located between Group Therapy and King's Jester.

Description: Overhanging jug haul. A hold broke off the original line, increasing the difficulty. Keep an eye out for the no hands rest ~2/3 of the way up!
Location: After you reach the Gallery, walk right around the corner and you will find this glorious overhanging jug haul. You'll know the line when you see it, if its a weekend you'll know it by the line on the ground. First bolted route right of the obvious "Squirrel House Crack."
FirstAscent: Alan Carrier + Co. 1989, FFA Eric Ulner 1989

Description: Somewhat sustained difficulty. Hard stuff seemed to be in the middle.
Location: Its the overhanging jug haul just around the 90 degree corner.
Protection: 6QD + anchor. one bolt is very hard to see from the ground.

Description: Easy pocket climbing, leads to a crux pulling the bulge, and ends on a stint of slab.
Location: Leftmost route in the Gallery before the corner.(Not the arete)
FirstAscent: Lawrence Stuemke 1988 First Free Lead Chris Schmick 1999

Description: Pocket climbing, to a bulge crux. Slabish ending.
Location: Immediately to the right of Earthbound Misfit.

Description: Another classic line at the Gallery, start on easy terrain and move through several cruxes up higher.
Location: From Group Therapy, this is the fourth bolted route to the right. From the obvious 15 ft tall flake feature at the start of Deep throat/King's Jester, it is the next bolted line to the left.

Description: Pulling the overhang is entertaining.
Location: Starts to the right of Sore Throat in the scoop and goes up through the overhang.
Protection: 4 bolts + anchors. Easier bottom climbing is protectable.

Description: Start on the big crack 10 feet further left of The Walrus.  Go up through the vertical seam.  Bottom can protect with wedges if you need them.     Variation 5.10c: Stay a few feet right of the 2nd clip.
Sustained high quality route, makes a great warm-up.  Crux is somewhat height-dependent and involves surmounting the first bulge about half way up. Slab top out.
Location: Located on Gallery wall, third sport climb from the right.

Description: Interesting climbing, different than most of the routes at the Gallery. The anchor is set unnecessarily far back up a lichen covered slab, but one could easily use "The Walrus" anchor just to the left before the low-angle slab.
Location: Located on the right side of the gallery, this is the first bolted route to the left (about 15') of the obvious "Cringe Chimney." It is just to the right of "The Walrus."

Description: Set up a top rope and stem your way up the chimney
Location: The wide chimney feature to the left of The Minstrel

Description: Start to the right of chemney about 6ft, after the last bolt there is a gear placement in a pocket, a #3 tri-cam , if you need it, may have been retro bolted,
Location: about 100ft to right of Group Therapy,

Description: First route right of the Minstrel
Climb the face near the hanging pine
Location: 30ish feet to the right of Crybaby Club

Description: Climb just left of the arete on steepness.
Location: Furthest left route on the west side.

Description: The left of three 10's on the west side of the boulder.
Location: It's to the right of Energizer on the west side of the boulder.

Description: Middle of the 10's on the west side.
Location: It's the second route on the west side of the boulder.

Description: A short route on the west side.
Location: West side of the boulder furthest right.

Description: Super fun, technical, bouldery start using the huge roof feature directly below the first bolt. Navigate the juggy tufa into a couple shallow holds on your way to the huge rail. Easy pocket and hueco climbing diagonally out right to the anchors.    Couldn't find this in any guidebooks or in the memory of local John Paine. Let me know if you know anything about it.
Location: This route starts like 50 feet left of Touch My Shelf and goes up and right after the steep overhang. We started under the first bolt and slightly to the right so we could utilize the cool roof feature, which is absolutely worth the effort.
Protection: Route was bolted...a long time ago. Seems to have been forgotten about--bolts are a little rusty, anchor chains/biners could use some love.    Also be ware. The hueceos and pockets up top are a little brittle so be gentle up there. This route is a little sandy/mossy, so go climb it!

Description: More steep goodness.
Location: First route encountered approaching from The Gallery.  On the right side of the overhanging wall.

Description: 100 feet left of Ragin' Cajun, stay inside broken block hallway. Starts in a roof with a large, flat flake. 5 QD to the first fixed anchor. Variation 5.13a. Two more QD left to the other fixed anchor. F/A Chris Schmick 2001 From "Vertical Heartland" 3rd edition by Eric Ulner
Location: Dirt trail leading up to the wall takes you directly to the start of the climb.

Description: A thought provoking and challenging climb for the grade on sculpted holds.  Don't let the top fool you!
Location: to the right of extinguisher, just in front of elm tree

Description: Beginning off the small boulder, pull through some tricky moves and the climbing get easier the higher you climb.
Location: To the right of Ridin' Cowgirls.

Description: Climb using small crips to reach the top.
Location: The short face just right of the small boulder

Description: Difficult moves off of thin holds, monos, and bad slopers on great stone = one difficult route!
Location: Found in between “Ice Harvest” on the left, and “Areteouffee” on the right.

Description: More challenging than it looks!
Location: Found in between “Ain’t No Sunshine” on the left, and “Rajun’ Cajun” on the right.

Description: Technical powerful climb.
Location: Found in between “Areteouffee” on the left, and “ Manhattan Project” on the right.

Description: Begins with a difficult boulder problem, which leads to hard sustained climbing and a blockbuster finish to the chains. To get full points for this route, avoid using the wall on the right. Contrived, I know.
Location: This route is found between “Rajun’ Cajun” on the left, and “Buckets of Jam” on the right.

Description: A bouldery start will get you onto the plates that  line the face, but you're not out of the bucket yet. Alternate jug hauling the face and thrutching in the wide crack until you come out to the ledge, where you can take a seat and consider your next move.     The anchor/descent is not ideal. You could scramble up the gully and try to find a tree to belay from, but I'm not sure what is available and getting down will be more of a chore. You can also traverse the ledge to the shiny new anchors two routes over and belay from there, but your follower might not be thrilled about the traverse.    Awkward route, but buckets of fun if you're into that kind of thing.
Location: Large dihedral crack on the big ledge.
Protection: Standard rack, big stuff is probably a good idea.

Description: Climb up the arete to the right.
Location: Found in between “Buckets of Jam” on the left and “Corporal Punishment” on the right.
Protection: 5 bolts. It’s advised to stick clip the first bolt:

Description: This route can either be done by reaching around the corner from Bill and Tees and clipping the first bolt, or by starting all the way on the ground and clipping the first of a traversing line of bolts that lead to the starts of the next few routes to the right. (Surely this will make more sense when seen in person).This route is fully bolted and does not require gear.
Location: Right and around the arete from Bill & Tee's Excellent Adventure
Protection: 7 or 8 bolts, depending on where you start.

Description: This route branches off of the rightward-traversing line of bolts leading from the start of Bill and Tee's. Shares anchors with Corporal Punishment.
Location: First route to the right of Corporal Punishment.

Description: A great looking almost blank face that have never been sent. Good Luck
Location: First sport route left of The Shootist
FirstAscent: Equipped by Chris Schmick, FA Brian Capps 2019

Description: The start of this route can be accessed by aiding to the third bolt of Stalking Horse and reaching out right to clip into the belay anchors. If you’re going to be belayed from the ground, you'll need a 50m rope to get back down.A large runout protects the anchors which are located at the very top of the cliff. It may be a good idea to rappel in to evaluate the top of the climb before committing.
Location: This is the first bolted route you will find left of Applejack Crack

Description: From behind the large tree, follow the thin crack upward until it widens into a large water groove off width/chimney at about 15 feet. Follow to the top.
Location: Just to the left of the end of The Gallery, just past the large chimney/gully.
Protection: Trad gear - large sizes and thin stuff for the beginning (I used micro-wires)

Description: Climb up to the depression near bolt 3. Be ready for hard moves
Location: First spot route to the right of Applejack Crack

Description: An odd route that definitely "strays" from the bolt line. The beginning is intentionally bolted to force a face move that is probably the crux of the climb but then the climb moves into the chimney for 2 bolts. Up higher there is a great looking, thin section of wall that is appealing but the path of least resistance climbs the dirty rock to the left.
Location: left side of gully (nice cool breeze) 30 feet left of Group Therapy. Last route on Applejack Wall in Yusuf's guide.

Description: About 30 feet right of "The Reckoning", easy moves up to a high block/ledge then climb the arete by its right side.
Protection: Use tree as anchors.  3 QD and a slider nut.

Description: Start 12 feet right of the arete and go straight up the face.

Starts on the slab between Viking Blood and The Flail.  A couple bolts of interesting slab climbing, followed by 3 bolts of business as the wall turns vertical to slightly overhanging toward the top.  Don't fall off the heartbreaker lurch to the chains!    The feet are pretty bad on this route.  You'd best pick a chilly day to ensure your rubber sticks! Also come with good skin, as there's a razor crimp at bolt 4.
Location: On the Battle Axe Tower, sandwiched between Viking Blood on the left and The Flail on the right.

Description: Start over the low roof and climb the face to anchors under the right of the high roof.

This is a former trad route that has since been bolted. It's a slab climb typical of jackson Falls, although with more features than you might expect. A little sketchy for the new leader, stick clip recommended in this case. Once established on the route, the first three bolts are pretty easy to clip. Keep moving right and you might need your belayer to describe the feet. Once you establish moving upward, it only gets easier to the top.
Location: On the right just to the left of the arete on the obvious slab of the actual Battle Axe Tower
Protection: 6 bolts (?) and shuts. Well protected, to the point of some rope drag.

Description: Start on the boulder and climb over the right of the low roof.

In the middle of the east wall, 15 feet right of Void Warrior. Initially, at rainy day 2002, Me and my friend from Poland, Tomasz Samitowski start bolting from the ground. We put 2 bolts. I equiped entire route 5 years later, after successful top rope attempt by my son Maciek. At this time I was not able even repeat first crux move.
Location: Middle of east wall
Protection: 2 old 3/8 bolts + 3 new 1/2x3.5 Hilti + new anchor (+chain)

Description: Long moves and some tricky climbing on pockets.   Possible climb above the anchor to the top of the tower. Established as solace, when I was not able to repeat  crux moves on my then 5 years old project on left.
Location: Far right of the east wall, between If I Could Fly on left and Wrecking Ball on north wall.

Description: Climb the overhanging prow of the tower, big dyno.
Start in a smooth, tiny right-facing corner then go up and left.  About 25 feet right of "Wrecking Ball", and just at the hallway entrance, its the leftward angling sport route.
The crux on this one is low to the ground. Don’t get too comfortable after the crux though, lack of feet makes it easy to punt before making it to the chains!
Location: The route directly to the left of “Tons of Fun”. The first route you encounter on the exam wall coming from the Dynasty wall.

Description: Climb up to a right-facing flake then the face and the left side of the bulge.  Lives up to it's namesake....
Protection: Chains are difficult to reach at top!

Description: Start 15 feet left of the small corner and climb up to the right of the high bulge.
Gear climb the left-facing dihedral.
A project given 5 stars in the guidebook, this has been sent since then. "Beautiful pockets leading to a steep slab top out.
Location: 15ft left of "The Bolted One"

Description: Gear climb the right-facing flake/crack in the corner.
Climb in the middle of the face.  Vertical, then steep.

Start 6 feet right of the alcove/chimney. Climb through the beginning bulged to gain the face, which is one of the most technical at Jackson. Pull onto the roof and get ready to crank. This climb is a great mix of balance and power, thin crimps and slopers, with a little spice to top things off.
Before entering the hallway, climb up and right on the left side of the steep face.
Rebolted this old JF project. Technical and bouldery start up a sloping seam followed by a good rest. Culminates in a hard deadpoint over a bulge from a bad pinch and a mono iron-jib.
Location: Right of "Splinter Faction."

Description: Tough lock off to start and hidden holds near the top. Are you a bolshevik?
Location: Starts on the lip on the right side of the large, horizontal roof. About halfway between the Jimmy boulder and Dynasty wall.

Description: A partially bolted route.
Location: 150 yards beyond the Munchkin Boulder

Description: Climb the route on the Munchkin Boulder found in the hallway corridor.
Location: The only bolted route on the Munchkin Boulder.

Description: Climb the short cliff face just right of the crack system.
Location: On the cliffline across from The Munchkin

Description: Beginning just right of the tree, climb the line up the middle of the face that is surrounded by huecos.
Location: To the right of the tree.

Description: The only drawback to this route is that it's short. Other than that its varied and challenging. Don't let the guidebook description deter you, the tops not really bad at all even if there is moss up there its still totally climbable.
Location: On the much smaller left wall, up and left from the main Dynasty/Emporer wall. On the main canyon wall opposite the Munchkin boulder. This is the right most of the 3 routes here. To the left is "Mighty Mouse" 11d, and left of that is "Tin Man" 11a.

Description: A great route on the left side of the wall. Climb through a short steep section to a puzzling crux, to a lower angle section leading to a final mantle at the chains. In other words, use the holds go up.
Location: Furthest left route on the large face of the Dynasty/Emporer wall. The only one that looks 5.9, ends below the big roof.

Description: Pull some serious moves on poor holds.
Location: This route is located between Flappin' Jack on the left, and Flair/DSB to the right.

Description: This project shares the start with DSB and Flaire, but moves left.
Location: Same start as DSB and Flaire

Description: Follow the flairing crack above the dihedral.
Location: Shares the same start as DSB, but head straight up instead of going right. This route is located between the routes Hydraulic Hyena on the left, and Dynasty/Emperor on the right.

Description: A great line on sculpted holds. No individual move is that hard, but the pump will get you if you're not careful!
Location: Start on the right angled crack and traverse right to the first bolt. Shares the same start as Flaire, and is between Hydraulic Hyena on the left, and Dynasty to the right.
Protection: 8 bolts. It would be wise to stick clip the first bolt!

Description: A serious endurance haul. Stacked boulder problems with lack of tests makes this one real hard!
Location: Shares the same start as Emperor of the North, stray left. This route is between DSB on the left and Empress of the South on the right.

Description: Bouldery down low with great pocket climbing.
Location: first bolted line on the left.

Description: Climb up the blunt arete.
Location: The last route on the right side of the wall, to the right of Emperor of the North/Dynasty.

Description: On the high point of the boulder inside the hallway.
Location: See abover

Description: This is a fun route especially on lead. The guide book says that it is a 5.10a but I would give it a 5.9 just because the main face is mostly slab with great stances and plenty of places to rest. Also I climbed this when the rock was wet inside the crack and it was still an easy climb for me. The crux is at the very top when you have to pull around and behind the prominent point.   The only bad thing about the route is that rope drag is almost unavoidable especially if you're setting a TR.
Location: This is the first large dihedral crack on the Royal Arch wall
Protection: This crack uses a range of different cam sizes. I used (2) #2, (1) #1, and (1) .75 BD Camalots along with a #1 metolius master cam and a .5 link cam. There are also two bolts at the top for anchors. no chains

Description: The hardest trad line in the canyon. Climb the thin crack till it's turns into a wide crack then top out.
Location: Locate hunters arrow chimney and no dogs allowed and in between you have the raconteur. There is a broken fixed nut about 15 feet up.
Protection: A little spicy. The one bomber fixed nut has now broken.

Description: Climb the crack
Location: The crack system directly right of The Raconteur

Description: Low crux to iron flakes at the top.
Location: This is the first bolted route to the left of the dihedral left of Deetle Dumps.
Protection: 5 QD, sling for last flake, + anchors.

Description: Climb the iron-plated line.
Location: Far left route when standing atop the shelf.

Description: Interesting moves through the first three bolts and then a little run out to the fourth bolt.
Location: Second line on the shelf.  Shares anchors with Arch Angel.

Description: Lower crux with fun moves all through the climb.  A little slabby and balancy as well.  Really fun moves pulling the roof at the end to clip anchors.
Location: Last route that starts on the shelf.  Moves up through the positive slab and then traverses left to the anchors above the roof.

Description: Cool line with a low crux and the another small one after the last bolt.
Location: This route is located 10 ft. right of Archangel.

Description: This route is located 10 feet right of The Meanest Flower.

Climb up and through a short overhang (fun!), past 2 bolts (crux at second bolt). After surmounting the bulge, scramble up a low 5th class crack system, with a maybe 5.8 mossy crux getting up to the anchor (Step left to share anchor with Ebee).
Location: Route immediately right of Ebee, look for the obvious crack/flake that starts above two bolts.
Protection: 2 bolts, and a couple pieces of gear, although the gear section feels about 5.8. Shares 2 bolt anchor with Ebee.

Description: Climb the bulging, three part roof network.
Location: Directly right of No Dancers

Description: Climb up the red colored smear on the wall.
Location: First sport route right of Kryptonite

Description: Open book gully.  Harder than it looks...
Location: Right of the Royal Arch Wall

Description: I thought this was a really great, very sustained technical climb. Epic shallow-stemming crux, sequential foot traverse. Small holds, but you don't have to pull super hard because the rock is vertical to less-than-vertical. Awesome. Climbs more like a Smith Rock 12a than most Jackson routes.
Location: Immediately to the right of the obvious water groove feature of "The Vow."

Description: Boulder up to a big ledge (currently the crux by a long shot because it is super mossy). Once there, enjoy fun, sequential and sometimes improbable technical climbing to the top. A good and varied route for sure.
Location: To the right of "My Head is Broke," which is bolted all the way to the ground. This one has the first bolt above above the ledge you boulder onto.

Pete's Lead is to the left of Smidgin.  The start is a left tilting ramp leading to the crack.  Get down by using the anchors for Smidgin provided it is not being used, or if the party on Smidgin doesn't mind sharing.
Protection: C4 Cam sizes .5 through 4. (4 is good at the crux but eliminates a solid fist jam)

Description: Slab route.
Location: Just left of Tina's Soul Food Kitchen and just right of Pete's Lead.

Description: This is a slab route that looks much easier from the ground.  The book Vertical Heartland has it listed as a 5.7, so I kept the rating.  It felt closer to a 5.9 to me.
Location: The route is the second bolted route to the right of the Trad route Peter's lead.

Description: The crux is the start of the route. This is a good litle route. A lot of fun moves can be found in the gully. You can stem, chimeny, or just smear your way up.
Location: The route is to the right of Tina's Soul Food Kitchen.
Protection: Protect the route with small pro. There are chains at the top. The route can also easly be toproped.

Description: Climb the not so easy start on Easy Gully. Gently reach right to clip the first bolt. Two back to back crux sections await you. Crank through the first and desperatly balance through the second.
Location: Starts on easy gully and moves right. Attack the two challenging bulges above.

Description: Direct start to Blood Beets. Pull hard through an initial boulder problem to a standing rest. Tackle a precision pockets section, then go straight into the coolest part of the route; 2 bulges of requiring some sort of wizardry to navigate. Ahhhhmazing!
Location: Starts 10 feet right of Easy Gulley

Description: Traverse along the crack parallel to the ground till you reach the jug rail on Who Let the Snakes Out, keep going on the rail till you reach another bolt on the 12c, then clip the anchors.
Location: Far left side of snakes roof is where the traverse begins. The route ends on the anchors of "here come the snakes"
Protection: Varied. small stuff till you reach the bolt.

Description: Climb up to the juggy rail.  Traverse to the right on said rail.  Clip chains.
Location: The route runs out the Left side of Snakes Roof.

Description: Big holds...big moves...bigger fun.
Location: This route goes right out the middle of Snakes Roof.
FirstAscent: Dave Groth, Rich Bechler & Rob Drysdale. 1990.

Description: Pull a few moves to get under the roof, set up for the huge crux throw, pull a couple more tough moves out the roof, then fight the pump at the sloper finish before the chains.
Location: This route goes out the right hand side of the roof.

Description: V5/6 problem to easier climbing
Location: On Arete between Feathered Serpent & Umbrella Girls

Description: Short, overhung route. Finishes at the scooped out dish just right of snakes roof.
Location: Far left route of Royal Arches wall. 15 feet right of Goin' Rogue.

Description: WOW! This one is hard. Moderate climbing to the third bolt takes you to a difficult boulder problem with a sloper from your nightmares.
Location: The bolt line directly to the right of “Umbrella Girl”.

Description: Start in the overhang for fun rock climbering moves. Grade is a guess, doesn't really matter anyway...
Location: Leftmost, tallest route on boulder
Protection: Bolted anchors.  Tricams for the flaring false huecos.

Description: Follows the obvious seam
Location: Middle route on boulder

Description: Try it no-hands!
Location: Rightmost, shortest route on boulder

Description: Fun chimney route.
Location: Just past Wave Wall as the cliff turns toward Main Falls. It is the obvious deep water groove splitting the outside corner.
Protection: Can use tree as anchor at top of route (2016).

Description: To clarify, Split Decision was originally done using the left-most features of Fine Nine, traversing left into the first bolt, and continuing straight up the bolt line. The first ascensionist proposed starting left of the bolts would be a better line, avoiding all Fine Nine holds and adding a difficult slab boulder to the beginning of the route. Perhaps consider this if you're some kind of purist, or if you have done the original line and would like an added challenge.
Location: On the main cliffline behind Lovely Tower, a few feet left of Fine Nine

Description: Follow the line of 3 bolts just the left of Fine Nine. The route goes straight up the slab with the help from committing smearing, quartz pebbles, and faint pockets.
Location: The route is on Wave Wall about 10 feet left of Fine Nine. It is directly opposite Hidden Treasure in the Lovely Tower hallway.

Description: Climb up a surprisingly engaging slab with committing crux moves up higher that can be baffling for some at first.
Location: Fine Nine is located on the main canyon wall, across from the Lovely Tower. It is the right of the two bolted lines on this face (on the left is Split Decision 12d, 3 bolts). It is most directly across from the Lovely Arete.

Description: This route has probably been climbed before us, but we found it on a wet day when I had intended to project Hidden Treasure and Velvet Green. After falling several times on Hidden due to the wet condition, I dropped a TR on the other side of the rock up a nice dry gully in the sun. It ended up being the most fun little 5.8 I have done at Jackson, and I highly recommend it. I set up the TR anchor with natural protection after leading up Hidden Treasure. Good if you have less experienced climbers in your party and you want to work on any of the hard routes on Lovely Tower.   **I'm adding this route because, in my opinion, it deserves consideration for bolting. I'm not a local, but I may consider looking into it.***
Location: Lovely tower, obvious gully on the unbolted side.
Protection: Slings and other stuff for a natural top-rope anchor required; leading any other bolted Lovely tower route required.

Description: A jug haul on the corner just left of Lefty Crack. Could maybe go on gear but would be a bit spicy perhaps. We set up a trad anchor for top-roping in the horizontal crack used for an anchor on Lefty Crack.  Found on a very wet day when the shaded "hard" routes on Lovely weren't good for projecting. The sunny side of the boulder was dry. So named because the party's dog took off and the only person on the ground not belaying couldn't speak English. Poor communication and a lot of charades ensued.
Location: Get on top of the tower by any fun means. Bring up 3-4 mid-size cams and set up a top rope just over the arete in the horizontal crack. Make sure you equalize it well. Start on jugs, and pull the various little roofs and bulges til you reach the top.
Protection: several medium-larger cams for an anchor in the horizontal crack up top. You will need to lead up another route to safely set this up, perhaps Lefty Crack is a good option, since you have cams on you ;-)
FirstAscent: Bryan Shelton (TR  FA to best of my knowledge)

Description: Fun and safe little 5.7 crack that is good for the new trad leader. Very safe stances, although the gear can be a little tricky. From lovely arete, go around to the left and ascend the obvious left-leaning crack at about a 45 degree angle. It's jug hauling near a crack feature; no jamming required.
Protection: Small to large cams, tricams placements can be found. Can set up a TR anchor with several large size cams in the horizontal crack up top, or can walk all the way up to the trees. Better to have a follower, though, to clean your gear. Follower can top out and rap down off of any of the bolted anchors for Hidden Treasure, Lovely Arete, or Velvet Green.

Description: Long pulls on pretty good holds.
Location: To the right of 'Lefty Crack' and to the left of 'Velvet Green'.

Description: A great pockety line with the crux below the last bolt...too bad it's so short.
Location: Route begins just left of Lovely Arete and climbs face using pockets.

Description: Where Lovely Tower and the Wave Wall form the Lovely Hallway, this is the obvious arete. A bouldery start to the first bolt leads to the meat. Fun stuff.
Protection: Four bolts to an anchor. The fourth bolt is most useful as a directional for a toprope, as the anchor is set well back in a funky spot.

Description: One of the cleanest lines around. Great "first" 12 interesting moves protected well where needed.
Location: Only Lovely Tower opposite of Fine Nine

Description: Start a few feet to the right of the first bolt. Climb up using decent pockets until you reach a blank section. Rest up, grab the jug, throw big and try to finish.
Location: The route directly to the right of Lost Innocence.

Description: Climb up the zig-zagging crack. The start is pretty cruiser on good holds until the second bolt. From here do your best to figure out how to make it to the top!
Location: The obvious zig-zagging crack. Located to the left of Cosmic Banditos.

Description: This is a tough one that only gets harder.
Location: Directly right of Lovin' The Rain

Description: Start on the arete from the ground down left then pull on to the face at the first bolt.
The crux is the first moves up to the first bolt. A fall here is quite dangerous if you swing off to the left. Easily break ankle here. (stick clip useful.)
Location: Far left of face of spleef peak opposite the falls
FirstAscent: Jim Thurmund and Mark Newman in 1987

Description: Hardest bolted line on the face, but a fun route that involves some interesting climbing and will have you reaching deep into your bag of tricks.
Location: Between Master Marley and Rattler

Description: Crux that works up a crack system involving some interesting and fun footwork right at the first bolt.
Location: This is the fourth bolted route from right to left on Spleef's main face.

Description: water grooves to knobs and jugs
Location: 12 ft. left of Blue Smoke

Description: water gooves,flakes
Location: Start at Garden Route and go left

Description: Its the high angle slab with a thin start up to good knobs and iron flakes.
Location: The route farthest to the right on Spleef's main face.

Description: Start on impossibly slick feet with small crimps for hands, move up to first bolt. Past this the route is 5.7/5.8 or easier.     If you stick clip the first bolt and pull up, it would be 5.7 A0 and a great route for beginners!
Location: First route around the right corner from the main (South) face of Spleef. To the right of it are two steep 12c's.
Protection: 3 bolts, 2 bolt anchor. Probably want to stick clip if this is near your limit, crux is right off the ground over an uneven boulder.

Description: Another pocket puller. Don’t worry, there are holds somewhere in the moss!
Location: Located between “Storm Watch” and “Songs from the Wood”.

Description: Pull on some small pockets to the top.
Location: The line furthest to the right on the wall to the right of Darden route.

Description: Start in the obviously chalked up inner corner. Follow the thin crack in the boulder up and to the left. Top out    This guy is a little dirty, so bring a brush.
Location: Smaller slightly overhung boulder on the back side of the Spleef Peak Area. Go down and right around the corner from the slabby routes on the large boulder.

Description: Moderate climbing leads to a distinct crux, with a delicate slab to finish the route off.
Location: On the wall to the left of the wall with 'Cro-Magnon Warrior'. The route starts on the right side in the deep red part of the wall. This is the only route on this wall.

Description: Lieback the crack to the good face holds on the right.  Top out straight up.
Location: It's the 3rd "door" dihedral corner.
Protection: Standard rack. Originally went mixed. The lone, manky bolt is now gone.

Description: Arching wide crack just right of L.A. Woman.  Might be full of muck.
Location: Just right of L.A. Woman, and left of Little Johnny Jewel

Description: A few tough, thin reaches down low leads to excellent, thoughtful climbing above on positive flakes.
Location: At the far left, climber's left, end of The Doors wall, this route climbs the vertical wall to climber's right of the arching wide crack, Ladie's Choice.

Description: This ones hard the whole way!
Location: To the right of 'Little Johnny Jewel' and to the left of 'Cro-Magnon Warrior'.

Description: Very obvious line in the middle of the wall.  Follow a seam using power liebacking.  The 1st sport route at the falls.  Mega classic.
Location: Beautiful seam in the middle of the wall.
FirstAscent: Eric Ulner, Tim Toula & Jim Thurmond 1986

Description: Wow this one is thin, so you better be on your crimp game! Begin by negotiating your way through thin holds, until they get slightly better. At the last bolt you'll run into what looks like a blank section covered in moss. Keep your eyes out for the mono, it's key to get to the anchors.
Location: Located directly to the right of 'Cro-Magnon Warrior', and to the left of 'No Brains'.

Description: Climb up the pebbly pocketed face. Holds are pretty painful!
Location: Climb the face to the right of 'Digital Direct' and to the left of 'Amoeba Brains'.

Description: Diffucult bouldery start leads to more moderate climbing up the arete.  After 3rd bolt exit arete to right and finish on slab top-out.
Location: The prominent arete directly across from Spleef Peak

Description: Cool looking lieback.
Location: The 2nd "door" dihedral.

Description: This is the possible looking, extremely hard, bolted arete seam
Location: Directly left of Snap Dragon

Description: Climb up the rainbow colored slab until you get the head wall. Take a breath before you break into an extremely difficult boulder problem with a one hand dyno to a sloper. It doesn’t end there, make sure you stay on your toes till you’re clipping the chains at the top.
Location: Found on the slab directly to the right of the “Wizards Sleeve” project.

Description: A beautiful sweeping dihedral crack on the dark bands of rock typical of the first Doors wall headed towards the N. Falls.   Cruiser with an exciting roof finish to the anchors!   If you see this is dry then climb it.
Location: First Dihedral encountered along the Doors area while headed towards the N. Falls from the dog walk.
Protection: small nuts to mid size cams

Description: A fun route when it isnt wet or mossy.
Location: Between morning beers and "the twist"   Its is marked by the red 'stain' on the wall.

Description: Begins as a jug haul to the high first bolt. Survive some thin slab to reach the chicken heads and a good ledge at the anchor.
Location: Two routes to the right of the prominent thin crack dihedral, Morning Beers, this route is next to the obvious black streak of The Stain.

Description: Climb the shorter, dark colored face.
Location: First sport route right of The Twist

Description: Get out your dancing shoes for this trickster.  Good fun.
Location: Just left of Beastie.  Goes through an offwidth at the top.

Description: Climb the off width that is protected by bolts. Not as easy as it looks
Location: Directly right of Fancy Feet

Description: Climb the face that bulges
Location: Directly left of Cyber Sex. It is easy to find since Cyber Sex has large "eye bolts" that protect it.

Description: This is the route close to the trail that is protected by "eye bolts". Climb through good holds and save some juice for the end.
Location: Directly next to the trail. Look for the "eye bolts"

Description: Step up the mossy slab to reach the first bolt. Pull the bluge and find a good stance to clip the 2nd bolt. High step and friction your way to the top.
Location: Route is on the Wave Wall ~100ft past Fine Nine, just right of Lithuanian Chimney. Ascends the rounded, bulging arete.

Description: Very precarious climbing through shallow pockets.
Location: Directly left of bug meat

Description: Weird start. bulgy. would be a better route if it wasn't so dirty.
Location: 3 or 4 routes left down from the corner of the rope entry
Protection: 3-4 bolts (I forget) plus anchors at the top

Description: This is the second bolted line left of the corner from the hand line. A very weird start leads up to a bulge. Pulling the bulge ends up easier than it looks, working the slopers above is not.
Good, short sport route
Location: This route is on the opposing wall to the left of the hand line by the main waterfall/pool

Description: This is the spot where the fixed line used to be. It has since been bolted as a sport route. A great way to get out of the canyon at the end of the day.
Location: This is the last route on the left side of the waterfall wall. Located on the right side of the leftmost corner.

Description: Crux is the first move. Fun climb but way too short.
Location: First route left of the North Falls. Waterfall will be on your right.

Description: Hydra is a nice short moderately bouldery line with three bolts, that goes up and moves slightly diagonally right.
Location: Just to the right of the pool, by the first waterfall. The bolt line trends up and slightly right.
Protection: 3 Quick-draws plus another two for the anchors.

Description: Third route to the right of the pool, with a bulge at the top.  First bolt is a good 15 feet off of the ground.
Bouldery start leads to 5.10ish climbing above
Location: Third and final (leftmost) route in the Leprosy Cave (see Brown Recluse for directions to the cave)

Description: A super fun sport route up the flaring gully.  Crux comes at 2/3 height and it really makes you stand and deliver!
Location: Middle route in Leprosy Cave (see Brown Recluse for directions to the cave) apx 10 feet southeast/down the cliff from Brown Recluse

Description: Another Frizzell technical masterpiece.  Finishes in between two high water grooves
Location: From the main pool/hand line walking southwest down the cliff line you will see the Leprosy cave (deep but only apx 4 ft high at it's tallest) will be up and right after about 100 yards.  Brown Recluse is the first sport route you will see.

Description: Climb the dihedral crack next to the low roof.
Location: 25 feet left of Suspended Animation
Protection: Small and mid-sized cams and nuts    Share anchor with Spring Animation
FirstAscent: FA- Eric Ulner 1985 Around 1992, Jim Thurmond bouldered down it after bouldering Wizard's Hat for a warm-up.

Description: Initially lead on 3 bolts, rated 5.11c. 2 bolts added + anchor shared with Deception.
Location: Between Deception (overhang crack/dihedral) and Suspended Animation

Description: Start climbing below and to the right of the crack in the middle of the wall.
Location: About 75 feet left of Settled Controversy.
Protection: 2 draws, mid size cams and mid size nuts + anchor

Description: Be patient with this one, it will be slow going on not so confidence inspiring holds. Slowly pull your way up a water groove
Location: First sport route to the right of Suspended Animation

Description: The route that starts above a bolder near a fallen tree
Location: 20ish feet to the left of Settled Controversy

Description: Ascend the lieback flake with the horn on top.  Top out on right.
Location: Directly behind a VW bug sized rock.
Protection: Small nuts, mid-sized cam, 2 draws + anchor

Description: This project is the face climb between the two cracks
Location: First sport route to the right of Settled Controversy
FirstAscent: Equipped by Phillip Carrier FA Jared Smith 2018

Description: Crack in the back of an overhanging symmetrical dihedral.  Looks like a wizard's hat.
Location: First route on wizard wall.  40 feet before reaching Settled Controversy.  Big dihedral resembling its namesake.

Description: The route between Wizards Hat and Eat Dirt. This one will need some cleaning before a send attempt
Location: Left of the leaning boulder near Wizards Hat

Description: Thought provoking start. Move up and a little right on the Face.
Location: two sport routes left of Mud Pie. Last sport route before the leaning block.

Description: Climb the dark red face using everything you can find
Location: This route lies between a big leaning boulder and the dihedral of Eat Dirt

Description: This widish crack flares somewhat and is usually fairly dirty and rarely done.  It's really not as bad as that description sounds though!
Location: This route is on the way to the Gallery down from the main pool/hand line by maybe 80 yards.
Protection: Medium to large sized gear - you can use the anchor of Mud Pie right next door to rap and clean.

Description: Good slabby/vertical sport route worth doing as you work down to the Gallery.  This route is also immediately to the right of the wide crack that is the route Eat Dirt.
Location: Down the wall from the hand line by the main fall/pool on the way to the Gallery by maybe 80 yards.

Description: Climb the face to the left of the Arete.
Location: First bolted route to the left of Slug Man. Look for the noticibke horizontal break in the wall.

Description: This is the face/slab route on the left.  Pull a move, stand on ledge x3
Location: This is the first route you come to.  If standing, facing the Manky Alcove it is the left most route.

Description: Fingery, vertical sport route that is short and sweet
Location: Inside the Manky Alcove the left wall - this is the left of the two routes

Description: It is recommended to stick clip the first bolt. Climb up and through a left leaning edge feature.
Location: On the left side on Manky Cove directly to the right of Hungry Wolf

Description: Stem up the back of the alcove until your legs can't stretch anymore and switch to the left side to lie back the crack to the anchors.  Fun route but too short.
Location: This is in the back of the Manky Alcove and the top is often wet.

Description: This is a fun slabby route in the Manky Alcove.  A bit of balance is helpful.
Location: On the right side of the Manky Alcove.  Western most route.

Description: Choss but unique for jackson
Location: Hike south (away from dog walk access) and find the large overhanging boulder on the right side of the trail just beyond manky aclove. Begins with the short arete and follows thru the overhang.

Description: Start on the detached boulder to the right then traverse left on slopers to gain the roof. Power through the roof using jugs and heel hooks, then mantle and clip the chains
Location: Other side of the large boulder from Tree Hugger

Description: Climb the 4 bolt route
Location: Other side of the large boulder from Needs A Name

Description: Climb this cliff line route that is broken up into 2 separate tiers.
Location: The lone cliff line route between the boulder that has Tree Hugger and the boulder that has Dolphin Friendly

Description: Unknown
Location: First rt on the left as you enter the hallway

Description: Face climb on nice holds. Pull the roof
Location: 2nd rt on the left as you enter the hallway

Description: Pull pockets up left to the blunt arete. Pinch and roll right to sidepulls then deadpoint left to gain the shelf. Hand traverse right then pull the roof.Move up left to the anchors. It's still dirty but super fun! Feel free to brush a little  on the way down from your flash.
Crux going from 1 to 2. Nice holds to a trickly finish.
Location: first route on the left side of the Rainy Day wall
FirstAscent: Leif Faber, Matt Queen, Jeff Frizzell

Description: A short but decent crack that can be protected strictly by nuts.  It goes up and right.
Location: First route inside the Rainy Day Roof.  Left most route.
Protection: Small-medium sized gear + can share anchor from neighboring sport route

Description: 5.10 a/b Its the first sport route, just right of "Spinkles". 3 QD + anchor. From "Vertical Heartland" 3rd edition by Eric Ulner
Location: see above

Description: Pull up onto the route using good jugs until about the second bolt, where the route transitions into crimps. The crux is moving out right and to clip the anchors. After a few falls, I found it best to clip whlie right hand is on the lower right undercling with high feet, instead of trying to use the higher hold on the left.
Location: second route on wall

Description: no visible anchors
Location: 3rd route from left

Description: Basically a highball boulder problem, but a really fun boulder problem. Lots of good holds with big reaches in between. Pull hard and fast and you're gonna have a good time.
Location: Zapped is the fourth bolted line from the left underneath the roof (not counting "Sweet Leaf"). It is immediately to the right of the corner trad climb "End of the Cluster."

Description: Utilize fingerlocks and good face holds; its more fun than it looks from the ground.
Location: End of the Cluster is the obvious clean corner just outside the right edge of the roof. It is immediately to the right of Zapped, and to the left of Fat and Sassy. It could theoretically be toproped off either anchor, with some swing potential.

Description: Hop up to ledge to for the first bolt. Then either follow the leftward leaning crack with some underclings or move slightly left and use a combination of the face the crack.
Location: 5 feet right of End of the Cluster, just out from underneath the Rainy Day Roof

Description: A liitle bit techy at the crux from 2 to 3. A bit pumpy to finish.     The grade is a guess please add your opinion
Location: Just right of Fat and Sassy 5.9, the second bolted route right of the obvious corner "End of the Cluster."
Protection: 4 bolts, anchor is 2 Metolious rap bolts in the roof (a little hard to see from the ground)

Description: This is the only route of Rainy Day Roof that goes all the way to the top.
Location: Directly to the right of Silver Lining

Description: Low crux passing the first bolt. Relentless to tricky finish.
Location: Second route to the right of Silver Lining.

Description: Short and bouldery.  May be easier?
Location: About 150 feet past Rainy Day Roof, across from a pointing boulder on the right.  Left route on the overhanging wall.

Description: Power through the low section until you get to the last bolt. Be ready to pull on some heinous crimps for the finish!
Location: The route directly to the right of Industry.

Description: Start with a little bit of technical climbing till you get to the second bolt. Proceed on overhanging jugs till you get to the lard flake. Use a combination of bad smears and good handholds to get to the roof crack.
Location: Located in the corner to the right of Industry.

Description: A big underclung feature helps identify this route. It is big and long. Have fun
Location: First sport route beyond the fallen boulders to the right of Automatic Damnation.

Description: Climb the zig zagging crack while protecting when necessary.
Location: The crach located within the dark stain

Description: Climb the slight arete feature until the horizontal break. Cut left and continue up to the anchor.
Location: Located on the face just right of Hearty Boys Crack

Description: Begin on Aggro-Sheen, but at the horizontal break, continue straight up.
Location: Begin on Aggro-Sheen.

Description: Begin on top of the boulder and carefully climb up the face using small holds.
Location: To the right of Aggro-Sheen located behind a large boulder

Description: Climb the rightward leaning crack protecting when necessary working towards the bolts to reach the anchor.
Location: Located behind a large to boulder to the right of Watch Dog. There should still be a tree fallen on the cliff face.
Protection: 2 bolts + small to mid sized gear to the anchor

Description: Follow the bolts as you climb through a bulge to eventually gain purchase on a slab. continue to the anchor from here.
Location: To the right of The DIggler

Description: Climb the face to work your way through a bulge, continue through a slab to reach the top. Large Eye Bolts mark this route.
Location: To the right of Unknown

Description: Climb up a steep face and upon reaching the 5th bolt, cut left to work towards the anchor. (Obsessive Climbing Disorder)
Location: To the right of Iniquity

Description: Begin on OCD and upon reaching the 5th bolt, continue straight up to the anchor. Route is often wet, if dry, you will not be disappointed.
Location: Shares the same start as OCD

Description: Splitter hand to off-fist crack leads to some fun offwidth twists, leads to some face climbing.  A couple rest ledges thrown in makes this climb a blast and a half, if you've got guts.
Location: On the main wall, around the corner and left of Detox Mountain, almost all the way to the 2nd class, It's the right-leaning splitter.
Protection: Lead on big stuff or toprope from the large cedar tree.  The last few moves are up unprotectable face.

Description: The large crack 20 feet right of Devil's Lake Dreams.
Location: On the main wall, left around the corner from Detox Mountain.

Description: Short line that does not receive great reviews
Location: At the base of the trail that leads to the top

Description: Climbs up on the short overhanging face.
Location: First route you come to.  Turn around corner and see steep face with 4 bolts.

Description: Straight up then move left into a cool span move. Gain the break then move slightly up and right to pull the overlap on edges. Finish up and left.
Location: On the main cliff Left of Elders

Description: Cocktail Generation with Elders finish
Location: Start on Cocktail Generation

Description: Climb Elders to the last bolt then traverse left to finish on Cocktail Generation.Maybe consider this link up if you've done all the other routes on the wall, or if you get to the last bolt on Elders feeling a little soft.
Location: Begin on Elders of the Tribe, the center route on the Detox wall with a left-facing flake about a third the way up. Finishes on top-left arete of wall.

Description: A gnarly climb and a super fun one to boot.  Standard J Falls sandstone pockets and crimps.
Location: It starts 15 feet right of the arete on the main wall facing Pricker Peak.  Trend left after the second bolt.

Description: A total classic in the Jackson Falls area and the midwest for that matter.  A tendon friendly pocket pulling extravaganza.
Location: Start in the base of the main wall facing Pricker Peak.  Go up the ceter draw line.

Description: Start low by Detox and move up line of bolts to the right.  Gets interesting after the layback crack.
Location: Route just right of Detox Mountain.
