Description: The rightmost route on the Detox wall, start as for The Farmer but continue up the ramp for another 10 feet to a lieback crack. Continue up the crack and finish on edges.
This is the cool looking Arete climb to the right of Detox Mountain’s main routes. It does not receive enough traffic
Location: The Arete to the right of The Carpenter

Description: Start on big easy stuff, up to first bolt.  Some awkward, hard face climbing, with high steps and thin holds to pull hard on, and scary slopers for the final pull to the top.
Location: Around the left corner from the main face, on the west face of Pricker Peak; the left most route.

Description: Looks easier then it is. Save some strength for the top
Location: First sport route left of Lucky Charms

Description: Crux is at the third bolt. Kinda of run out past it but it's pretty easy climbing.
Location: Layback feature to the left of Raisin Bran

Description: Shared anchor with Lucky Charms
Location: 12 feet left of Cheerio Bowl corner.

Description: Climb through the first three bolts (crux) to the prow like feature.  Then take a good rest and head left to the face, up the arete and then cut right and up to the finish.  A pumpy finish to the chains.
Location: On the furthest left side of Pricker Peak.

Description: A way cool line up the middle of Pricker Peak.  Follow the line to the bulge.  Pull that, then finish up.
Location: The middle of the face to the right of Cheerio Bowl.

Description: A nice line, bit more powerful than its neighbor Captain Crunch.
Location: Hidden Peaks (Pricker Peak)   directly right of "Captain Crunch" 5.11a

Description: Big holds on slightly overhung wall. Good route to get your final Red Point warm up pump on.
Location: On Pricker peak across from Elders. Start just right of Honeynut Girl. Shares anchors with Honeynut Girl

Description: Beginning above a two foot boulder, climb through an obvious lieback up and left
Location: 10 feet left of Zoom To Doom

Description: Two moves of fragile rock lead to pockets in excellent rock. Fight hard direct or come in from the left with style. Three sections of interesting climbing with slight breaks in between. You may find it pumpy for the angle.
Location: West side of the Monument around the corner and down the hill from Stubborn Swede

Description: One of the best routes of the grade at Jackson
Location: The leftmost (of four) route on The Monument's south side.  Next to the Unclaimed 5.9.

Description: Another fine route among the many quality lines of the Hidden Peaks area. Climb the middle of the face (left of Lothlorien and the tall tree close to the face). A tall first bolt gives you an idea of the spacing.
Location: Left of the tall tree growing near the middle of the face.
Protection: 4 well spaced bolts with a healthy runount on easier terrain to bolted anchors. For those wanting a little more security, there are some horizontal cracks between the upper bolts and the anchors that take small to mid-sized cams.

Description: First 20 feet are vertical to a slight balancey crux then the angle easies slightly along with the difficulty.
Location: Lothlorien is located on The Monument in between the arete of Naked Blade and the Unclaimed 5.9
Protection: 4 bolts, plus a small/medium cam or two

Description: A wicked fun mixed route on the arete of the Monument.  Head up the arete to a really good rest on a ledge, a brown tricam has a bomber placement here.  Then sport up to the finish.
Location: As facing the Monument from Pricker Peak it is on the striking arete on the right side.
Protection: small to medium gear and a brown tri-cam, then 3 bolts or so to the top.

Description: This is a mixed line that has 5 bolts to help protect the face. You’ll need some gear for the dihedral seam at the top.
Location: Around the corner from Naked Blade

Description: Great holds lead to a tricky crux.
Location: This route is located on the stand alone tower feature known as Boner’s Boulder. It’s the only developed route on this feature.

Description: Climb up the left side of the nose
Location: Left of the nose

Description: Climb up the right side of the nose
Location: Right side of the nose

Description: Adventurous meandering route with all kinds of climbing moves, roof crack, offwidth, squeeze, face, anchor on tree.  Extend to prevent rope drag.
Location: Overhanging start at corner of the basement, left to Coup de Tat, Rap off from tree

Description: Climb up the manky overhang using a variety of sandy pinches. Very thuggy!
Location: The route to the left of Coup.

Description: Start by climbing up Misery, but link into Obed Simulater B. instead of clipping the chains.
Location: Start on Misery, then cut right into Obed Simulater B.

Description: Link "Misery" into "Coup de'etat"
Start on Coup, but continue left through the roof.
Location: Start on Coup, but cut left at the roof.

Description: V6/7 to easier climbing above
Location: right side of overhang

Description: Begin on Coup d'etat for the first few bolts then traverse left to finish on Misery.
Location: On the right side of the cave.

Description: Enter a non typical sport route for the canyon.  Adventure up the wide crack feature using more than your average sport climbing technique.  An ode to good fun on good rock for those who grew up/fell in love with climbing in Illinois and will never forget their roots.
Location: This is the large crack/gulley feature that divides the face to the right of the overhung basement wall.

Description: Climb up an easy section to get to the business. Climb up and over a couple of bulges with good clipping stances, and push through the crux above the final bolt.  Fun, and very well protected!
Location: This is the first route on Belleville Wall.  Walk 80 feet past The Basement and look to your left.  This is the overhanging route going up the wall just past the corner.

Description: The route at the entrance to the corridor.
Location: The route across the hallway, on the cliff line, to the left of I Be Lichen It

Description: It’s the route down the corridor from Lindapalooza on the left side of the cliffline
Location: Refer to description

Description: There is a water dike in the middle of this route.  Pull slopers, pinches, side pulls, pockets, and under-clings.  Boulder to gain the lower bulge, then enter the gully, use your shoulders.  At the top of the gully, come out on the face and pick the pockets on the first roof up to the giant fin.
Location: On the SW corner, the last route before rounding the corner and continuing on the main trail.  Just Southeast of Town Square.

Description: Sustained overhanging route.  Tough finish to the anchors.
Location: As you first approach the Town Square from The Basement, this route will be in front of you. It's the overhanging route on the north side. From "Vertical Heartland" 3rd edition by Eric Ulner

Description: Bulge between 2nd and 3rd clips is the crux.  Pinches, heuco's and jugs.  A little overhanging for 1/2 of route, transitions to slab.
Location: It's 50 feet right of "I Be Lichen It", and on the outer west side of the Town Square. From "Vertical Heartland" 3rd edition by Eric Ulner
FirstAscent: Jim Schneider, Margie Belt, Mike Braun, 1998

Description: Good feet, a few bulges to get over.  Pinches, heucos and jugs.  Bolts nicely spaced.
Location: It's about 12 feet right of "Monkey Shower". From "Vertical Heartland" 3rd edition by Eric Ulner.

Description: Good pockets and jugs to clip from.  A few bulges with good feet.  Slab after last hanger to anchors.  Move right for good feet and a hand jam.
Location: It starts about 6 feet right of "Katie Did". From "Vertical Heartland" 3rd edition by Eric Ulner.

Description: Boulder up to the 2nd bolt.  Wrestle your way around the fin and fight to the anchors. Unique movement for the Falls!  Grade is a guess, please add your opinion. First TR ascent: Jeff Frizzell
Location: Starts in the overhang right of Spank You Very Much.  Rap off Metolius Rap anchors

Description: Fun and juggy laybacking and stemming with good gear. Crux is probably 1/3 the way up.
Location: Left leaning feature to the left of Bubbling Crude. Used the anchors on "Possum Grits", two routes to the right, to descend after cleaning the top rope anchor.
Protection: Large gear from 1" to 4", two size 3 C4s would be helpful, and a #4 C4 is nice for the first piece. I used the small tree at the top and a #2 C4 in the crack below it to make a top rope anchor. Bring some longs slings or cordelette to make this easier.

Description: Engaging climbing throughout, chains are slightly to the right of the rest of the climb. Crux is probably clipping the chains, I traversed over and clipped while still below the bulge, but it also looks like you could pull over and then traverse to the anchors, although that also seems a little strange.
Location: Bolted line to the left of "Possum Grits" 5.9, and just to the right of the 5.8 crack feature "Double Knot Spy."

Description: Start on the bulgy start. Good rest just by the first bolt, nice safe start. The trick is finding the underclings throughout. Really good 5.9 on bomber sandstone. Good jugs at the top. Various beta to get from the last bolt to the anchor. Pick your adventure!
Location: Just left and including the arete before the small ledge that leads to Whee Doggies
FirstAscent: Ed English, Jim Schneider, Granny Clampett, 1998

Description: Lieback the juggy lip on the left side of this crack, don't forget to look for good feet on the left for rests. Sustained and continuous, a fun natural feature to climb.
Location: The obvious crack feature to the left of "Whee Doggies!" 5.8, and just to the right of "Possum Grits" 5.9.
Protection: Toprope off the Whee Dogies! anchor (don't fall, or wide piece as a directional), or lead with extremely wide gear.

Description: A pockety line starting from up on the ledge. This area is rarely trafficked but the holds stay nice and clean. Good route for the young leader. Also, a nice ledge up top to teach cleaning anchors. It's just near a 5.9 and past several other 5.9s. A very good beginner area.     The hardest moves are near the bottom, then move up and left for jugs.
Location: Get up on the ledge, it's the obvious bolted pocket line on the left.

Description: Good holds lead to a big move off of undercling jugs. Connect the huecos with what few feet options you have, and move through one more section to gain the ledge/rest. Easier climbing leads you to the anchors.Note: Height dependent moves will make this much harder for anyone under 5’7.
Location: Leftmost line on the Space Cowboy wall. Scramble up the platform to begin.

Description: Variation on "Space Cowboy", continue left to the separate anchor. 8 QD + anchor. From "Vertical Heartland" 3rd edition by Eric Ulner

About 30 feet past the S.S. Minnow, it starts just right of the big, overhung dihedral. Cross the crack after the second clip and face climb through the bulge to the top. 8 QD + anchor. From "Vertical Heartland" 3rd edition by Eric Ulner

RouteName: You Can't Take the Sky From Me
Description: In a battle between claustrophobia and acres of air below you, this climb forces you to fight for any shred of sky you can.  20ft of upside-down, offwidth hell leads to an mild finger traverse, and then 40ft of your standard chimney (lil' dirty, lil' runnout, lil' fun).
Location: It's the bigtime crack intertwined with Space Cowboy.
Protection: Single rack of mid-big cams.  A #5 protects the crux (or lets you aid out of the roof section). The chimney is well protected via pockets deep in the back.

Description: Start Left of a big tree on easy terrain, follow fun mega-jugs along a traverse for 3 or 4 bolts, then up the face to the shiny new chain anchor. Good times! Crux is probably somewhere on the face. Listed as 10b in the Daneshyar guide, but its probably easier than that. Significantly easier than three hour tour.
Location: Skipper is currently the only route on the face opposite the side with Three Hour Tour/Swabbe/Salty Dog. Also possible to access the anchor from any of the other routes on the SS Minnow.
Protection: 7 bolts, and a nice tree to lean on by the second bolt. 2 bolt anchor. There isn't really a great way to make the traverse at the beginning of this super toprope friendly.

Description: North side of block. Start on boulders next to "Swabbe" and climb left toward the prow and arching toward the summit. The last (fifth) bolt you see on the main face is the last bolt on the route, but the terrain above is really easy. After clipping this bolt the route moves left and finishes up the left (low angle and highly featured) side of the headwall.
Location: As you approach the SS Minnow from the Dog Walk, this will be the leftmost route on the first side of the Minnow you see, although the lichen somewhat camouflages the route. It starts right next to "Swabbe" 11a and traverses out left to the arete and then up to the anchors.

Description: Continuous technical climbing, close to vertical but not overhanging. Different in character than a lot of Jackson routes.
Location: Obvious route splitting the main face of the SS Minnow. Starts on some boulders, just to the right of "Three Hour Tour." Swabbe is identified by a small overhang 2/3rds of the way up the route.
FirstAscent: TR David Kessler, FFA Jeff Frizzell

Description: A fairly easy 10a climb for the area, definitely recommended for people new to the grade. Generally good holds on good rock.
Location: Rightmost route on the main face of SS Minnow. Starts above a small boulder, behind a big fallen tree.

Description: Brutish pull to start. Stick clip if you must. Angle left to the anchors. Safe with a precarious feel. Good rock/holds
Location: just left of Mad Hatter

Description: Left angling groove then back right to the anchors
Location: Atop the mini hallway just past the Minnow

Description: This route is not in the newest Jackson guidebook. Staying left of the decaying tree trunk, follow bolts through what looks to be bleak sections and work your way to the anchor.
Location: First sport route to the right of Mad Hatter

Description: Crux shortly after 2nd bolt.    Try to avoid the temptation of the iron flakes to the left midway up!
Location: Slabby route to the left of Ever Ready Betty. Starts near a right-leaning crack.

Description: Pinches, slopers, pockets, dimples, deadpoints, smears, side pulls, Improbable finish. It aint over til its over.   Sweet!
Location: First route left of Ever Ready Betty

Description: More to it than meets the eye. Safe, mental, and entertaining. Be strong grasshopper.
Location: Just left of Mirror man

Description: Right of "Ever Ready Betty"    Low Crux. 10ish climbing to an upper mini-crux and the anchors. Well bolted.
A black water runnel to the left of Lasso the Vulture.  Strat with an awkward mantel to 5.9 slabby open book goodmness.
Location: A little off trail and to the left of Lasso

Description: Also known as Cowgirls in The Sand. Start on Groovy Marcia move right and follow the buttress left of Disco Fever.
Location: The Ranch

Description: Starts out slaby with long reaches to vertical terrain with few bad options for holds. Power through the defined crux about half way, but keep your cool for the next few bolts, it's very possible to fall after the crux.
Location: Two routes to the right of Groovy Marcia.
Protection: 7 draws for the climb + 2 for the anchor.

Description: Difficult moves off pockets crux is mid way up.
Location: Directly right of Disco Fever

Description: This is definately one of my favorite route in the Falls.  A lowdown crux (between first and third bolts) follws to easier climbing up and to the left of the blank roof.  Follow the chimney (would you believe it) to the anchors.
Location: Walk along the trail in the Ranch ast the S.S. Minnow until the wall is on your left.  It begins a little bit right of the big blank roof.

Description: A decievingly easy start leads to hard face climbing.
Location: Further down from Lasso, but not quite to Kill Bill, it is a detatched pillar up a hill and into an alcove.

Description: Techy little right leaning corner (sweet) to a bulge. I may have screwed the bolting up a little at the buldge. My applogies
Location: Between Condor and Kill Bill

Description: Ease up and the right under the two tiers then straight up.
Location: between Thrill Jill and Kill Bill

Description: A pretty cool slab up the middle of the face.  The last climb on this side of the canyon.
Location: The furthest left route in the canyon (facing South).  Past condor.

Description: Power slab to better holds through the bulge
Location: Just right of KILL BILL

Description: Low bouldery crux with consistent climbing through the rest of the top section.
Location: Climb is located further down from Kill Bill and climbs out the left of a bouldery roof.

Description: Climb the crack
Location: 8 feet right of Southern Inquisition
Protection: Trad Gear, not sure if an anchor exists

Description: Bigin by using the tree. Let guilt be your guide
Location: left most route on the slab

Description: Maroon water groove
Location: Just right of Porch Vista

Description: Shares first bolt with Road Runner
FirstAscent: Jeff Frizzell Chris Newsham, Steve Ranney

Description: Shares first bolt with Catus Wren and anchor set with Cara Cara
FirstAscent: Jeff Frizzell Chris Newsham, Steve Ranney

Description: Just right of Road Runner. Mildly overhanging start. Hard to see first bolt. Shares anchors with Road Runner
Mildly over hanging on very good stone. Fun moves
Location: Just left of Cross Dressers

Description: Short & Sweet
Location: Left of Darwin's Theory

Description: 1 move wonder
Location: Right of Cowboys & Cross Dressers

Description: Crux passing the first bolt. Safe but mildly run out to the Anchors. Great stone in a beautiful red streak.
Location: Up hill and right of Darwin's Theory

Description: Right leaning semi tube with pockets
Location: rap

Description: angles left hidden hold left
Location: Rap

Description: just right of Buckaroo
Location: rap

Description: Just right of Barbed Wire
Location: rap

Description: Just right of Javelina
Location: rap

Description: Just right of High Lonesome; Just left of the waterfall.
Start same as Poncho Via, Hand traverse to the firrst bolt on Three Amigos,pull onto the face and keep moving left past bolt 2, up left to 3, then straight up to the anchors.
25 feet right of the waterfall
FirstAscent: Jeff Frizzell, Thomas Diehl, Stephen Wilmas

Description: Right most route on the wall
Pull through a balancy start then crimp your way p to three large pockets. Gather your energy, put on your best sending suit, and burst out right to an obvious flake.
Location: The first route on the main Grotto face. On your left as you enter the Grotto from La Hacienda.

Description: A tough lock-off right off the ground leads to great climbing above. Keep your guard up until the last!
Location: 20' left of Hardwood Haberdasher

Description: Climb and powerful face on good pockets up to overhanging iron-flake jugs. Finish with a balancy mantle, guaranteed to keep you on your toes!
Location: In the center of the main Grotto wall just to the right of an obvious crack/ramp system

Description: Great pockets lead to some fun iron flakes. Waltz your feet up high and undercling the tails for the finish.
Location: On the right side of the main Grotto wall, just to the right of a large left-leaning crack

Description: Follow the right side of the arete on good pockets and luxurious underclings
Location: The left route on the main face of Top Hat Tower, as you approach the grotto from La Haceinda this face is on your right.

Description: Use large pockets to undercling your way to a pair of tricky moves to bring yourself to the anchors. Just like the Owl-Cat of legend this will keep you on your toes until the end!
Location: The middle route on the main face of Top Hat Tower, as you approach the grotto from La Haceinda this face is on your right.

Description: Start a little left and work a move using some positive, yet hidden holds. Pull the tricky move, and then cruise easier territory to gain the anchors.
Location: The right route on the main face of Top Hat Tower, as you approach the grotto from La Haceinda this face is on your right.

Description: Fun climbing on the roof on the back side of Top Hat Tower. A short face leads to a beefy roof with big moves on decent holds. Fight the pump and let your feet cut for a great finish!
Location: Back side of Top Hat Tower around the corner from Owl Cat and Krakendile

Description: To the right of Top Hat and Cane. Follow the short face to the burly roof moves. V5/ 12c.
Hard to read finish
Location: Mass Production wall. It's about 30 feet left of "Slave Labor", "Carpal Tunnel" and "Workshop".
FirstAscent: Mike Balossi, Darrell Sauer, Jeff Stockton 2002

Description: Starts at the same point as "Slave Labor" and "Carpal Tunnel". Stay with the left line.
Location: Mass Production wall. 20 feet left of "Assembly Line".

Description: Starts at the same point as "Slave Labor" and "Workshop". Take the middle line after the 2nd clip.
Location: Mass Production wall. 20 feet left of "Assembly Line".

Description: Starts at the same point as "Carpal Tunnel" and "Workshop". Veer right after first clip.
Location: Mass Production wall. 20 feet left of "Assembly Line".

Description: Two difficult, technical cruxes on razor crimps separated by a section of more moderate climbing. Not for those afraid of a little blood.
Location: From "Candy Corner" (5.7), go left to the Mass Production Wall, and then 15 feet left again.

Description: Seemingly impossible start leading up to some unique climbing on typical Jackson slab holds. Some may consider hard for the grade.
Location: the first climb on the wall to the left of the belay ledge, left of team honda

Description: Begin on the platform, climb up the beautiful Black and Tan face. Keep your eye out for the drilled mono.
Location: Left most line on the Black and Tan wall. To the left of Last Gasp of Hope.
Protection: 6 bolts. Stick clip the first bolt!

Description: Climb up the left angling crack until I️t stops. Proceed to climb up the face.
Location: Shares the same start as Poseur and Hoser.
Protection: 8 bolts. Stick clip the first bolt

Description: This one is a little bit easier than Poseur. Climb up the middle line. Crux is a litttle thuggy and near the middle of the climb.
Location: Middle line between Last Gasp of Hope and Poseur.
Protection: 7 bolts. Stick clip the first bolt.

Description: Begin on the left Angelina crack, but cut right and follow the furthest right bolt line. The crux is between bolt 2 and 3. But it’s not over till you clip the chains.
Start on small holds and move up the overhanging face with large holds and larger moves. Cruise the roof to the chains.
Location: This route is down left and around the arete from fashionably late. The route is the just before the detached ledge.
Protection: 7 bolts, 6 have fixed draws, 2 bolt chain anchor with fixed carabiners.

Description: This ones a little thuggy, with a dynamic move for the crux. You end up linking up with Team Honda near the top.
Location: The route directly to the right of Team Honda.

Description: Climb up the pocketed arete that leads to a committing slab above.
Location: The route directly to the right of “Pinocchio Theory” and to the left of “Fashionably Late”.

Description: Very fun, slightly technical pockets up a vertical face to an over hanging jug finish
Location: Main Wall

Description: Start the route off by pulling on a couple small pockets, and a hard lock off move/drive by. The climbing gets easier, but it’s not over till you clip the anchors.
Location: The rite directly to the right of “Fashionably Late”.

Description: A low sever crux leads to easier terrain above.
Location: The route directly to the left of “Congo Spray”.

Description: Same start as Zambezi. Cut left after the second bolt to climb Congo Spray. The crux is right at the third bolt.
Location: Same start as Zambezi, cut left at the second bolt. Located to the right of Egyptian Conniption and to the left of Float Trip.

Description: Start climbing up the water groove. Do some long pulls on pockets. Interesting crux matching and moving off a not so great hold. Climbing gets easier after crux.
Location: Located on the River wall. To the left of Float Trip and to the right of Egyptian Conniption. Shares the same start as Congo Spray, but heads right at the third bolt.

Description: Start with a moderate boulder problem to get from the ground to the second bolt. The crux sequence is between the 3rd and the 5th bolt.
Location: Located to the left of “The Nile” and to the right of “Zambezi”.

Description: Tough climbing leads to a extremely severe crux. I’ve been told the crux sequence is about v10 alone. Luckily after the crux it’s gets significantly easier on he way to the chains.
Location: The route with a couple perma draws directly to the right of “Float Trip”.

Description: Climb up the left-facing flake until it runs out. Then move right and over the bulge.
Location: This is the route closest to the arete on the left hand side of the wall. It can be found to the left of “Traffic Jam”.

Description: Enjoy your ride up the wall on good positive holds.
Location: Located directely to the right of “Killer Chickens” and to the left of “Spectator Sport”.

Description: Climb up the pocketed face.
Location: This route is directly to the right of “Traffic Jam” and to the left of “Delirius”.

Description: This route climbs up the arete on the right side of the wall, next to the chimney.
Location: This route is directly to the right of “Spectator Sport” and to the left on the wall to the right “Victoria’s Secret”.

Description: This route climbs up the dark streak slab. Probably also pretty dirty!
Location: This route is directly to the right of the route “Delirious” on the other wall, and to the left of the route “Mystical Season”.

Description: Start standing on the boulder to start the juggy traverse. The jugs run out when you pull yourself onto the head wall.
Location: Begins on top of the boulder directly to the left of Balance of Power.

Description: Very tall aesthetic route, with great movement.
Location: The second route to the left of Remove La Ropa.

Description: Start by aiding your way to the first bolt. Once in place, pull a long move to the lip and proceed to pull on sloping holds to a hard dead point move to a jug. Finish on easier terrain afterwords.
Location: To the right of Balance of Power, and to the left of Remove La Rope.

Description: The freed start to the old aid start of EOP. Pull down hard on a slightly crumbly, compression boulder problem at the start into EOP. End at single bolt anchor. A project continues up and right.
A neat boulder problem gets you to a steep roof. Move through the "Jackson Falls Jugs" in the roof to a deadpoint gaining the face and easier climbing to the anchors
Location: On the left side of the section of the main wall that bulges out like some sort of pillar. Just right of Delirious.

Description: An interesting start leads to the first roof. Spend some time to figure out how to get in position to pull the roof. Don’t get comfortable! The climbing only gets harder for every bulge you pull.
Location: The route directly to the right of “Remove La Ropa” and directly to the left of “Key Lime”.

Description: Climb up the lime green streak near the gully.
Location: The route directly to the right of “Jarred’s Route” and to the left of “Dupuy Conqueror”.

Description: Climb up the golden streaked face.
Location: On the left most side of the main wall. Starts to the left of “Circle in the Round”.

Description: Low crux leads to sustained climbing.
Location: Found between the routes “Duppy Conqueror” on the left and “Ooh La La” on the right.

Description: Shares the same start as “Hubba Hubba”, but you break left and follow the red streak at the 4th bolt.
Location: Shares the same start as “Hubba Hubba”, break left at the 4th bolt. Found between “Pool of Reflection” on the right, and “Circle in the Round” on the left.

Description: Fight through the low crux at the first bolt to gain the steep sustained face.
Location: Between “Pool of Reflection” and “Circle in the Round”. Shares the same start as “Ooh La La”.

Description: Start with an interesting vertical crux to a good rest before big moves and sustained climbing through overhanging rock to hero jugs. A 13a variation goes up the arete to the right, bypassing the beginning crux. Listed as the Pipe Dream Project in Vertical Heartland.
Location: On the right side of the overhanging main wall in front of the large spectator boulder

Description: A variation of the route “Pool of Reflection”. Start around the corner to the right, and join in at the 4th bolt.
Location: Starts around the corner to the right of “Pool of Reflection”.

Description: Climb the crack and either end at the anchors or top out through the right gully.
Location: The middle of the wall to the left of Four Bettys Wall.

Description: Pure jackson fun, sloppers and all!
Location: The bolt line in the middle of Four Bettys Face Wall, (the wall to the left of X Block).

Description: This route is tricky! Keep your eyes peeled for hidden holds.
Location: Starts to the right of Four Bettys, and to the left of Three Day Impression.

Description: Interesting face climbing to the right of an arete leads to a nice rest, where you cross to the other side of the arete and tackle several classic Jackson-style bulges.
Great warm up for the harder routes in the area.  A little thin at the start and continuous.
Location: Located just around the left arete of the south face of the X Block.

Description: This route starts on the left main face of the X Block and goes up the arete for 2 bolts. Then head left to finish up XOXO
Location: Left side of X Block

Description: Pumpy.
Location: Leftmost route on the south face of the X Block (10 feet left of X Factor).
12 feet left of Xterminator (2nd route left on X Block).

Description: Goes up the arete.
Location: On the right arete of the south face of the X Block.

Description: Climb up the pocketed face on the left side of the buttress.
Location: The left most rote on the Salemander Buttress. Located directly left of the route “Skink”.

Description: Climb up the bulging face.
Location: Found on the Salemander Butteress. Found in between the routes “Gecko” on the left, and “Chameleon” on the right.

Description: This route starts off running with a low crux. Continue up the face using what sandy holds you can find. Shares the same anchors as “Salamander”.
Location: Found on the Salemander Buttress. This route is located in between the two routes “Skink” on the left, and “Salemander” on the right.

Description: Climb up the sandy face. Don’t get tricked into going the wrong direction!
Location: This is he last route on the right of the Salemander Buttress.

Description: Huge, grand, stunning. Walk your way up the perfect slab.
Location: The huge boulder around the corner from Body Karate, about halfway down the canyon. Look for the massive, clean, sheer slabby face.
Protection: No. Kind of a do not fall situation.

Description: Fun little boulder problem! Sit start matched on rail, find feet and work your way up. Many variations exist. You can also work left onto the Arete which is fun as well. If there is another name for this please make the change. You can toss your shoes up and put them on, on top so you don’t have to walk through all the moss and mud.
Location: About 100 yards past the Yosemite slab just off the trail on your left.

Description: Start low on flake (same start as Berlier Problem), move up left.
Location: Creek Boulders (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

Description: Start on slopers, travers right on arête then pull yourself over the lip.
Location: Starts at the end of Body Karate and Hypoglycemia.

Description: A fun 5 move problem that starts on the upper portion of the rail. Starts on two crimps with the left foot pasted on the lower rail and the right foot heel hooked on the side of the boulder. Reach high left for good crimp. Switch feet onto the rail. Reach out right for sloper on right corner of the boulder. Heel hook up high left by left hand. Find right hand crimp on top and sloper on left and top out.   It's a fun short problem with the crux being the top out portion up the front of the boulder.
Location: This problem is located in a large cave opening left of a small waterfall just past The Gallery with Battle Axe Tower slightly further down the trail.
Protection: 1 crash pad will do. Two would be better.

Description: Start on two underclings. Work up through two finger pocket and sloped rail. Get to jug rail and finish by turning on to the slab to the right or left. Have fun!!
Location: On the slightly overhung face of Yosemite Slab boulder facing the trail.
Protection: Depends how confident you are on the slab top-out. 1-5 pads.

Description: Start low, matched on flake, then move right to a juggy gaston, then pull up.
Location: Creek Boulders (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

Description: A powerful and beautiful roof compression problem. It starts with a couple of big throws, then some compression with tensiony, far away feet, and finishes with hero climbing on an awesome rail.    If you always wanted to climb The Vice, but don't climb v13 or can't get to Africa, this is your problem.   Arguably the best boulder problem in the canyon, and good enough that it stands out in the region.   Feels v9 to some body types.
Location: This problem is located underneath the boulder just uphill from Yosemite Slab (v0-ish). Look for the steep compression problem leading to a beautiful finish rail.    Start on the undercling about 5 feet deep under the roof. There will be an obvious, left-facing foot rail. I started with my left hand in the good part, my right hand in the undercling that was left over, left toe in the foot rail, and shot right hand out to the rail.
Protection: 2 big pads from Organic were perfect for us.

Description: Just go straight up that corner from a sit start.
Location: About 3 ft right of wolverine.

Description: Start with left hand on a crimp side pull, right on lowest chalked ledge. Catch thumdercling, adjust and huck for the lip.
Location: Starts on the right side of the face that Body Karate is on.

Description: Start with your left hand on undercling crimp, and your right hand undercling pinch. Establish feet, then catch crimp and finish.
Location: Starts left side of the face that David and Goliath is on.

Description: Begin with a sit start under the the Body Karate boulder, throw to the lip and traverse right and finish on Body Karate.
Location: Same boulder as Body Karate, but the side closer to Yosemite slab.

Description: Sit start. Begin with left in positive pocket, your in one of the few shallow two finger pockets. Fire your way up to slopey crimps, then into the slopers at top. Fantastic mantle at top.
Location: O.B.D. Area (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

Description: Work your way up the right arête of the Yosemite slab.0
Location: Right side of the Yosemite slab.

Description: Start on crimps under the small roof, paste your feet and fire to the sloper lip. Establish your left hand on undercling, then try to figure out a way to mantle!
Location: Creek Boulders (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)
Protection: Pads + Spotter (DON'T FALL INTO THE WATER)

Description: Begin matched on jug, do a few moves up on crimps, then left into the arête and up.
Location: Reefer Madness Area (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

Description: Start on the obvious jug and dyno to the chalked up sloper.
Location: Can't remember exact location. Feel free to edit.

Description: Start on two small thunderclings with horrible feet, throw for the jug. Traverse right and up through the jugs  NOTE: The start holds to this problem likely broke sometime after its 03/20/09 FA, making it harder.The best guess based on the first ascensionist’s opinion and the (only?) 2 other ascents of the Pre-Break version put its difficulty at ~V9.The first ascensionist of the original Young Thugs repeated the Post-Break version on 10/30/20 and proposed a tentative grade of V11 (as well as the name “Cum Thugz”).Additionally, while the Pre-Break version was a drop off problem from the jug ledge out right, the newly re-opened Post-Break version tops out the entire boulder (via V0- jug hauling).Also, this is not a jump start, but starting from a 2 (or more) pad stack is totally legit. As long as you establish on the start (first crux) before thrutching to the jug pocket (second crux), you’re golden. Due to the way-more-subjective-than-normal nature of one move wonders, grade opinions for this problem would be much appreciated.
Location: Just south down the hill  of lovely tower, past the cool looking section with the horizontal seems.

Description: The original start begins on two crimp side pulls, but the start holds and feet tend to be wet, so you may have to start in the next couple holds. Pull through the crimps into nice positive holds, then lean back on gastons. Then fight through slopers near the end.
Location: O.B.D. Area (see Sandstone Warrior guide book for more details)

Description: A sweet compression problem with a knee bar and a crux top out.
Location: The problem to the left of Davey Crokett.

Description: Start matched on a jug about chest height, climb up the center of the boulder. Sharp pockets at the end, with s slopey topout.
Location: The center line of the Alamo boulder. Goes up the tallest part of the boulder.

Description: Starts on positive holds, go up using compression moves to a cruxy top out.
Location: Directly to the right of Davey Crockett.

Description: A low ball that's pretty much just a topout.
Location: To the right of Windfall.

Description: Get to the holds up above your head using the large steps on the left side of the boulder. Establish yourself, get a high heel, and go for the big slot up high.
Location: Directly to the left of Texas Revolution.

Description: Texas Revolution starts near the middle of the boulder, on the monster jug. Walk your feet up to get hold of the small left hand crimp, get your feet up, and do a dead point to the high right hand crimp. Get hold of a left hand, get your feet up, and launch for a hold near the top. This is a tall man problem unfortunately.
Location: Center of the boulder.

Description: Start on big holds around chest height, use good feet and good holds to get up.
Location: Starts to the right of Texas Revolution.

Description: Start low on two jugs, throw a heel toe cam in, match the left and work your way through a series of pinches and slopers. This problem isn't over till you've topped it out.
Location: Armageddon 5000 starts to the left of Red Sea.

Description: Same start as Red Sea, but go directly up the arete.
Location: Same start as Red Sea. Climbs the face directly to the right of Armageddon 5000.

Description: start low and left. make a few moves on whatever holds feel best to a hard move to gain a good hold in the middle of the face.  keep moving right then up the heady, somewhat slopey topout
Location: backside of boulder. start on good holds down and to the left. the problem starts heading straight up to top out right above the detached boulder on the ground.

Description: Moses starts on a horizontal edge/pinch to the right of Red Sea. Move left to a crimp and then pull a large lock off move to intersect with Red Sea. Finish up on Red Sea.
Location: Moses starts directly to the right of Red Sea.

Description: This is a link up of Red Sea into Big Mitch.  Sit Start as per Red Sea, but instead of topping out once you get the giant sidepull jug after the hard bit of Red Sea, continue rightwards and slightly down into the start of Big MItch and then finish as per that problem.  I doubt this is a First Ascent, but posting it as such is the most surefire way to get a discussion going about it. Who did this first, what did they name it, and what was their grade opinion?
Location: Sit Start the same as Red Sea, then do the first half of Red Sea, then continue over into Big Mitch and finish on Big Mitch.

Description: This is a link up of Moses into Big Mitch.  Sit Start as per Moses, but instead of topping out once you get the giant sidepull jug,  continue rightwards and slightly down into the start of Big MItch and then finish as per that problem.  Just as with "Big D" I doubt this is a First Ascent, but posting it as such is the most surefire way to get a discussion going about it. Who did this first, what did they name it, and what was their grade opinion?
Location: Sit Start the same as Moses, then after the 1st half of Moses, continue over into Big Mitch and finish on Big Mitch.

Description: Start matched on a pedestal ledge, climb right on good edges, finish it off with a large throw to a good sloper.
Location: Between Red Sea and King Solomon.

Description: Based on "Secrets of So iLL" video: Start in middle of the wall and dyno to gaston-jug (crux). Lower start on crimps may exist.
Location: Red Sea boulder, the wall to the left of the slopey rail for Cain and Ankle.

Description: Sit start and climb up slopey rail using some crimps out left.
Location: Left side of scooped face on back of Red Sea Boulder.

Description: Start on horiztanal holds with hands crossed, then reach up to the seem to the left, paste your foot and fight your way up using nasty slopers.
Location: Starts the right Cain an Ankle. Obvious bulge looking problem.

Description: Climb up the last seam to the right of Big Meech to the positive ledges and the classic slopey topout.
Location: Last line to the right of Big Meech.
Protection: A single crash pad should be fine.

Description: climb arete nearest to the path on Atlas
overhanging face nearest to the trail with fun topout
Location: to the right of V1 arete problem

Description: Starts as a sit start and works right.
Location: On Atlas boulder to the left of Calypso.

Description: Sit start and slap your way up. Top out seems like the crux.
Location: The trail side of Atlas Boulder

Description: to the right of Calypso
Weight of the World
start with good, chest height hands. work straight up sidepulls. big jug on left is optional, but not necessary.  small detached boulder on ground is off.
Location: cliff side of boulder. first problem you see when walking the trail.

Description: climbs the left runnel on the boulder
Location: leftmost runnel on the boulder behind atlas

Description: Start low on the big ledge and move up the overhanging arete through good slopers and pinches. Top out over the corner where the arete meets the top slab.
Location: On the boulder opposing the face of Atlas.
Protection: 2-3 pads to protect the rock below the entire problem.

Description: Start on your choice of good holds to the right of the runnel. Climb the face and opposing runnels to a somewhat committing move up high, easy topout to follow.
Location: first climb left of the arete on the boulder behind atlas

Description: Start on your choice of good holds and climb the face between the right two runnels. Approachable climb with a friendly top out.
Location: Middle line on the large boulder behind atlas

Description: Climb the obvious flared runnel in the center of the boulder. good holds to a slightly slopey finish
Location: middle runnel on the boulder behind atlas

Description: A lowball traverse problem on perfect stone. From a sit-start on the lowest left side of the boulder, follow the lip of the bloc from left to right. When the holds end, mantle it out.
Location: It is the small, UFO-like piece of stone jutting out of the ground that you will see when approaching the 911 Aretes from the back of the Shadow of a Man boulder.

Description: Climb the sloping arete on the leftside of the boulder. Sustained climbing to a relatively easy topout. Climbs harder than it looks.
Location: When facing Your Body is a Wonderland, this obvious boulder will be to your right. Start low on the left arete and follow this to the apex.

Description: Another fun arete climb! Ascend the small boulder using the arete on the left side. Make sure to not mantle it out too early.
Location: On the trail near the cliffline, walk a bit further than you would for Your Body is a Wonderland and the 911 Arete boulder. There will be a small boulder facing the trail.

Description: A surprisingly fun one-mover. Sit-start low on the very obvious smiley crimp and get to the jugs at the lip.
Location: On the trail near the cliffline, walk a bit further than you would for Your Body is a Wonderland and the 911 Arete boulder. There will be a small boulder facing the trail. Climb the trail-side face.

Description: V0 sit start.
Location: Right of Far Nearer. Sit start of the right arete.

Description: On the face opposite Shadow of a Man, start on the semi-circle crimps and move up to the small, crimpy seam. Make a long move right to the bread loaf. Stand up to the slopey rail and bump to the sloped side pull. Arete is off until the top out near Tennis Shoe Arete.A traverse is also possible all the way to KFC/Fat Lip.
Location: The face opposite Shadow of a Man.

Description: Start on edges on the arete do a long reach, followed by another long reach up and left. Easy top out, but not a great fall if you blow it.
Location: The arete left of KFC. On the boulder behind Shadow of a Man and Secret of Davenport.

Description: A compression problem that goes up between Tennis Shoe Arete and KFC. Go to the pocket with your right, then climb up the two arete features.
Location: Between Tennis Shoe Arete and KFC.

Description: Move through good holds until you can get your right hand on the faint, slopey arete. Work your way through this cool feature to the easy top out. Short but sweet.
Location: Walking down the trail to Shadow of a Man, this relatively small boulder will be on your right. Worms Way will be to your left, Shadow of a Man just ahead. KFC climbs the trailside face.
Protection: 1 pad, spotter if you want it

Description: Start sitting quite low on the center of the Shadow of a Man face. Follow small crimps left and up slightly. Slap the lip and do a weird mantle about five feet above the ground. Not the best problem at the Holies, but cool holds. I climbed this thinking it was an FA and gave it this name. Dave Chancellor has since told me it has been done, but he says he cannot recall the name, so we will just go with this.
Location: Shadow of a Man boulder, same face as the namesake problem

Description: Start on Shadow of a Man, traverse left and finish on Secret of Davenport. I've heard that this is the same grade as Secret of Davenport, but I disagree. Plus it heads a few cool moves!     P.S. You can also try to do the sit start to Shadow of a Man, and then connect that into Shadow of Daventport. FA may still be up for grabs!?
Location: Shadow of a Man.

Description: Begin on the Shadow of a Man sit start, several feet to the right of the normal start for Shadow. Pull a large first move to some crimps, then traverse left into the start for Shadow of a Man. From there, traverse into and finish on Secret of Davenport. Adds a few moves to Shadow of Davenport. Not too much harder than Secret/Shadow of Davenport.
Location: A few feet to the right of the normal start of Shadow of a Man; same start as Shadow of a Man Sit

Description: One of the best of the grade the Holies has to offer. Starting on a low jug, move up to a slopey sidepull, do some magic with your feet and reach your left hand up to a bad crimp. Get your feet up, and do a tricky move to a blocky jug in the middle of the face.
Location: On the face of the Shadow of a Man boulder directly left of the right arete.

RouteName: Shadow of a Shadow of a Man
Description: New ultra classic line of 2021 -- start on the footholds of the normal Shadow of a Man and go straight up. The crux is trying to pull on without dabbing on the damn ground. This is as low as it goes... May be impossible for those with wider frames as the space to pull on is quite narrow. And digging it out would just ruin the natural beauty of the line. This is NOT the same as Shadow of a Man Sit, which starts about 8ft to the right.
Location: This starts on the footholds of Shadow of a Man.
Protection: Pad as for Shadow of a Man; I think 2-3 pads works well

Description: For the sit start, begin several feet to the right of the normal start for Shadow. Pull a large first move to some crimps, then traverse left into the start for Shadow of a Man.
Location: A few feet to the right of the normal start of Shadow.

Description: Work your way up a tall slab that leads to a committing mantle up high.
Location: Located to the right around the corner from Shadow of a Man. Start down low and to the left of the tree.

Description: Follow the thin seam to the top-out. Crux is about mid-way up.
Location: This route is located on the same boulder as shadow of a man (around the corner to the right of it). Its on the South West facing side of the boulder approximately in the middle.
Protection: A few well placed pads and active spotters should keep you safe.

Description: Start on two matched pockets and move up the slab on sparse holds and kind of bad feet. The topout is a little tough.
Location: On the Shadow of a Man boulder, on the slab face that is between the Shadow of a Man arete and Seafoam Arete. It's near the middle of the face and starts on two matched pockets, to the right of Seams Easy V5.

Description: Follow the slopey arete to the top of the boulder.
Location: Walk around to the face opposite of Shadow of a Man on the Shadow of a Man boulder. It will be the arete on your left.

Description: Follow a line of small, sharp crimps up the slabby face. Could have more stars if the holds felt a bit better to hold...
Location: Facing Seafoam Arete, it is the problem that ascends straight up the face.

Description: Start standing on slopers, follow the slopey lip about halfway across the entire face and then mantle. Poor feet.
Location: Facing Seafoam Arete and Comfortably Numb, it traverses the swooping lip of the boulder starting on the right side.

Description: Starting on two strange slopey holds, pull onto the wall and lock a heel-toe cam. Work upwards on crimpers to a slightly high top out.
Location: Two lines left of Worms Way
Protection: 3 pads or so would be good for the top out

Description: Starting on a very awful looking hold, follow nearly non-existing holds slightly left and upwards. I do not know very much info about this route, and as far as I know it is unrepeated. Another twisted boulder problem from the mind of Kehl...
Location: Located between Worms Way and Baby Killers. A trifecta of crazy, double-digit problems... Begins quite high on an improbable looking hold that may or may not be chalked.

Description: Climb Worm's Way to the jug, but rather than hanging and dropping, follow a line of crimps to the top of the wall and top out. Might be nice to have these moves dialed in just in case you send Worms Way and have a bit more juice left at the jug. Would be easy to climb up the jug feature to work the crimp moves.
Protection: 2-3 pads and spotters. Falling off the top of this will probably be safe, but scary nonetheless.

Description: Start at the beginning of the arching rail feature and climb up the "worm" through jugs and slopers with helpful heel hooks to keep you from cutting feet. Finish on the large jug at the end of the rail.
Location: In between the KFC boulder and the Public Enemy boulder. Climbs Worm's Way without the hard, V9/10 start.

Description: From a sit start, traverse right on a series of poor pinches to a really large move to gain the huge swooping jug feature. Using the jug swoop, do a sequence that clocks in around v3 and hang and drop at the large circular jug.
Location: Facing the Shadow of a Man boulder, turn around and walk to the cliffline. You will see an obvious, swooping jug feature. The problem begins seated underneath and to the left of that feature.
Protection: 2-3 pads and a spotter. All the difficulty is 3 feet off the ground but falling off the v3 section with no pad would just be adding injury to insult.

Description: A tall proud line. Begin on the middle of the face and work your way up the wall using positive crimps. You may want to try the moves on a rope first, the crux is at the top.
Location: Located to the right, around the arête of Worms Way. The start is on the middle of the face.
Protection: Lots and lots of pads and spotters! Also the landing is very slanted.

Description: An interesting slab problem revolving around one difficult move. Start standing on a thin left hand iron crimp and right hand broken sidepull. Work upwards on small holds to a very long lock-off. Continue towards the jugs near the top of the wall. Hang and drop from the jugs at around 15 feet. The rock is pretty but a bit brittle. Be careful!
Location: From KFC/Worm's Way, walk uphill to the back of the huge boulder that Worm's Way is located on. There should be a large, orange amphitheater across from the slab on the back of the Worm's Way boulder. The Other Axis is located about 10 feet left from the rightmost arete of this wall.

Description: This may have been an FA as I've never heard any talk about this climb, but it seems too obvious to not have ever been done. Name is what my buddies and I have always called it. Climbs the obvious arete to the right of The Other Axis on sharp holds. Hang and drop when the holds get really juggy. Dirtyish...
Location: Uphill from KFC and Worm's Way in the huge orange amphitheater-type wall. The rightmost arete on this wall.

Description: Stand start on the obvious ledge and figure out the beta of choice to reach the ledge about 8 feet above. Top out left to the arete and have at least two pads to jump down on.
Location: Directly behind the Worms Way boulder on the cliffline.

Description: Start on One Bourbon and move right across the face. The crux comes at the One Scotch starting holds. Finish as for One Beer.
Sit start on the left hand side of the boulder. Move up to a good sloping ledge and through sloper pockets to the top out.
Grab holds at head height in the middle of the face and make a move to the top of the boulder.
Start on a good hold at chest height on the left side of the boulder. Move up and left to a large jug and make one more move to the top.

Obvious compression/heel hook move leads to a classic sloper's mantle.   Video here at 2:25  vimeo.com/148795707   We climbed this on 02-2015, let me know if I'm wrong about the FA nature of the ascent :)
Location: On the Bar Stool boulder. Start with the good side-pull of One Beer left hand and right hand around the corner, then head straight up. Toping out is easier if you traverse left a couple feet first on the lip.
Protection: Good landing, crash pad should suffice.

Description: Fun body positioning with a throw to the top and a classic Holies mantle to finish.
Location: Start around the corner from Half-Wheel, just right of the tree. Sit start on slopers with left foot on nub. Move up and left, with a good throw just left of the tree. Mantle or top out at Half-Wheel.

Description: Fun slab to pass the time and work on some good feet.
Location: Around the left corner from public enemy. See photo

Description: Far left, low sit start on short problem

Variations exist for the Start. Either very low on juggy pinches and huecos, or slightly higher on slopey-er pinches. Either go straight up or up and left. Grade depends on these factors, but basically falls withing the V1-V2 range.
Location: Directly to the left of Inspector Gadget. One of the leftmost lines on the Public Enemy Boulder.

Description: Starting seated, reach to a friendly crimp with your left hand and leap to a very positive edge above the lip of the boulder with your right hand. Mantle it out. A fun jump, albeit not the biggest dyno in the world.
Location: It is about in the center of the trailside face. Once you've topped out, jump off the boulder onto a pad to get off.
Protection: The boulder is not very high and one pad should be fine

Description: Between Inspector Gadget and Darkside is this tricky one mover. Start standing with your left hand in a small undercling pocket and right on an awful crimp. Pull onto the wall and smack the lip of the boulder. Move left a bit onto some more positive slopers to top out.

Starting standing on a left hand undercling and a right hand crimp, do two hard bump moves to reach your right hand to the lip of the boulder. Fun and tricky mantle to put you on top. Cool holds and movement, but a bit too lowball to be a classic.
Location: About five feet right of Inspector Gadget, right before the ground starts to go downhill

Description: The usually dirty face to the left of Platypus
Location: Between Dark Side and Platypus

Description: Start on a big jug, then cross with your left to a interesting pinch and find a way to reach the top of the boulder.
Location: Narwhal starts immediately to the left of Platypus.

Description: Start on a low undercling with your left hand and a side pull with your right hand. Pull two moves to the jug on Narwhal.
Location: Between Narwhal and Platypus.

Description: The Square arete on the far right side of the Public Enemy Boulder. Starts on two slopers and does a big move up and left, then another bump with the left hand. A strange three finger undercling/sidepull pinch at the lip leads to a jump to a 45 sloper. Unique top out.
Location: The Farthest right side of the Public Enemy Boulder.  Its the Arete.

Description: Around the corner from Platypus on the big beautiful always-sunny 55° wall, start matched on the obvious right-facing (and hollow sounding) flake at about head height. Directly under the lip from where you start Son of the Morning. Match on the flake, Paste your feet on the garbage footchips, Huck to the lip, And get on top. Note #1: Chris went all the way up the tall slab/4th class scramble on the FA, so I guess you should too.Note #2: don’t be persuaded by Chris’ insistence that this is “only V6”, this thing is V8 all day.
Location: Towards the right side of the 55° wall at about head height is an obvious right-facing crimp flake. That’s where you start Directly under the lip from where you start Son of the Morning.  P.S.A.- it’s probably best to avoid trying this thing when it’s wet or after rain. The flake is hollow and will definitely rip off someday, but we can delay the inevitable if we’re smart.Also, clean your shoes before you try this thing. This sandstone is already pretty soft, and if you have sand and rock on your shoes it’s just gonna grind away at the feet when you push on them. And the feet on this thing are already TERRIBLE, if any of them break it’s gonna be a major bummer.
Protection: Only needs a couple pads. Really easy to try solo.

Description: This is the Low Start to Fading Light. Squat Start matched on the diagonally right-facing flat jug plate undercling hold that is ~10 feet down and left from the start of Fading Light. Again, this is a Squat Start, the first ascentionist did NOT start sitting, so you aren't required to either. Time will tell once a consensus forms, but I think this is one of the hardest lines at The Holy Boulders, up there with MJ & The New Zero. At the very least I think the first move of Ra, from a purely physical standpoint, is the hardest single move at the Holies.  P.S.A.- it’s probably best to avoid trying this thing when it’s wet or after rain. The flake that Fading Light starts on is hollow and will definitely rip off someday, but we can delay the inevitable if we’re smart.Also, clean your shoes before you try this thing. This sandstone is already pretty soft, and if you have sand and rock on your shoes it’s just gonna grind away at the feet when you push on them. And the feet on this thing are already TERRIBLE, if any of them break it’s gonna be a major bummer.
Location: The obvious 55° overhang on the Public Enemy boulder. Around the corner from Platypus. Start ~10 feet down and left from the start flake of Fading Light matched on an obvious diagonal right-facing plate undercling. You can start from a squat.
Protection: Couple pads. All the hard moves are low to the ground

Description: Start on the far right side of the arête in the scoop feature. Follow the crimp seam to a left side pull and a deep pocket jug. Continue on bad slopers all the way to the corner and top out on better holds.
Location: The long, left angling arête of the public enemy boulder. Around the corner from Platypus
Protection: Pads and spotter. Falling with the heel on is not fun

Description: Link-up of Fading Light into Son of the Morning. Start matched on the start flake of Fading Light, after you get to the lip, traverse left to finish on SOTM.
Location: Around the corner from Platypus on the big beautiful always-sunny 55° wall, start matched on the obvious right-facing (and hollow sounding) flake at about head height. Directly under the lip from where you start Son of the Morning.
Protection: At least as many pads as you’d use for Son of the Morning

Description: The logical extension to Son of the Morning that starts on the far right corner of the wall, matched on a crimp slot. Adds a few not-so-hard moves into the start of SOTM, but overall increases the pump factor enough to earn 9 V points.
Location: On the far right side of the 55° wall matched on the crimp slot at the corner.
Protection: At least as many pads as you’d use for SOTM.

Description: A beautiful tall, slabby arête.
Location: Anthrax Arête is on the boulder next to the Public Enemy boulder. If you're facing Platypus, it's the boulder to the right, on the opposite side.
Protection: Pads + Spotters. Be careful, to the left of the arête is a drop off!

Description: Start deep in the cave with both hands in the hand jam section. Work out the cave using fingerlocks, smears, and brute strength. Pull the bulge and finish in the massive hueco for a nice sit down finish (or top out the tall fist crack).
Location: On the main cliffline in between public enemy and undercling king. Look for the massive hueco (15 ft     high) above the cave.

Description: Unnamed problem from the comp. Sit start with hands on a slanted crimpy flake. Smear right foot in the dish and choose 1 of the 2 foot nubs for your left foot. Traverse right along the lower ledge using crimps, a sloper, and a heel hook or two. Lip/top of the boulder is off until the topout at the first crack on the lip. Casual topout on jugs after that.
Location: On the second boulder next to the path in the Tyler Durden area when approaching from the Mollusk. Traverse left to right towards the unnamed V2 arete.

Description: Unnamed V2 from the comp. Sit start on the obvious jug/flake. Climb up pinches on the arete to a juggy topout.
Location: The right arete on the second boulder in the Tyler Durden area when approaching from the Mollusk.

Description: Starting sitting the same as Tyler Durden, cut left and move to a good pocket and do a large move to a jug. From here, go straight up and somehow execute a tricky, dirty and scary mantel off not good holds. Be mindful of the slightly sketchy flake out left. AKA "Marla and the Tree," for reasons that may be obvious when you arrive at the problem.
Location: Starts at the same place as Tyler Durden and cuts up and left. Walk off same as Durden. The tree behind the problem will make it easy to recognize.
Protection: Pads and a good spotter to help you avoid the tree

Description: From a sit start on two juggy holds, work upwards utilizing either a long pull off a small gaston or a big throw to a sloping jug off a crimp near the gaston. Grab a near the top of the boulder before slapping back to another sloper. From here, move right to a good sloping feature and top out. There is a variation that begins on Tyler Durden that cuts left and moves back right to join the top of Durden, and it is around the same difficulty.
Location: Obvious line up the center of the Tyler Durden boulder. Walk over to a smaller, slabby boulder to get off.
Protection: Because of the traversing and slightly insecure nature of the top out, 2 or more pads would be preferred.

Description: Start on two underclings under the bulge. Work your way up to the next slopers and guck for a slopey edge up high. The boulder to the right is off.
Location: Odd Job is located to the right of Tyler Durden and to the left of Robert Paulson and the tree.

Description: Start standing on an undercling and reach back to one of a couple good sloping holds near the back of the boulder. You may have to hop a bit to reach the hold. Top out. Small, short and sweet.
Location: On a very small sloping ramp to the right of Tyler Durden. Walk off the boulder to get off.

Description: Climb the arete to the left of grade school starting on a jug at head height.
Location: Arete left of Grade School

Description: Start on 2 big undercling jugs at the start of the horizontal crack. Cruise over on juicy underclings and follow the left leaning crack up. At the top, grab a slopey hueco in the big cut out, get a high foot, and reach up to nice jugs above the bulge to an nice top out
Location: Opposite face of Tyler Durden. Tall, vertical, heavily-featured face.

Description: A short, ugly boulder problem (similar to the first ascentionist), which consists of two moves. Starting on a jug with a right heel hook reach to a bad sloping edge and then do either a big bump to a jug up and right or match, then do the big bump.
Location: The farthest left line on the first boulder in the Brown Cow Area. Starts right of a tree, on a good jug very low to the ground.

Description: Left most (of the good climbs) on the first boulder. Goes up the center of the wall utilizing two big sloping square pinch features. Tops out up and left.
Location: Center of the Wall, starts on obvious Jug feature. Down climb is back and left of the boulder.

Description: To the Right of "V2 (I)." Starts on a Jug and climbs up and right through crimpy flakes and sidepulls, and eventually a righthand seam. Tops out using a juggy "spearhead" looking hold.
Location: To the left of the obvious jug crack on the first boulder in the Brown Cow Area.
Protection: pads and spotters... Be careful of the flexing edges down low. Dont step on them too much!

Description: Short and Dirty Crack on the right side of the first boulder you come to at the Brown Cow Area
Location: Obvious crack on the right side of the first boulder in the Brown Cow Area

Description: Good but short. Sit Start on the farthest right side of the first boulder in the Brown Cow Area, on small edges. Climb up the seams and edges to juggy top out.
Location: On the farthest right side of the boulder.

Description: On the first boulder at the Brown Cow Boulder. Traverse left from the farthest right sit start holds to the V2 (I) and top out as such. A good warm up.
Location: Runs the length of the first boulder

Description: Fun little problem on the left side of the Brown Cow Boulder. Jugs to a fun topout.
Location: Two problems left of Brown Cow. RIght in front of a small tree.

Description: Fun climbing on cool edge features to a high right hand gaston finger bucket and a fun topout. Starts on the ledge features which is used as a heelhook on Brown Cow.
Location: Start directly left of Brown Cow.

Description: Fun but contrived. Climbs the obvious brown streak of wall with black speckles. Start on your choice of low start holds (a left hand edge, and a right hand crimp or right hand slopy pinch) with a massive left heel hook. The heel hook ledge is "off" for a hand. Figure out some beta and work your way up powerful sidepull pockets and features to some sharp jugs and a thoughtful topout. Holies V6.
Location: The obvious brown speckled streak of wall with lots of chalk.

Description: Start on low jug undercling and do a big move up and right, out of the overhang to a good edge. Match the edge and finish on jugs. Crux is not draggin yo azz on da ground.
Location: directly down and right from Brown Cow. Starts on jug undercling in the chossy mini roof low to ground.

Description: Tall face to the right of Brown Cow. Start on high start holds and climb up the featured wall.
Location: on the rightside of the Brown Cow face, seven feet left of the arete.

Description: Dig hard on that heel and follow the bad slopers up and right to the start of Sukha stand. Start hold tends to be wet for a while after a good rain.
Location: Sit start low and left of the start for Sukha, and follow the bad slopers.

Description: Really fun!! Classic Holy Boulders Slopey Jugs to a hard topout. Starts directly to the left of the arete on the Brown Cow Face.    super fun and easy dyno eliminates can be done on this climb if you're into that :) d
Location: Rightmost line on the same face as Brown Cow. Big Slopers and Jugs. This also serves as the downclimb. .. stack pads and jump off.

Description: Sit Start on two 1 pad crimp/seam/edges and either go out left to a pinch on the arete and then head up, or do a big left hand move straight up to a good rail. Juggy topout.
Location: The leftmost line on the back face of the Brown Cow Boulder. Right around the arete from Sukha.

Description: Start in good edges with a big ass right foot down low. Climb left and then up. Heed the name. Do a righthand cross move to a good slot, and then jump out left to a comfortable slopey jug. Big jugs all the way to the top! instant classic. Thanks to Phillip and the ICA for cleaning off all of these old classics!!!
Location: The line directly right of Helios.

Description: Start in slopers at chest height and traverse right through more slopers to a somewhat dirty topout. Fun, just needs more traffic. Walk right to get off the boulder.
Location: To the Right of Cross and Toss.

Description: Sit Start on obvious crimper plate/flake feature. Do a big lockoff up and right to some good slopers, fun and casual topout. Wish it were longer!!
Location: Second rightmost climb on the backside of the Brown Cow Boulder. Starts low on obvious crimp plate feature.

Description: Fun little warmup on good slopey edges. Farthest right line on the backside of the Brown Cow boulder. Short but sweet.
Location: Just to the left of the arete on the backside of the Brown Cow Boulder. Farthest right line.

Description: The first route on the next boulder if heading right up the trail from Sukha. The sloper up and right of the first crimp on the face looks good, but is practically useless; bumping your left hand up the rail is the better option.
Location: Start low on the big holds immediately right of the tree, move up the rail until beneath the slopey crimp. Then move up directly to the slopey rail and top out.  Going out right into the groove puts you on the V2 variation.

Description: The starting section has a fun sequence moving through big holds. Easy topout.
Location: Start the same as Fisherman direct, but move farther up the rail until in the groove, and then move up to the topout from there.

Description: Community Service stars on a left hand pinch and a slopey crimp for the right. Work your way up the boulder using slopers and pinches.
Location: This problem is located on the right side of the same boulder as The Fisherman.

Description: The back of the Mollusk boulder is littered with a large amount of holds, most being very positive. There are many variations that exist. Traversing from left to right (and back again as much as you please) is a great way to get warm on some great feeling holds.
Location: On the back of the Mollusk boulder
Protection: Pads and a spotter if you're going to top it out

Description: Sit start on great jug and okay feet. Follow obvious jugs. Great sloper to left of the small crack and a good lefthand sidepole on the left edge make for a clean topout.
Location: SW corner of boulder. Sit start hand-matched on great jug.

Description: You'll have lots of options to go up and down the rails that run this side of the boulder, but a lot of the holds are junk. Give it a feel before jumping on. Good warm-up.
Location: Start on Lowrider and traverse right. Topout up the crack at the end. Have a spotter to drag your pad, and to keep you from hitting the tree if you fall off the topout.

Description: start on horizontal finger cracks at chest high to the left of con artist, work straight up crimps on short problem. This was formerly mis-named as “El Pinto” , but it was an unnamed V1 from the comp.

Start on your choice of very poor slopey slot crimps and head straight up the short slabby face. Hard move off bad left hand crimp. Deceivingly hard. Selected quotes: "Oh, that'll go next go for sure." "That was so close!" "Maybe next trip..."
Location: Center of the Mollusk boulder
Protection: 1-2 pads, a spotter isn't really necessary but may help

Description: Follow the very obvious line that goes along the slopey scoop on the right side of the boulder. The classic warm-up of the Holies.
Location: Right side of the Mollusk boulder

Description: Sit start on some bad feet and a sloping crimp in the middle of the boulder. Make a strong move up to jugs for an easy topout. The V1 next to con artist was perviously misnamed as “El Pinto.”
Location: This problem is on the right side of the boulder directly behind you as you’re looking at the mollusk.

Description: Start in the cut out part of the boulder, then figure some way to get your feet up onto the slab part.
Location: This problem is around the right arête of Bubble Wrap. It's the obvious slab problem.

Description: Start low on a thin rail and a right undercling, bust through the opening move and continue up the face to the easier top-out.
Location: First problem on the far right of the Bubble Wrap boulder. This will be the initial problem you encounter coming down the trail.

Description: Start low and work your way up using slopey pinches. The topout is probably the hardest part.
Location: Hourglass is located the right side of the largest boulder in the second cluster of boulders, next to the small bridge.

Description: Climb using good hold to the top
Location: Left most problem on the boulder. Refer to photo.

Description: Pull using good holds to reach the Death Star. Continue up and through the middle of the Death Star
Location: First problem to the right of No Disintegrations. Refer to photo

Description: Climb using thin horizontal seam to reach the right side of the Death Star. Climb to the top from here.
Location: First problem to the right of Death Star Center. Refer to photo

Description: Start on good horizontal seams, get your feet set and make a long reach to a good hold. Continue using horizontal seams to reach the top.
Location: First problem to the right of Battle For Endor. Refer to photo

Description: Start on the right side of the boulder pulling on crimps. Make a long reach to good holds and continue to the top.
Location: Refer to photo

Description: Climb using thin horizontal seams to reach the top
Location: To the right of Boba Fett.

Description: Use good holds to reach the top
Location: To the right of That's No Moon.

Description: Sit start with your hands on the lowest slopers possible. Climb up using more slopers to a crux, slopey topout!
Location: On the right side of the Bio-Terrorism boulder.

Description: Same start as Bio-Terrorism, but when you reach the lip, start moving left, then top out.
Location: Same start as Bio-Terrorism

Description: sit start and go up along arete
Start matched in crimpy hueco, post your feet, then go for the lip. The topout is the hardest part!
Location: Wall facing the path.

Description: Tall but doable. Start on a large undercling sidepull jug feature and work up and slightly right. Crux is a long move to a gaston from a small 2-3 finger right hand gaston. high as hell, proud.
Location: when facing the jungle book arete, this climb will be up and right of you. You will see a large hueco on a face up the hill. This is the boulder you want. Head through the corridor to a a tall face, with a large jug undercling/sidepull feature at about 6 feet. This is kings high

Description: Begin on a sloper, pull a couple lock off moves, then cruzer at the top.
Location: Left side of the face that Jungle Book is on.

Description: Classic overhung arete madness on the leftside of the New Zero Boulder. start on the left of the arete on jugs climb up aways till the holds disappear then do a large, but static move to a sloper on the arete. Slot a toe-hook then match the sloper. Cut your feet and enjoy the ride. Stick the crazy swing and then campus the final moves to a hard but manageable topout. Absolutely hyper-classic
Location: the arete to the left of the new zero
Protection: many pads and spotters for crazy swing.

Description: THE testipece of the Holy Boulders. Jason was shown this line when it was dubbed "fatty sloper action" and devoted his time to be rewarded the FA of the best line at the Holies. Start down and right on the arete jug and move up and left through horrible slopers to a hard heel hook or hop move at the lip. absolutely gorgeous climb on sticky holds with perfect Fontainebleau friction, and features.
Location: to the left of Michael Jordan. the first, and rightmost line on this boulder.

Description: The amazing looking sloper problem to the left of Crimson Flower. Sit Start down and right in the "Air Jordan" feature. Make a big move up and left and then work through the slopey feature to reach a bad right hand crimp. Make a huge dyno move off of this crimp to a hold over the lip. Hard, scary mantle.
Location: to the left of Trillium/Crimson Flower.

Description: Sit Start as for Michael Jordan, pick your ass up and traverse rightwards into Crimson Flower via a somewhat cryptic sequence and finish as for Trillium.The irony won’t be lost on cultured individuals (such as those reading this no doubt) that Reptilian Shapeshifter is the BONAFIDE Trillium Sit Start, whereas Crimson Flower is merely a LOW start to Trillium, rather than being a true SIT as often described. Avoiding the dab plays into the difficulty a bit, but not as much as it might seem at first glance. All in all, this is a worthy goal for those who’re at the point where running laps on Trillium is child’s play, but who’ve long since realized that this gets them no closer to a send of the intimidating Michael Jordan. Real Ballers might even use this as a stepping stone to MJ...
Location: It’s the same start as Michael Jordan, the slopey blob thing near the bottom of the slopey runnel running up the face of the boulder.
Protection: Pads. For the start you needn’t hardly any at all, for the end just use as many as you normally use for Trillium.

Description: Adds two moves. Low start with right hand slopey hueco sidepull, and left hand hueco sidepull. Left foot either toe hook or heel-toe cam. Climb up the slightly overhung wall utilizing slopers, pockets, crimps and a second heel-toe cam. Cruxy top-out. Sometimes also known as "Crimson Flower"
Location: The Sit Start to Trillium

Description: Starts on a left hand 3 finger pocket (four for some) and a right hand slopey slot. Utilize either a hard to place heel-toe cam or a bad smear to get to an iron crimp feature. Slopers, sidepulls, and crimps lead you to a hard topout.
