Location: To the right of Michael Jordan, the leftmost line on the first boulder.

Description: Dont know who put it up, and fairly certain it has never been repeated. Climb the water groove directly left of the tree, and to the right of trillium.
Location: directly to the left of the tree.

Description: Start directly to the left of Enlightenment. Stand Start on two holds at chest height. A right hand sidepull, pockety fingerlock thing, and a left hand pinch. Hard move going left to a pinch, go right to a sloper, then duckbill crimp, then top out. Two topouts are often done. If you traverse right into enlightenment, it feels morelike v6, but the original way stays straight, and avoids all the holds on enlightenment. This way probably clocks in around v7.
Location: start to the right of a tree and left of Enlightenment

Description: This is the first boulder you will come upon in the Illuminati sector. Climb the rounded arête utilizing slopers jugs as pinches. Sit start low and slightly right on arête with big feet. The crux is the topout. Enjoy
Location: First obvious arête with slopey huecos and jugs. Down climb is on back of boulder

Description: Start on two wide sidepull crimps, and drop into a right hand crimp. Then climb straight up the technical face... (look for that undercling!) a committing last throw to a jug in order to avoid dabbing/crashing through the  tree. Crux is making the stab into the slot at mid height. Some use the thin undercling, others go big...  Absolutely classic.. Enjoy.
Location: To the right of Enlightenment around the arete. obvious face climb on crimps and slots.

Description: Line to the right of Undercling King. Start in front of a large tree. Climbs the obvious left angling feature. the moves to the top are relatively easy, then the heat comes,, watch out for that tree ;) Running with scissors... you're not SUPPOSED to do it.    ***EDIT***    Since being posted, the tree has been removed and the landing cleaned... Scissorless Running
Location: To the right of Undercling King

Description: Same start as Running with Scissors, but cut right when you reach the seam heading to the right side of the boulder.
Location: To the right of Undercling King.

Description: Start on high ledge, pull move into large flake and climb up.
Location: Directly to the right of Bubbles.

Description: You better keep your core tight if you want to finish this one. Have It starts with your left hand in a pocket and right on the arête. Work your way up the arête using smears and balance. The finish move is the crux.
Location: Have It is located on the arête of the cliff cline up the hill from the Full Grain boulder.

Description: A tall slab with a little dyno with decent holds.
Location: To the right of Avant Gardener.

Description: Climb up tall featured slab. The crux is at the beggening.
Location: Avant Gardenor is on the right side of the same wall that Presto is on, but to the left of Lemon of Pink.

Description: The slab along the arete to the left of Presto. This is also the (scary) downclimb for Presto.
Begin a few feet to the right of the arete. Climb up the slab face using good feet and a crimp near the top. Arete is off.
Location: Behind Have It and around the corner of Stand Up to the Right.

Description: Start on a side pull around head height, get a smear and pull up to a bad right hand side pull. Hand-foot match, and stand up.
Location: The right side of the same slab the Stand Up to the Left is located. Also directly behind Have It.

Description: For this problem you're going to start on the left bigger hueco on the big slab face. Once you have your hands in it, start traversing left and up to a committing last move.
Location: This problem is directly up the hill to the left from the Full Grain boulder, and slightly to the right of the tree next to the boulder.

Description: Start in the middle left of the face, then work your way up and to the left to the arête using crimps.
Location: Located on the opposite side of the Boulder as Stand up with the Left, in the corridor. The start is a little bit to the right of the arête.

Description: Same start as B-Cup, but go up to the pinch with your right hand instead. Use a toe hook to pull a rose move to the top.
Location: Same start as B-Cup.

Description: Start towards the bottom left of the slab, hand(s) in a slopey dish. Continue straight up the slab until the crux at the lip, don't slip!
Location: Downhill from the cliffline and trail between the Illuminati boulders and Vulture's nest area. Just uphill from Jump for Jesus.
Protection: A few pads and a spotter.

Description: A slab problem using the right arête of the Full Grain boulder.
Location: Swade is located on the right side of the same boulder as Full Grain. Start and finish using the right arête.

Description: Climb the finger crack that splits the face like an exponential decay function through a graph. Sit start low on the crack and finesse your way up with toe jams, gastons, and laybacks.
Location: Just downhill from the Full Grain slab, but before Jump for Jesus. The crack can be seen by looking through the corridor between Jump for Jesus and the abutting boulder to the right.

Description: Start matched on the large hole, move out left to the arete, and top out.
Location: Left side of the boulder that Jump for Jesus is on.

Description: Start on two opposing crimpy side pulls, dyno to the lip and top out.
Location: Downhill from Full Grain, right from Bill Cosby. On the far right side of the boulder's face.

Description: Start sitting down, climb up on good holds.
Location: To the right of Jump for Jesus

Description: Start low, with right hand on the arête, left hand on anything you can grab. Stand up to a small left hand crimp, get a higher right foot and shoot for the lip.
Location: Shoot from the Hip is located a couple boulders to the right of the problem Jump for Jesus. When heading that the direction, you'll come face to face with the slaby problem.

Description: Start low with left hand in a two finger pocket and right hand on a pinch. Huck to the lip and mantle.
Location: The problem immiedtly to the right, around the arête, from Shoot at the Hip.

Description: Start low, with right hand at the end of the pockety feature, and left hand on pinch. Huck for the lip, then mantle.
Location: A few feet directly to the right of Bourban Shooter.

Description: Work your way up the face using pockets.
Location: Bubbles is located on the cliff line, a little bit to the right of where Have It is located. Unfortunately there isn't a direct path to the problem.

Description: Start low on sloper, throw for the boob, then pull to the lip.
Location: B-Cup is located on the cliff line. To get there start at Have It, and move left along the cliff line for about a hundred yards till you hit an arête. You'll know you've found it when you see a iron boob-like hold.

Description: Start low and to the right of the start for B-Cup. Pull the first move to the start of B-Cup, then throw for the arête to finish.
Location: Starts down and to the right of B-Cup.

Description: Start on two good side pulls to the left of Bangin Blood. Climb up using some nasty slopers.
Location: To the left of Bangin Blood.

Description: Start on flake, pull over arete to crimps and top out.
Location: To the right, down the cliff line from B-Cup.

Description: Same start as Bangin Blood, but go directly up instead of using the crimps out right.
Location: Same as Bangin Blood.

Description: This thing is absolutely crazy! You begin under a short roof, get set up on a couple crimps and do a huge dyno to a sloper. Then work up using the slopers, a mono, and a heel-toe cam. The second crux is throwing to the lip. After this you top out on about 10 feet of slab, 20 feet off the ground.
Location: Cripps is located up the hill from Brown Recluse on the cliff line.

Description: From a sit-start just left of the middle of the face on a right hand sloper hueco, and a left hand juggy hueco, climb left and then upwards on cool sloping jugs. Move out right for first crux move before finally heading straight up and left on fingery holds to the scary and difficult topout.
Protection: Many pads, as the landing isn't perfect and a fall near the top of this big boulder is possible!

Description: Climb up the large water groove, using slopers and pockets. Crux is near the top.
Location: Twin Eagles is to the right and around the corner from Brown Recluse.
Protection: Pads + Spotter. You'll probably want to get on a rope and clean off all the holds as well, due to the problem not getting much traffic.

Description: Start in the good, high horizontal.
Location: On the cliffline just up hill from BR boulder.

Description: TW and I cleaned this off in 2013. The moves aren't too hard, but the commitment factor is.
Location: Start about 10 feet left of the water groove feature on a high sloping jug.

Description: Start on flakey jug, then work your way up using slopers.
Location: Directly to the left of Cracked Shell.

Description: Start low on jug and throw to crimp ledge. Match and fight through slopers to finish.
Location: First route to the left of embryo stasis.

Description: Start as per Embryostasis, but continue left out of the embryo feature into the slopey topout of Cracked Shell.
Location: Look for the embryo-like hueco. Begins on jugs below at the same spot where Embryostasis starts.

Description: Start low on pointed jug, climb up through the "embryo" and topout through the thin seam.
Location: Vultures Nest Boulders (center).

Description: Start on jug rail to the right of embryo stasis. Traverse right to the arete, climb up and top out.
Location: The climb to the right of embryo stasis.

Description: Begin on good holds low and to the right of the arete feature. Climb through the arete to a hold in the seam. Top out to the left from there.
Location: 20 feet to the right of the main Vultures Nest problems. Locate the obvious arete feature.

Description: Start low on pockets, traverse up right and top out behind the tree.
Location: To the left around the arête from Open Gates.

Description: Sit start on the far left side of the overhang. Crux is a fun dyno off a left-hand pinch.

Sit-start to Open Gates. Starts in the hueco down and right. Getting of the ground is the crux. Lift off the ground using mental fortitude that your bicep doesn't burst and fall into a slopey crimp. Get a heel toe cam in the hueco and reach up for a weird 2-3 finger sideways pocket. lock that off to the crimp on open gates, busting left to the pinch and throw to the finish.    I've searched for a first ascentionist to what I thought was an obvious problem. The only thing i have found is that Luke Parady may have done this problem many many years ago but the person was unsure. So if anyone knows, I'm all ears!
Location: Hueco start under roof. Sit Start

Description: A classic line that I am really surprised that I couldn't find online before. Perhaps an FA by me -- likely a barefoot first ascent. Start on Chocolate and Cheese V2 on the Open Gates Boulder. Traverse left then slightly down into the middle of Open Gates V4/5. Finish up by executing the crux of Open Gates and topping it out. Initially FA'd barefoot by me, which probably made it harder than it had to be -- but also more fun. Felt like a V7 or a soft V8 since I couldn't get the left foot down to the jug foot for the crux of Open Gates -- some other beta would probably soften this up a bit so some repeats are welcome!
Location: Walk in from the parking on the side of the road that a line of cars usually parks at. Five minutes along the path you'll see the Open Gates boulder. The line is described above.

Description: Easy side of V2 problem. Start on obvious diagonal shelf in the middle of the boulder and then up and over the bulge on huecos and horns. A variation of continue to the left side of the crack is also possible and a smidge harder. Obviously been done before but no info here. If it already has a name, feel free to edit.
Location: Huge diagonal shelf in the middle of the boulder. Hard to miss.

Description: Kung Fury has the same start as Flugelhorn, but instead of topping out directly up, you move left behind the tree on small sharp crimps.
Location: Same start as Flugelhorn.

Description: Short, steep, pinches & compression on the far right side of the boulder.

We started seated off a right handed crimp with a left heel hook, and moved up onto slopers before continuing left towards flugelhorn's topout. Finishes with a fun mantle. It's a pretty fun lowball sloper battle and figured more people aught to try it out.   Name is just something fun we thought of and the grade is a guess. This line was already pretty clean so I assume it has been done before by someone. I figured I would go ahead and post it here, but if you have any information on it then please let me know.
Location: This is ten feet or so to the Right of Flugelhorn, below a large groove in the rock, just before the boulder gets very low and mossy. Ill add a picture sometime soon.

Description: Start as low as you can on the slopey arête. Traverse right on good holds, then top out.
Location: Left side of the boulder.

Description: Find the good right hand undercling and left hand edge to start. Establish a foot, then follow slopers, seams, and jugs to the top. Lower variations are possible to spice things up a bit.
Location: Wall opposite Hot Rats boulder.

Description: Surprisingly fun 2-3 move mantle problem. Establish in sidepulls and flip yer mitts for the mantle. I obviously do not claim an FA on this: if anyone knows the name of this route please let me know and I will edit this. Fun enough problem to share on here though.
Location: Across from Sweet As, Man.

Description: The start to this problem is down low, on a right hand pinch and a left hand crimp. The first move is the crux, and you need to be careful to not dab on the boulder behind you. Fun arete climb.
Location: To the left of Sweet As.

Description: Start low on a flat shelf and climb up through a flake and some positive slopers to an even more slopey top-out slab. Finesse your body over the bulge and finish your way up the delicate top section.
Location: Trend right on the trail through a few large, tall boulders with a very low angle slab to the right. This boulder is located directly through this corridor, the problem is located in the middle of the face.

Description: Start matched on a large flake and cross into an interesting plated-mushroom hold on the roof then move out the the large, positive sloper to the right. Establish on the sloper and move up through your choice of pockets and other holds to a jug and following top out.
Location: This problem is directly right of Sweet As, Man. Look for the big sloper.

Description: Start on head-high jugs, heel and cross up and right to some smaller holds. Then toss to the lip, mantle, and scramble to the top.
Location: Take the trail right between two tall boulders. Walk past a slab on the right towards Sweet As, Man, then turn right.
Protection: One or two crash pads should do it.

Description: Start matched on two crimps down low. Pull some moves to get out to the arete out left. Same finish as Stilleto.
Location: Same boulder as Stiletto. The start is down and right of the bulge.

Description: Start low on the obvious double crimp, pinches up and left, with some blind slaps left to the arete. This seems to be the route that most some people are doing in videos tagged as Hot Rats.
Location: Start on the same obvious double crimp as Hot Rats but instead of going straight left through the roof, make your way up on pinches before traversing left to the Stiletto/Hot Rats finish.

Description: Climb the offwidth chimney on the warm-up boulder. Shimmy your way up to the lip without using the arete.
Location: On the warm-up boulder near Fire Up the Barbie and Hot Rats.

Description: Awkward moves in a short fist crack lead to a ledge underneath a roof. Once you figure out how to stand up underneath the roof, one kind-of-airy move will get you above it, then a short army crawl will put you in reach of the anchors.
Location: Right facing crack to your left when you meet the cliff line on the trail from Shadow of a Man
Protection: Standard rack, maybe an extra #3 C4, maybe a #4 to protect the easy move to mantle at the top of the crack.     Bolted anchor with chain and rap rings

Description: Some nice feet on the arete of the crack wall at the beginning peter out a third of the way to make for a pretty blank extended crux that ends with a difficult mantle. A couple of easier moves for a second mantle will get you up to the anchors.    Definitely requires solid off-width technique. Long sleeves recommended.
Location: Once you meet the cliff line above Shadow of a Man, walk to the right past the roof. The wide crack is in a left-facing dihedral
Protection: #5 and #6 C4s    Bolted anchor with chain and rap rings

Description: A nice(although short) line that starts as fingers and gets gradually wider after a small ledge. There are a few face holds to pull on when the crack turns to wide hands near the top.
Location: This crack is located near the point where the main trail meets the cliff line by shadow of a man. When you meet the cliff line, there will be a wide crack slightly to your left. Turn right and follow the cliff for a few yards.Look for the obvious crack next to a small tree.
Protection: Standard Rack. Bolted anchors have recently been installed at the top.

Description: Climb the face using big holds and easy moves
Location: First route you come to on the trail. On the left side of the first tall wall

Description: Climb just left of the corner, work your way up to the seam and continue to the top
Location: To the right of Know Your Grammar
Protection: 3 bolts to the anchor (shares anchor with the route to the right of it)

Description: Begin pulling on good flakes and climb into the scoop. Work to get high feet and pull the small bulge using a good left hold and a pocket. Continue through good holds to the top.
Location: first route to the right of ticket to ride

Description: Begin by climbing left of the arete. Use good holds on the arete to access a blocky rail on the left. Continue through tricky moves to the top.
Location: To the right of

Description: Climb the featured face. Follow the bolt line and pull through good holds to reach the top
Location: First route to the right of Geometrics

Description: Climb through good holds through a leftward leaning fin. Pull over the top of the feature and clip the anchor
Location: Refer to photo when posted. Left side of hallway, on the right

Description: Mixed, climb the protectable crack to a single bolt. Anchors are over the second ledge.
Location: Directly left of Dr. Feel Good

Description: Start up the easy face to a hard sequence using poor feet.
Location: Directly right of Sir Mix-a-Lot

Description: Begin on Dr. Feel Good, but immediately move right after clipping the first bolt. Climb to cool iron blobs.
Location: First route to the right of Dr. Feel Good

Description: Probably should stick clip the first. Start on not so positive holds below the first bolt (fairly engaging). You may think it's in the bag after clipping the 2nd and 3rd but another crux awaits before the chains. Keep it together. Great rests on this route with some cool holds and interesting moves.  Note: For an easier start you can also traverse in from the shared start of the routes that begin to the right. But I recommend doing it as it was first done. Treat yourself don't cheat yourself. :-)
Location: Directly left of Phillip's route

Description: Start on good holds traversing up and left. Use the obvious but not so positive slot for the left hand and rock up to a slopeyish crimp. Make the clip and utilize the rest, the hard part is over. Locate the secret jug for clipping the 3rd. Once you hit the lip it's positive holds to the chains. Quite possibly the best route at the Pass.
Location: Refer to photo when posted

Description: Climb through the steep face on good holds
Location: Directly right of the Unnamed 5.12

Description: Begin in the left crack. Work your way up to a small roof, cut left with the crack, and continue up.
Location: Left corner crack when you enter the bedroom

Description: Climb the right crack, protecting when necessary. When the main crack system ends, pull over a small roof and climb the last crack section and top out the route.
Location: The right crack in the bedroom
Protection: Standard rack to No. 3. Currently a top out climb. No anchor

Description: Narrow chimney. Requires a top rope set by someone who has considerable experience building anchors.
Location: As you enter Carol Lamb’s Bedroom from the right passageway (walking between between Sprecher Brew Co and Sir Mix-a-Lot), look for the first overhead boulder that joins the two walls. This route is on the side of the boulder closest to the trail (farthest from Carol Lamb’s Bedroom).
Protection: As of this posting, there are no fixed anchors. Requires a top rope set by someone who has experience building anchors.

Description: Narrow chimney. Requires a top rope set by someone who has experience building anchors.
Location: As you enter Carol Lamb’s Bedroom from the right passageway (walking between between Sprecher Brew Co and Sir Mix-a-Lot), look for the first overhead boulder that joins the two walls. This route is on the side of the boulder farthest from the trail (closest to Carol Lamb’s Bedroom).
Protection: As of this posting, there are no fixed anchors. Requires a top rope set by someone who has experience building anchors.

Description: Beginning  on Draft Root Beer, climb the opening moves. Clip the first bolt and work up and left to an in-cut shelf. Clip the bolt and continue up and straight from here until you reach the anchor.
Location: Begin at the same spot as Draft Root Beer

Description: Start on the arete, and begin pulling through good holds. Angle up and right moving through a good side pull and edges to reach the anchor
Location: To the right of Unnamed 5.10. Refer to photo when posted

Description: Beginning on Draft Root Beer, climb up through the first two bolts. From here climb up and right and clip from a good jug. Work the difficult traverse into a corner. Clip again and climb the corner up to a large block jug and eventually around the arete. Clip again again and pull to the anchor.    5.8 Variation: Shown in RED on the beta photo. Bypass the tough traverse section and  Layback the crack as a more direct start for the route. Traditionally protect when necessary to reach the bolted line.
Location: Begin on Draft Root Beer
Protection: 6 bolts to the anchor. Extend the last 3 bolts for better rope management

Description: Starting at the low point of a jug rail matched(butt should be on ground) work your way right working the feet to a fairly easy cross. Work feet again an set for a throw then to another. Then traverse right an work your way up the easy face. The finish has good holds but there is some that could be questionable(Use your best judgment). Top out is a right hand up to a horn feature then slide left onto the ledge. Also in the traverse you will encounter two sharp crimps an a crummy slopey pocket. Not sure on the grade. Hopefully others will get on it. If I am not the FA please let me know and we can change it.
Location: To the left of flying pig. You will see a sign at this area. When facing it look left and down to the obvious starting jug.
Protection: Couple pads and a spotter if you go up the face for the finish. I gave this pg-13 simply because the face has not been cleaned and one should move delicately through this section.

Description: Climb the featured face to a hard roof sequence. Make sure you have an attentive belay
Location: Left route on the overhand about 50ish yards down trail from Draft Root Beet

Description: Climb the face. Traverse right around the roof. Follow easy ground to anchors.
Location: Directly right of Flying Pig

Description: Make thin moves to easy ground. Climb the steep, juggy roof to high anchors.
Location: On the overhang located about 100 yards down trail in the tree line

Description: Start matched on good hold beneath the two big pockets and work up and left to a hang and drop
Location: Located to the right of the Overlook wall

Description: Fun line.  Start on shelf and move through pockets, throw for the jug and top out.  Rinse and repeat.
Needs some more cleaning and traffic on the boulder. Then, it will be a classic. Stand start and work straight up using the well-featured holds.
Location: Right side of boulder.

Description: Start in the big hole near the ground and work straight up using the crack
Location: Starts to the left of Bane of Chris

Description: A neat addition right off the trail.    The obvious line traverses right  through the rail into the pocketed roof section and finishes with a good top out to the right.   It is a very obvious line, so I imagine that it has been climbed before.  Any Route name/ FA info?
Location: The first left hand hallway encountered after carol lamb room.    Just before the stairway leading to the top of the cliff.   Starts down and to the left on an obvious low angled arete.

Description: Start on Kitten's Claws and work right using the underclings and top out on Bane of Chris
Location: Same start as Kitten's Claws

Description: Start standing with good holds and a massive pocket for a foot. Then use an undercling to reach up onto bulging face of the boulder and blindly find the crimp. Now match the crimp, hike up your feet, and then toss your left hand up to the ledge at the peak of the arete. Then get your feet up to the crimp and walk off the top.
Location: The large overhanging bulge to the left of the slab face on the same boulder as Dream Crusher.

Description: This is a fun slab problem that starts on two small ledges with tiny variations in the rock for feet. Moving up to a sidepull and then manteling onto the top of the boulder is probably the crux. We climbed it in 90 degree weather. It is probably more of a 2 when it's cold out.
Location: This route is on the freestanding boulder directly in front of the Alto Standard, is right on the trail. You'll find it on the left side of the slab close to the staircase.
Protection: You might want a pad, but it's not that bad. Great landing.

Description: Start matched on a huge ledge with small feet. Then move up and to the right to a crimp and a great jug. Then use another good hold on the top to move up the face.
Location: Just to the right of Dream Crusher on the slab face.

Description: Sit start and work up using the variety of well-featured holds.
Location: Not actually on the railroad boulder, but directly across the trail from it on the face of the boulder facing toward the start of the trail.

Description: Low sit start. Start on left side crimps and move up right toward lip.
Location: The small overhang boulder directly on the other side of the trail from the railroad boulder.

Description: Stand start and work up.
Location: Start in center of boulder.

Description: Begin by sitting on ground with hands on a jug. Reach to the right for a sloper.
Location: Left of Sexy Arete

Description: Begin by sit starting with one hand on and edge and one on a jug
Location: Left of Loose Lucy

Description: This is the sit start for Loose Lucy
Location: To the left of Dog Fight

Description: Begin with hands in a slot.
Location: To the left of Dog Fight

Description: Start on high edges and pull a difficult move to shelf above.
Location: Starts on the opposite side of Sex on the Beach problem.

Description: Begin with high hands on an edge. Climb up the low angled face.
Location: Right of Dog Fight

Description: Begin this problem with your left hand in a pocket and your right hand in a crack feature. Layback to the top.
Location: Just left of Marks Arete

Description: There are a lot of holds on the arete, so the beta can be hard to read. There are a couple variations on the problem, but I began the problem starting on two holds on opposite sides of the arete, doing a big move up and left. A couple more weird slopey moves will put you on top. Not the best problem at the Beach, but not bad either.
Location: Faint arete to the left of Jimbo's

Description: Starting standing on good holds, move upwards to a big cruxy huck to a nice sandstone sloper. Top out the boulder. The classic warm up of the Beach. Awesome, overhanging sandstone action.
Location: Facing the main overhanging face of the Sex on the Beach boulder, it is just right of the slight arete on the left side of the face.
Protection: A pad or two, if you want

Description: Starting on the good start holds of Jimbo's, head right on good crimps and jugs. Hit a huge jug in the middle of the face and go straight up to two incut crimpers. From here, move your left hand once more into a good, slightly slopey jug, hike your feet up and do a hard move to the final hold. Ultra classic. One of the only problems in the v6 range in So iLL on jugs!
Location: The big overhanging face of the Sex on the Beach boulder, the huge block you encounter when you arrive at the Beach. The obvious line of good holds. Walk down off the boulder to get off.
Protection: Pads and spotters optional. I have fallen topping this out and completely missed the pad and fell into the sand and I didn't think it hurt at all.

Description: Proud Mary/Sex on the Beach link-up. Start on Mary, do some moves to gain the jug of Sex, finish on that. Found this on a local guy's 8a.nu page while I was looking around for obscure boulder problems...clever name...sounds fun man!
Protection: Whatever you used for Sex on the Beach, plus a pad near Proud Mary

Description: This extremely overhung line follows incut crimpers to the top of the boulder. Starting on two small jugs, either explode up and right to a small but positive crimp or reach your left hand to a bad slopey edge and lock off to the incut crimp. From here, get your left foot very high, and get left hand to a small gaston far away, using the incut intermediate next to it or just going straight to it. Grab a couple good holds and do a simple top out. As far as I know, this is the second hardest problem at the Beach. A lower start on two bad crimps may be possible when the sand is low... So iLL strong men, get out there!
Location: Right side of the overhung Sex on the Beach face. Walk off boulder to get off.

Description: Start on horizontal slopey crimps, pull the first move to a good side pull. The first move is the crux, and the problem is pretty much done after that. Holds will probably be sandy, so be careful!
Location: Wash Out starts to the right of Proud Mary.

Description: Climb the pocketed face
Location: Pocketed face to the right of Wash Out

Description: Sit start on edges and throw your left to a crimp and right to a jug.
Location: North side of boulder under brief overhang.

Description: Sit start on the arete feature. Climb up and traverse the overhand on the left, back over Brouwer Problem.
Location: Right of Brouwer Problem on arete.

Description: Low start on opposing gastons. Use some creativity to top out.
Location: Right of Boot Lip Traverse

Description: Sit Start on edges, a few options to the top.
Location: Right of You Bet Arete

Description: Sit start with your right hand on a jug and left on a pinch
Location: Far left, North side of boulder, facing the river

Description: Climb the TALL left side of the boulder that faces the river. High start on jugs.
Location: Just right of Grass Stains. Look for the jugs on the left side of the face.

Description: Climb this problem using the undercling
Location: Just right of Tall Boy

Description: Begin by using obvious pocket.
Location: Right of The Undercling Problem

Description: Climb the tall crimpy face. Highball
Location: Right of Pocket Rocket look for crimps

Description: Low start on undercling feature. Climb up and to a "softball" hold
Location: On the smaller of the two boulders. Up the middle of the face

Description: Low start on the obvious line
Location: The arete on the larger boulder next to Dancer.

Description: Start low with one hand on an undercling and one on a sidepull.
Location: Opposite side of the boulder from Mark's Problem

Description: Start as low as you can on the shelf and climb the arete
Location: On the North side of the Wasteland on a small boulder

Description: Start high on slopey holds, snag the crimp above and mantle out.
Location: Its on the left side of the middle boulder that makes up The Wasteland

Description: Beginning on The Marksman's slopey pocket, throw left and slap along the slopey rail eventually pulling the Gorham Nights mantle. Unique
Location: Locate The Marksman on the middle boulder that makes up the Wasteland

Description: Jump start to a sloper and figure out a tricky mantle.
Location: On the right side of the small arete to the right of Gorham Nights

Description: Sit start and grab on slopers. Pull through some dimple like holds to a lip.
Location: Right of The Marksman under a small overhang.

Description: Several boulder problems with variations exist.
Location: North side of the large boulder (Battery Rock) facing The Marksman

Description: Start on an arete and climb up and left. Traversing into the holds of Face Problems.
Location: The arete on the North East corner of the large boulder (Battery Rock)

Description: This is a very strange/unique problem. Dream Weaver starts inside the cave, with left hand on a positive crimp undercling under the bulge, right on on a small edge side pull. Start the problem off with a tough first move, then find some way to work your way out the cave.
Location: Located inside the cave on the bulge.

Description: The top out of Dream Weaver/Driftwood. Start on good holds and top out.
Location: Starts on good holds at the edge of the cave.

Description: Start on low slopers and traverse right towards Dream Weaver. Driftwood has the same topout as Dream Weaver.
Location: Start on low slopers to the left of the cave where Dream Weaver starts.

Description: Start right around the arête when coming into the cave, then climbing directly up, using pockets and slopey edges.
Location: Located around the arête when walking in around the arête.

Description: Climb up the face to the left of King of Smears.
Location: Directly to the left of King of Smears.
Protection: Pads and spotters. You may have to build up a landing as well.

Description: Climb through the vaguely featured face to nice holds on top. Classic V3
Location: The classic line that goes up the rather blank face.

Description: Pitch 1: Start on Unfinished Symphony but climb up and leftward towards the path of fixed gear. After the first clip climb up and leftward to anchor chains.    Pitch 2: Climb above the belay and continue through the gully to a safety bolt. Continue by angling up and right, then go around the exposede arete and up to the anchor. (most common route for pitch 2)    Pitch 2 Variation: "5.12a" From the belay, traverse rightward to the first bolt. From there crank through the roof and follow the arete to the anchor.
Protection: natural small to medium gear with bolts.
FirstAscent: Jim Thurmond, Alan Carrier, Eric Ulner 1987

Description: Pitch 1-5.8 Starts about 30 feet left of the big off width. Start in the left facing dihedral with a thin crack. Follow crack system up and to the right. Go around corner and rig a hanging belay here. Pitch 2-5.10a ascend the ramp dihedral to a safety bolt and top out above.
Location: Follow cliff line left ward till you see the off-width. Past here about 30 feet. Easy walk off or rap from chains on the sport route to you right.
Protection: Mixed gear of varied sizes. Cams for first pitch. Not a bad idea to have a couple tri cams forr belay. Sling the horn and 1 quick draw for pitch 2.
FirstAscent: (5.8/A.4)Steve Nelson/Adam Ggrowsky/Mike Azrin mid 70s.1st Free Lead Sean Sucras,Clay Erickson(installed bolt on 2nd pitch) 1984

Description: Its the sport route that climbs a thin seam
Location: Begins 5 feet left of Fear of Flying

Description: big long offwidth crack, that gets bulgy and dirty near the top. some real nice sit down rests near the top. finishes out with some face climbing. took me a while to figure out offwidth moves, but it was fun figuring it out. might want to wear pants and tape ankles or wear high top shoes (i've lost some skin to this one). i've only top roped this route using several trees at the top for anchors.
Location: on the left wall of the dihedral, to the left of "Cave City"
Protection: I top roped it using long pieces of webbing to anchor to the trees at the top. to lead a person would need several large cams for the offwidth.

Description: Deep dihedral crack. fairly straightforward climbing. a fall while leading could be bad. several spots you'll have to squeeze through.
Location: the dihedral crack to the right of Fear of Flying.
Protection: i used the trees at the top of the cliff for a top rope anchor. you need two long (60') pieces of webbing. to lead you would need a varied rack.

RouteName: 2 Six-Packs, 1/5 of Scotch & A Full Moon
Description: Begin with some high bouldering up a 5.5ish looking slab. Reach a 6ish foot protruding boulder with a flat top. Climb on top of that, Climb through 4 bolts to reach the top.
Location: Sport route to the right of Cave City

Description: A fun toprope.
Location: a little to the left on the wall that is directly in front of the trail. Identified by the big plate that looks somewhat like Africa or South America (i could see both).
Protection: bolt anchors at the top for toprope. could be lead but the trad lead rating i think is an R or X.

Description: A few starting moves will get you to a large ledge, where you can place gear in the crack. Edges and jugs through bolts. Clipping stances are usually pretty good. Finish straight to the final horns; the chains are on the wall above the finish.
Location: Right of Africa, left of the large chimney/crack, start up on moderate edges and flakes.

Description: A nice first trad climb. good stances for placing gear and good gear.
Location: obvious crack that runs up the middle of the face at the end of the trail. it's to the right of the Africa.
Protection: small to medium cams and nuts. a good horn to sling around 2/3 the way up the route. there is an anchor the the left on the ledge at the top but NOT one directly above the climb.

Description: Thin and strenuous, bouldery start. Fun
Location: Moving left, it's the 1st sport route.  Look for the high 1st clip.  Stay right of the 2nd and 3rd clips.

Description: Climb the face, clipping the two bolts as you move working into the crack. Work you way through the crack as it widens and becomes slightly overhung. Climb over the ledge and reach the bolted anchor.
Location: This mixed route is the first one you come to as you approach from the church. Locate the route that has one climb the face and transition into a narrow, then widening crack.
Protection: Two bolts and mid sized cams to the anchor.

Description: Begin on High Flying Bird and pull over the first bulge. From here work up and right, skipping the open book feature of H.F.B. and a word towards a bolt in a "honey comb" featured spot. Clip this bolt and pull the last strenuous bulge to reach the anchor.
Location: Start on High Flying Bird and after pulling the first budge, climb up and right.
Protection: Mixed gear with 3 bolts to an anchor

Description: Begin by climbing up the short face, clipping two bolts as you go, and eventually reach the top
Location: It starts on the ledge about 10ish feet right of the 4th class scramble
Protection: 2 quick draws and top out the route

Description: This is hardly climbed so bring a brush to clean it up. Climb the short face.
Location: Starts 2 feet right of Number 35

Description: Climb the vertical crack on the left side of the steep overhang.
Location: Starts 10 feet to the right of Short Stuff

Description: From the belay ledge, traverse leftward 15 feet and go up to the bolt located at the base of a gully. Climb the left side of the gully and go straight over the bulge to the top.     Variation (5.7) Stay with the crack at the top of the 2nd pitch.
Location: Begin at the belay ledge

Description: Begin from the belay ledge, and go straight up. Move through the center of a gully and clip the bolt near the ledge. A long, easy slab tops it out.
Location: Begin at the belay ledge

Description: Pitch: 1 (5.11) From the belay ledge, traverse rightward around the corner to the first bolt. An interesting upward reach move takes you to the second bolt. Continue about 25ft rightward across a ledge system to a fixed, hanging belay.    Pitch: 2 (5.7) Mantle above the belay and look up and right for the last bolt. Angle up and left to the top.
Location: While looking up at the upper wall, look up at the lower left part of the wall and locate a grassy ledge. This serves as the fixed belay station.

Description: Climb the chimney crack to the left of Schoolyard Blues
Location: Chimney crack to the left of Schoolyard Blues

Description: Fun face climb with a wild roof!
Climb the large rounded arete with a psychological crux at 2/3 height
Location: around the corner from the fully bolted "Schoolyard Blues" (about 70 feet)
Protection: 3 quickdraws plus some medium sized gear

Description: Climb the crack system "gully" protecting when necessary and eventually top the bluff out.
Location: the crack just right of Ghosts and Goblins
Protection: Trad gear of varied sizes + bolted anchor

Description: If necessary, use the oak tree to access the slab. Climb the slab to the right facing dihedral crack inside of the overhang. Once in, climb with the feature and top out on the left.     Jeff stirred the wasps, John made them mad, Brian got nailed!
Location: 30ish feet to the right of Ghosts and Goblins
Protection: Trad gear of varied sizes + bolted anchor
FirstAscent: Jeff Scheff, John Payne, Brian Vana 1985

Description: Ascend the right leaning seam that goes up a slab and continue with it as it becomes vertical, followed by going through a small open book gully. Continue until you reach a small ledge before you reach the top.
Location: Starts 10ish feet to the right of Big Sting
Protection: Trad gear of varied sizes + bolted anchor

Description: Route on bulge just left of Dos Equis.  A bouldery start leads to relaxed climbing with not exactly ideal gear placements; get creative with mid size cams and nuts.  Joins with Dos Equis last two bolts to the anchors.
Location: Just left of Dos Equis.   Rap off dos Equis anchors
Protection: Doubles of Small to mid size cams and nuts. 2 QD plus anchors

Description: Head right look for the two X-like features in the rock about 15 feet up. A waist-high roof is underneath. Goes straight up.

Ascend the slab/face next to a tree 12ish feet left of the actual bolt line. Traverse into the route and make careful moves until you traverse under an overhung arete. Ascend the upper arete and eventually reach the anchor.
Location: The sport route to the right of Those Bear Memorial

Description: Pitch 1: (5.8) Climb up the gully until you reach the base of the arete. Build a belay here.    Pitch 2: (5.10a) Traverse the dihedral crack (don't forget to clip the bolt) up and left to the next gully and belay at the tree.    Descent: 4th class out from here, or rappel from the tree
Location: Begins at the base of the gully to the right of Jack In The Green
Protection: Set of cams and nuts + 1 QD

Description: Ascend the shallow, easy looking gully above a low roof.     "Go Ahead, Make 'Em Dance"-E. Ulner
Location: About 50 feet right of Hypothermia. The route ascends the gully.

Description: Short, fun and slightly fingery route near the end of the bluff
Location: Third sport route from the far right side of Cedar Bluff

Description: Follow the bolts to reach the anchor
Location: First route to the right of St. Louis Graffiti

Description: Climb the leftward angling dihedral feature
Location: The dihedral feature to the left of Oily Easter Beaver
Protection: Trad gear of varied sizes to the anchor
FirstAscent: John Payne Greg Simons, Frank Borzager

Description: Climb the face while following the bolt line.
Location: First bolted route to the right of April Fool

Description: Enjoyable slab route. Starts with a crack in the middle. When that ends, you work your way left a tiny bit to a crack on that side.
Location: A short ways to the east of "St Louis Graffiti." A short ways west of the 2nd class walk-up.
Protection: Cams .3-.75, two bolts + bolted anchor.     The anchors are accessible via the walkup to the east. You'll probably want somebody down at the bottom of the route to shout up to you so you know when you're in the right spot. Also, probably a good idea to anchor yourself to a tree in some way before heading out on the ledge to set up a top rope.
FirstAscent: John Payne, according to Vertical Heartland guidebook

Description: Name totally made up (certainly not a FA but not in the guidebook, though I thought it worthy of description). Grade is a tired 4th-day-on estimate, so probably soft. From good ledges at the back of the cave, move straight out the cave to a close pair of positive ledges. From here, go to a slopey 2 finger LH pocket/pinch, then make a big RH move to a solid 4-finger pocketed ledge, probably cutting feet. Make another big move with the LH to a similarly positive pocket and begin the romp to the top on giant incut pockets.
Location: LH side of cave, probably the first chalked line on the left. The left hand pocket should be obvious (there's a little 1 finger divot just left of it).

Description: Name totally made up (certainly not a FA but not in the guidebook, though I thought it worthy of description). Grade is a tired 4th-day-on estimate, so probably soft. From ledge at back of cave, slap to pinch on lip of the low roof tier. Use foot trickery of choice to bring LH to flat sidepull. Slap RH to another pinch, then move up on good ledges.
Location: Right of the pocket problem in the shallow cave. Comes out of the low roof near the dihedral where the shallow cave meets the tall cave, then moves out and left to top out by whichever way is easiest.

Description: Sidepulls galore. Beta I attempted: start sitting on sidepull edges/pinches, throwing high to more sidepull edges (good LH, semi-slopey RH) before moving to better holds above. Name totally made up (not in the guidebook, though I thought it worthy of description).
Location: Just right of the dihedral on the left end of the tall cave portion. Middle sidepulls at face level should be obvious. Start sitting with opposing sidepulls (there's another sidpull left of the LH start hold).

Description: From a sit at the starting edge, move through slopers, pinches, and an undercling to reach a pair of incut edges above. From there, move out left to a similar, smaller, pair of edges. Figure out the moves straight up to the big mouth-shaped ledge above, then top out through easier roof climbing above.
Location: To the right of the compression problem. Start sitting on the obvious edge low with an incut LH and flat RH. Moves through an obvious undercling and two incut edges above to thin crimps out left, eventually hitting the giant ledge above them.

Description: This is a nice little cave with the roof ranging in height from 4-12 feet.  Always stays dry and there are a handful of eliminates/problems possible - enough for a session or two.
Location: Walk to the far right hand side of Cedar Bluff and this is what you will find.

Description: Sart on same jugs as the v4. Go left & reach around to the other face to match on sloping but positive edge. Top out Left.
Location: This boulder defines the right side of a dihedral which starts about 30 paces west of the bouldering cave. There are 2 cool v4ish problems on the side which is (at first) hidden from view.

Description: 1st problem on overhung face. Jugs to start, left hand to fat slopey pinch, and top out the bulge.
Location: This boulder defines the right side of a dihedral which starts about 30 paces west of the bouldering cave. There are 2 cool v4ish problems on the side which is (at first) hidden from view.

Description: SDS just right of unnamed v3. Pinch, move to sidepull in big hueco and top out left in slopers or right in small, left-facing pockets.
Location: This boulder defines the right side of a dihedral which starts about 30 paces west of the bouldering cave. There are 2 cool v4ish problems on the side which is (at first) hidden from view.

Description: Facing "the son" directly to your left against the corner are the under cling starting holds. hit the huge block jug and up and right to the pad and a half flake, big stretch right again to a good hold then mantle the son.
Location: Head up the trail from the church and hang right at the bluff line, they are about 20 ft before you hit the cave, in an overhang.

Description: Start matched low on the right side of the arete, throw around and out left to the bumpy rail, out high right to crimp seam and match, then shoot for the flat jug at the top, mantel.
Location: Head up the trail from the church and hang right at the bluff line, they are about 20 ft before you hit the cave, in an overhang.

Description: Start on the two jugs next to "The Son" start, throw up to the pinch then to the jug on the lip, hit the high sloper and reach for the slopy rail with the seam in it, fire for the side pull Jug and finish the mantel.
Location: Head up the trail from the church and hang right at the bluff line, they are about 20 ft before you hit the cave, in an overhang.

Description: Start with two jugs around head high all the way to the left of the wall. Traverse to the right until you reach the end of the wall. My route included a mix of crimps, side pulls, and some slopers. **All cracks where mortar is missing between the stones are off limits** Only features on the faces of the rocks can be used.
Location: This is on the south west wall. If you are standing at the light on Wentworth and 18th St, it is the wall you see when your back is to the skyline.

Description: Start with sidepull and undercling. Crux is getting to the upper banister crack. Feet are tricky.  A surprisingly good climb for what it is.
Location: Follow the area page directions to the wall. This will be in the middle of the wall.
Protection: pad(s) or the trash cushion underneath the route

Description: An old chimney on the side of a school, built out of stone rough enough to climb.
Location: Pull into the school lot, you'll see the route. The only way down is to downclimb.

Description: Not quite as high as the West Side Bridges but more technical.
Protection: 1 pad for up to 12 brick layers. Anything higher double stack pads.

Description: Besides Glazed Doughnut, this is one of the hardest bridge routes. The mortar lines are really shallow and forces you to grab the features of the stone.     Beta. Shark tooth in the middle. Trails to the left.
Protection: ! pad or 2, depending on how high you get.

Description: Don't let the mortar cracks fool you.    There's a good grove for crimping every 2 stone layers. Not every stone layer.   This bridge support has been sprayed with a glaze coating to help prevent weathering. This is bad because it makes some spots smooth, this is also good because the route might be to easy without it.   Named after Kevin fell from the arc onto his chalk bucket that contained loose chalk. His face was powdery.
Protection: 1 pad will do if your climbing to the arc. If your going past the arc you will need to double stack your mats.

Description: The moves on this problem are not as repetitive as chalk dust.     Named after Kevin falling onto his unopened coconut water, causing it to spray and soak the pad.
Protection: 1 pad, double stack pads if your passing the arc.

Description: You can choose to boulder to the top or top rope.
Location: Once at the top you can walk down a steep hill, or repel.
Protection: Pads, anchors are at the top but they look pretty old and rusty.

Description: Start 4' to the right of the plastered crack.   Climb upward until you're roughly bridge level then start going right.
Protection: If bouldering 3 pads and 2 people. One person to spot, the other to adjust pads.   If trad climbing bring roughly 3 small sized cams.

Description: Crux is a high left right in the middle of the route
Location: it is the second route from the left

Description: Getting over the roof
Location: left side of the water fall

Description: crux is getting over the roof
Location: right side of the water fall

Description: Crux is right after the beginning
Location: far right of crag

Description: reference pictures for route. A fall could be bad since the ground is slanted and goes into the water. The wall takes over a week to dry after a rain and even then its still fairly wet.
Location: Middle section of the wall that is to the left of the waterfall

Description: Sit start on the vertical arete of the tall boulder and make literally one move before mantling
Work your way up about two moves before mantling on the flat part of the boulder
Location: The shallow dihedral right under the flat part of the tall boulder

Description: Sit start with the first move as the crux. Make an awkward throw to a ledge and work your way up from there.
Crouch start on the two deep crimps with a right flag. The first move is the crux: left hand to another deep crimp above. Then, right foot step right arm up, and catch the top with your left hand.
Location: Near the California Blue Line stop, in the courtyard between the apartment highrise and Colectivo Coffee. There are two climbable boulders; this is on the West side of the taller of the two.

Description: Start on the right side of the boulder, without using the lip traverse left around the arete and top out on the overhanging far side
Location: The shorter of the two climbable boulders
Protection: No pads, you'll never be more than 5 feet off the ground.

Description: The middle has some sharp crimpy holds. Some of the holds nearby are loose so double check what you are grabbing.
Location: Under the fallen tree

Description: The pictures show where the hands are. The feet are open, but that being said the rock is so crumbly that solid foot holds are spread out a little bit.
Location: Refer to the pictures for the start and end of the route.

Description: The small pockets on this wall are the perfect size for your middle and index fingers. Climb the pockets to the top out.  Video of First Ascent
Location: On the west side of Carlson Tower balcony, along Kedzie. Look for the small pockets right off of East the side of the street. Just North of the river.

Description: Top out on the piller then there’s and easy down climb to the top of the wall then down climb the wall.
Great feet all the way through
Location: Northwest corner of the underpass bridge. Start low on pillar using compression then go all the up to top out. Decent problem with moves you probably won't see at the gym.

Description: Traverse the front of the cave. Start by sliding down into the left hand opening as far as you can, then go up and right, finishing by mantling onto the rock pedestal on the climbers right of the right entrance.  Avoid the rail marked on the main photo (use the lip of the cave above it), its pretty hollow sounding!

Work your way out through the entrance of the cave, mantle and finish on top of the rock. There are at least three jugs, and a majority of the route is a large rail. Any and all rock inside the cave is on. Don't use the rail marked in the main page's photo, it's chossy and let's not break it. There is a pretty solid heel hook near the end of the route, kind of fun.
Location: Enter the cave through the wider opening, the start of the route is immediately to the left on the pillar.

Description: The crux is attempting not to dab. I had to use a lot of heel hooks to accomplish this. The route would be pretty nice if the dirt mounds weren't in the cave. It is a scrunched up route with some awkward moves. Any and all rock inside the cave is on. Route starts further back in the cave, and then follows the same line as The Great Escape. Traverse the side of the cave to the left and out, the rails toward the back of the cave seem to be constantly moist so chalk is nice.    If you are climbing this route, you must be desperate for a climb!
Location: Once you enter the cave, there are two small holes/paths towards the back. The route starts on the right of the hole that is on the left.

Description: See picture for what's on. Along the bottom of the wall, the concavity and the rail just below it (a few mm wide) are also on for different beta.
See picture for what's on. Small hands match more easily.
See picture for what's on. End is anticlimactic.
See picture for what's on. For the starred holds, try to avoid using the tops. Crux is at the end. Can also be done in reverse.
See picture for what's on. Do whatever to get to the start.
See picture for what's on. Along the bottom of the wall, the concavity and the rail just below it (a few mm wide) are also on. Crux is the start.
Use the words on the school sign to get to the top.
Location: Bateman Elementary School Sign

Description: This boulder is made of concrete conglomerate rock that lays on an old railway structure. It tops out at over 15 ft and is a slab-style boulder until the very end. The name "Nutri Grain comes from the very crumbly concrete rock that makes up the boulder. This one will take some problem solving and make sure to be careful, the rock isn't all that strong so don't beat on it. The Crux comes just before the top out; look for a small indent in the rock for your right foothold then get a side pull on the arete to bring your left foot up just before you top out.Crash Pads and Spotters HIGHLY recommended! This boulders top out is pretty high and there is a risk of serious injury with and especially without spotters and pads.
Location: This boulder is located just off the Illinois prairie path in Bellwood. punch "Madison St & Cernan Dr Bellwood IL 60164" into your maps and park on the street once you arrive. look for the railroad overpass and large concrete structure just next to the path off the road. There is an already small established path right off the IL prairie trail, take that and the boulder is just to your right as you enter.Exact Coordinates: 41°52'43.6"N 87°52'06.8"W

Description: This is a "Figure 8" traverse. Start off matching both hands on the north west point of the rock at the blue mark with feet on the green marks. Traverse right using the crack at the red line mark and various holds below it. Do not use a hold above the red line. Work your way under the middle cave and out to the south east face of the rock, avoiding any hold above the red line. Work around the south face and traverse left along the south west face to the cave again, following the same guidelines. Route is complete when hands and feet make it to the north starting point.
Protection: Traverse stays low. No additional protection needed.

Description: Follow the obvious line to the top
use only the left arete/crack and right crack (blue line crack) to compress and hug your way up this boulder! feet - whatever you can use!
Pockets only
Dyno to the top from the start holds
On the same boulder as Rock-a-bye Baby  Stand start using only top ring and bottom ring of the Boulder. Start jugs on right and traverse the whole and end at start holds.   Good warm up boulder.
Triangular ledge is bomber.
Location: Climber's side of big boulder. See picture for start. Left hand in a pocket, right hand on neighboring ledge. Big deadpoint to triangular ledge, then top out. No other holds used. If you are tall and/or have big wingspan, deadpoint to big pocket instead of ledge.

Description: West face of "Big boulder." Sit start, climb pockets only, all other holds are barred!
Start with hands on red circled holds. Use a combination of the purple hand holds to work up to the black hold and top out. All features not circled are off limits for hand holds. All feet are good.
Location: West face of largest boulder

Description: This route requires creativity. Purple indicates right hand, red indicates left hand, and black is feet. **No hand matches** except for on the top out. Sit start in the crack on indicated hand and foot holds. Move up and left while keeping your feet to the right of the arch. Feet can never touch the left side. Crux will require finding proper feet to reach the top left pocket and a big mantle finish. Top out is to the right of the final top hold.
Location: West face of the largest boulder.
Protection: Possible pad for the last two moves.

Description: Jams only. Somewhere around a BD#1 or BD#2. Probably good for learning how to handjam, as there are decent feet and it is less than vertical.
Location: Slab side of big boulder. Go up the big crack. Jams only until top out, though you can continue to use the crack to mantle - probably a V0 if you do.

Description: Handjams only!
Location: Climbers' side of big boulder. Up the obvious butt-looking crack (~BD#2). Spread 'em and get your feet on the rocks then put in one handjam to start. Handjams only until mantle. Bonus points if you don't crimp-jam on the starting hold. Topout on the horn.

Description: use small pockets on the wall
Location: start on the pockets on the arête by the quarry and top out.

Description: Start on the opposite side of Ring Around the Toesies and top out at the start of Ring Around the Toesies.

Hands start on the West face, toe hook the ledge on the East face. Work your way underneath the arch to the East side of the boulder. Do NOT use any section of the boulder below the circled areas in the photos.
Heel hook around the boulder then rock up on your heel to top out. Hands start on SW face of the boulder. Do NOT use any section of the boulder below the hand start.

Sit start with hands on the bottom two blue marks and feet on the green marks. Mantle up to grab the small crack circled blue. Your feet can only touch the two original footholds and the two starting handholds. Dyno to the top, directly in the middle, grabbing hold of a small flake that sits about 8 inches in from the edge. Do not grab the edge of the top rock! After grabbing, your feet can go anywhere to top out.
Location: South face of the large boulder

Description: Start on a left hand crimp and a right hand sloper with a heel down and to the left. right hand throw to a slopey crimp rock up on your left heel and throw left hand to a small sloper rail. Then right hand bump to a sharp crimp. stand on your left foot and move your left hand to the final sloper. Easy top out.

Sit start at the obvious left crimp and right sidepull crimp as seen on the photo's. Follow the line directly up and through the face. Throw a high right heel to make your way up, but no standing on that same right ledge to help you top out. You gotta climb that slab!

Basically the goal is to move up left from the start. You have to find your way around and over the bulge. That is the crux of the problem. Start with a left hand on the sloping ledge, and right hand on the low crimp. Sit start again, may be a little less of a sit if you are shorter.  This one is a bit more contrived. Only use the low right foot for a bomber heel. Then don't use that ledge after. Also, only use the right hand hold to begin the boulder, it is off for a foot. I've x'd out the areas on the photo. Harder if you are short.

Start on the low left incut. This is where your left hand and left heel goes. Then you have a high right hand on the sloper, you have a small buldge where you can catch the sloper more securely. Pulling up into the start is the first hard part. Then match the sloper, shift the hands, find a better left heel, then big drive up into The Dark Side finish.   Just don't use The Dark Side's starting crimp for any reason, or right most juggy crimp. Anything below the waist foot wise is on. The photo's have more info.   Bring out your inner Jedi!
Straight up the main column of the SE face of the bridge. Only the limestone is on.

Climb up the corner of the SE face of the bridge. Only the sandstone cornerstones are on. it may be possible to do without using the short line of cornerstones under the mantle but I couldn't work it out right now.
Location: SE face of the bridge.

Description: Traverse of SE wall starting low and working uphill/east using the limestone holds. Sandstone top cap is off (except for easternmost pillar).
Location: Start in the downhill corner of the SE face.
Protection: You won't get up too high and there is grass to land on

Description: Only use the sandstone cornerstones on the vertical arete and top out on the mantle. The crack is off, and the pipe/conduit is off. Once sent, either climb onto the bridge deck and walk back down or downclimb using the limestone holds to your right.

Chicago Park District may not have planned for this to be part of the climbing at Steelworkers Park, but it is too obvious and appealing to be ignored.  Surprisingly nice, if short, you climb up the fingers crack to the top of the ore wall, where you can enjoy a nice view downtown and to the active steel works in Indiana. Most of the route you can cheat the crack a bit with bonus features on the sides, especially the two boreholes, but towards the top you are committed into the crack for a couple moves.  Bits of iron sticking out give an easy topout up and left, but don't forget to place a final directional cam or clip the I-beam if you are anchoring off the main barrel.  You can climb up the regular wall and set a TR in the same way. The bits of gravel at the very edge of the crack have the potential to pop, but mostly feels fine, and you can place gear solidly into it.
Location: At the right/eastern edge of the climbing mulch, it's the obvious splitter crack.
Protection: BD#0.5, as many as you want.  Optional #3 placement, could also get away with 0.4s, maybe up to 0.75? Slings to anchor off the top to the left, or rig an anchor off the I-Beam.  Possibly tricams or wires if you only have a couple cams?

Description: Sit start on right hand crimp rail and left hand sloper. Climb up and right using various slopers and crimps and make a committing move to a final jug. Watch out for dabs on this lowball!
Location: On the north facing side of the boulder.

Description: Sit start with left hand side pull crimp and right hand low on the arete. Hard to get off the ground. Bump up the right hand and make your way straight up. All of the arete is good. I tried to avoid using any of the holds from "tar and feathered".
Location: Northwest arete of the boulder. Directly to the right of "tar and feathered"

Description: Tell 'em you're with Mac is a 255 ft (77.7 m) section of wall (within the Pacific Union Traverse crag) that runs along Kinzie Avenue between cross streets Hart Ave. and Wolcott Ave. This route was broken down into thirteen 20’ sectors, based off of the metal poles that line the Pacific Union rail at the top of the wall. The distance between any two markers is approximately 10 ft. Start at the metal gate on Hart St and traverse east to the Wolcott Ave. There are two major boulder problems as cruxes. However, the real challenge is linking 255 feet of crimps, slopers, gastons, underclings, side pulls, and small footholds without getting pumped. Finding a midway no-hands rest just before the first major crux (140 ft mark) is key to sending this beast of a route. (First Ascent: Brian T. Murphy, July 29, 2020)
Location: Tell 'em you're with Mac is a section of wall (within the Pacific Union Traverse crag) that runs along Kinzie Avenue between cross streets Hart Ave. and Wolcott Ave.

Description: A beautiful, one of a kind continuous roof crack hidden like a true gem amidst the beauty of Cedar Lakes western shore.  No, really, it's worth it. Starts with great Fists/Hands for several moves before a challenging final not-quite-fingers-not-quite-Hands-battle before exiting the cave to a hang and drop. Two to three pads are enough.  Bring a towel if it’s seeping it can be dried out in a day.  If you see it dry, don’t hesitate.  Oh, and bring a spider stick
Location: Landmarks are your friend here.  Honestly, finding this thing was half the fun, so enjoy the hike.  This is located between the two points of the Wolfden loop trail. Around 1.5 miles in, just after passing beneath a large overhanging Chossy wall, focus on the cliffline.  Look for a natural arch key hole at the top of a boulder, followed by a very clean, recessed area of vertical wall. Just past this, keep looking at the base of the cliff for a small cave opening directly behind a large Ash tree.  If you see a large, egg shaped boulder then you have just passed it!  Turn around and look closer.  The cave drops down below eye level looking from the trail, so keep your eyes peeled!
Protection: 2-3 pads or you could genuinely just have an active spotter.   Anti-spider spells are key here

Description: Climb the tricky water runnel up to a roof.  Do some creative stemming to pull the roof and reach the anchors.
Location: Just left of the prominent dihedral.
Protection: Four bolts to a two bolt anchor with quick links.

Description: 5.9 climbing to crux move at the roof when traversing right to the anchors on Middle Face. Very exposed move, and has potential for pendulum swing into opposite wall. Not sure if anyone has climbed this route before. When traversing I knocked off a large rock that almost hit my belayer.
Location: The crack between Middle Face and Left Face. Lower on bolts on Middle Face.
Protection: Set of Cams #.5 - 3, set of nuts. Save #3 for the traverse.

Description: Several bolts of pumpy pocket climbing leads to a mediocre rest.  The crux is moving past the final bolt to the anchors and is difficult to read.
Location: Starts about ten feet right of the large dihedral.
Protection: Four bolts and a two bolt anchor with quick links.

Description: This is an enjoyable climb that ascends the right side of the dugout.  It is comparable in difficulty to the Middle Face.  However, the anchors are inexplicably located about ten feet past the logical end of the route, requiring the use of a rusty upward driven bolt to aid to the anchors.  The sandy boulder problem this bolt protects is probably possible (grade is an estimate), but not nearly as quality as the rest of the route.  A lower set of anchors would decrease the grade to about 11D and increase the overall quality.
Location: Rightmost route in the dugout
Protection: Five bolts to a 2 bolt anchor with quick links.

Description: Work along the left side of the grooved arete using a variety of holds on solid stone.  A fun climb that's more challenging than it appears from the ground.  If reach is an issue for certain sections, climbing towards the gully will yield a way around.
Location: After crossing the creek coming from the main Amphitheater, this is the first route on the right going towards the large capped roof.  Begins to the left of the arete in the gully.
Protection: 8 glue ins. 6 + anchors w/ quick links

Description: This is the large arching crack on the left side of the main amphitheater wall.  Large to medium sized gear will protect most of the route.  You can lower off of the sport route that meets the crack to avoid the somewhat chossy finish.  To get your money's worth, you can lower off of the anchors for Inception.

The route is split in half by a no hands ledge in the dihedral.  The bottom and top are of comparable difficulty, but with very different styles.  After the initial boulder problem, head straight up until the third bolt.  The route initially went straight up to a series of sloping horizontals above the bolt and then left.  Since then, a critical crimp has been considerably downsized.  It is probably easier now to do the bouldery traverse below the bolt, join the dihedral and climb up to the bolt.      After the rest ledge, head left and enjoy quality overhanging slopers to the anchors.  Be sure to give a soft catch for the upper crux, as you tend to swing into the slab below.
Location: Left most route leaving the shared first bolt on the left side of the main wall.
Protection: Seven bolts to bolted anchors with rap rings.

Description: Begin low and left in the amphitheater, work up and right through the first two bolts. Above the third bolt is the first bolt of legacy. From here follow the bolts through a series of side pulls, slopers, and edges to reach the final section. A technical slab wait for you at the top. Get psyched!
Location: Begins in the left corner of the Amphitheater and work the route that goes up the middle. Refer to photo

Description: Extremely fun.  Head right after pulling the low roof and follow the ledge for several bolts.  Get a good rest before embarking on the quality overhang above.  Stay on your toes for several bolts of slopey, bouldery climbing.      Difficult to get back on after taking the huge whipper at the end of the crux.  A tighter catch helps there.
Protection: nine bolts to a two bolt anchor with rap rings.  Due to how far the route traverses, the bottom four or five bolts are best cleaned on top rope to prevent a dangerous swing.

Description: Slightly longer and more difficult than inception.  Follow inception until you get on top of the worm-like sloping feature with a crack running along the bottom.  Rather than clipping the sixth bolt on inception, clip a bolt to your right, and traverse this feature to the right for about 15 feet and head up out the roof. Three cruxes of increasing difficulty separated by mediocre rests will take you to the anchors.    As with Inception, it is HIGHLY recommended that you clean the first five or six draws on TR to avoid a dangerous swing.  It is easiest if you clean the anchors and all of the draws that you can reach easily while lowering, then toprope it to get the first ones.  Alternately, on the last go of the day, you can leap frog the draws on the traverse, cleaning as you go, then get the rest on lower.
Location: Rightmost of the routes sharing the common start.
Protection: Eleven bolts to a 2 bolt anchor with rap rings.

Description: This route follows a crack system just left of the chimney on the right side of the amphitheater.  Climb the layback crack and plug some gear at the top of it to protect the bouldery moves to the first bolt.  Crank through the steep crux, place some gear, and relax once you can stem on the wall behind you.  The face above is bolted and moderate, but a little scary due to the amount of dirt and lichen, as well as the ledge below.      Rebolted May 2012.
Protection: Some gear and several bolts.  Rap from Tree.

Description: This is the dihedral chimney on the right side of the amphitheater.    I know almost nothing about this route.  The name was provided by Jim.  The grade is a complete guess, only included because a grade is required to submit the route to the site.
Information on this route was from Jim, who has not climbed the route in a long time.  It follows a short roof crack on the prominent arete of Moon Rock.
Protection: There is at least one bolt on the route, which should be considered suspect.  There is also some natural pro.  Not sure about anchors.

Description: Follows the arete right of the roof crack.  Any additional info on the route would be appreciated.
This line is deceptively slopey and difficult.  The crux in the middle of the route is very cool but hard to read.  Pumpy.
Location: This is the right-most route on Moon rock.
Protection: Five bolts to bolted anchors with rap rings.  Be sure to clip the low bolt on the ledge, which makes the falls a little cleaner. Clipping the second isn't too hard, but a fall would be bad.  A stick clip is recommended.

Description: The easier variation of Ralphie's Ruse. Fun pocket pulling ties your back into the main route.
Location: 3ish feet right of Ralphie's Ruse

Description: Follow crimps past the first few bolts and easier climbing to the anchors.   Variation:  Climb the tricky pockets ten feet right of the start, clipping three bolts, and join Ralphie's at the fourth bolt. makes for a better warm-up once you figure out the sequence.  FA: Phillip Carrier 2011
Location: This is the left of the newly bolted lines on Moon Rock.  It begins about 15 feet right of the prominent arete.
Protection: Five bolts to a two bolt anchor with rap rings

Description: After a few bolts of surprisingly tricky climbing on big holds, head right out the overhang and up into the large water groove.
Location: Start about 25 feet left of Shout under a roof. This is the only route on the wall with new bolts.
Protection: Five bolts to a two bolt anchor with rap rings.

Description: Climb the prominent arete, which is sandy and tricky, up to a sandy ledge below a roof.  Do some big moves to gain jugs at the lip and make the clip.  A difficult boulder problem on tiny crimps and pockets gets you to the anchors.
Location: The obvious arete right of Phillip's Overhang.
Protection: Five bolts to a bolted anchor.  Be sure to use a long draw on the fifth bolt, which is just over the lip.  Falling at the crux with a short draw will shred your rope.

Description: Absolute classic, one of the best moderate climbs in the canyon. Sit start low in the crack and make your way to the top out.
Small roof with great holds along the left arete.
Location: Right side of the hallway, about halfway in.

Description: Start in the corner on the right wall, low on the large rail. Work straight up until you're chest is wedged in the off-width and top out onto the moss carpet. Good luck on the down climb, it might just be the same route.
Location: To the right and downhill from the opening of the hallway.

Description: This climb is easily identified by a bright red, almost rainbowy iron mark right in the center of the face. Start low on the jagged iron and follow the positive seam to the ledge halfway up the face.
Location: Walk down right from Passage to Green and take a right. Bright red rock makes this climb obvious.

Description: Wow it's mossy, but there's just enough rock available to make this climbable. Center flakes on the uphill side of the slab face.
Location: Directly uphill from Mineral Spirits. Opposite side of Fall Silent boulder.

Description: Sit start matched using the right side of the low flake for hands. Use the various crimpers on the face to make it up to the lip and top out.
Location: Opposite side of mossy feet boulder, uphill from Mineral Spirits.

Description: Start with a right gaston on a small crimp feature out right and the left on the obvious sloper rail in the middle. Have fun figuring out the feet and make it up to the top. Do not use the large protruding boulder underneath for feet.
Location: This route is located facing the river. If you hike along the east side of the river, this route should be pretty easily visible.

Description: Dihedral crack.
Location: Hike down the west cliff line until this obvious route jumps out at you.

Description: Start in the first crack right of the "L" and work up the crack from there.
Location: First obvious crack to the right of the "L".

Description: Start in the third crack feature of the Metro Wall and follow it to the ledge for the topout
Location: Right of Red Line

Description: Sit start on the small over hung face on the cliff line right of the tall slabs.
