Big jug ladder right around the corner from late for the train.

This problem is on the front left corner of the boulder if you are facing the creek, sit start off a sloper to a small crimp, then move the left hand to another crimp then the right hand to the top, short problem, but fun to work out.
Location: Read the previous description

Description: Climb straight up over a couple of overhangs.     This is the route I did back in 1965. It wasn't V4-John Gill
Location: locate the overhangs

Description: In the middle of the wall you will see a V-shaped notch beneath an overhang resting on a smooth undercut bed of rock. this is the Persian Wall. Climb, if you can, straight up the wall, through the notch, and over the overhang at it's widest part 45' to the top.
Location: Read the directions already listed

Description: The problem starts at the bottom right of the cave climbs to meet the other wall, then goes up to a slab top out filled with lots of moss and moisture.
Location: Read previous description on how to get there

Description: Right arete
Left of Chugga Chug
In front of the tree, left of Can't Stand the Train
Left of when my train pulls in.
First vertical route on the right side of the face.
Start on the right arete and traverse the crack to the left and finish topped out on the left arete.
Location: Downhill from metro wall, start far right on the jug on the arete in the crack.

Description: Start with left on the arete and right on lower crimper and work your way up the face.
Location: This boulder is in front of and downhill from the cave. The route is on the left arete of the face opposite the cave

Description: Start low in the crack and work your way up and right on the slopey pockets.
Location: Find the low crack on the far left.

Description: Find some funky side pulls and teeny feet and make it up to the top.
Location: Right of Resistance is futile.

Description: Fun slab on the rounded arete.
First of the easy slabs on the left of the face
Center line
Right line of the easy slabs
Wow these holds are tiny, don't let the feet pop at the top, it's a weird fall.
Start with hands low on the small rail and the teeny crimper. Right of Balance of Terror, also terrifying balance on this one.
Sit start and pull through good holds to a slopey topout
Location: Leftmost boulder problem

Description: Harder then the problem to the left, great slopey top out
Location: A few feet to the right of Sit Start V1

Description: Start on decent edges, climb up and out through a slopey top out
Location: A few feet left of Rebuttal

Description: According to Sandstone Warrior, "rumored to be John Gill's hardest problem".
Location: Gill area

Description: Sit start low on the left corner and finish and top out on Roadside Wall
Location: Starts on the left corner of the roadside wall just to the right of the tree.

Description: Start low on an pocket you can undercling. Pull the difficult mantel
Location: Share the same start as Road Worthy

Description: Many fun variations on this wall leading up to the top out of "Miller High Life"
Location: Roadside wall, start low to the left of the "Miller".

Description: Sit start down low, work your way out and up on obviously rails and jugs till you reach a set up slopers and top out. Protection: Pads and Spotters
Location: Start right on the “Miller” painting

Description: Begin in cave feature. pull hard and reach to a lip, top out from there.
Location: Left of dwarf, refer to map.

Description: Sit start from a jug and move up and right. Push hard through a mantle and finish. Short and sweet.
Location: Gill area

Description: Begin as low as you can. Pul through good holds to some large throws out right, pull the slopey top out.
Location: Refer to photo

Description: Climb up and down the obvious Iron flakes. Top out is doable, but needs to be cleaned up.
Location: Stand alone boulder near in the main boulder field, facing towards the pool. Its hard to miss.

Description: Begin in the crack,traverse to the right and then head up. Fun problem
Location: around the alcove area that has the dihedral

Description: Start a low as you can with your left hand on the arete and your right hand on a undercling
Location: To the left of classic face

Description: Climb the different options
Location: To the right of the V3 Arete

Description: great warm up one hard gastone move
Location: By the frist pinic area foot bridge

Description: Slabby start, to good pockets towards the top of the boulder. Find feet and stand up reaching for pockets and top out.
Location: Free standing boulder across from Gill Traverse. This problem runs up the middle of the boulder facing the creek.

Description: Climb up the boulder to a great pinch
Location: To the right of Pocket Slab

Description: Begin on the undercling and have fun figuring out how to top out!
Location: Locate the undercling near the Arete

Description: start standing on awkward chest-height holds. throw for top.
Location: to the right of storm and rain. obvious line up center of matrix boulder

Description: starts under small roof with right hand on big sloper, left on edge under roof. move up, over roof, and towards arete/top
Location: from trail leading from parking lot, first group of boulders on left. located on left side of main part of matrix boulder

Description: Sustained first pitch followed by a spectacular traverse into an alcove up through a roof.
Protection: Standard free rack w/ small to medium cams.

Description: This is a high quality line with great movement on solid rock.    P1 (5.10c):  Follow bolt line to a roof with anchors.  This is a great pitch by itself and many people only do this pitch.    P2 (5.11d or 5.9 C1) Pull the roof on crimps and sidepulls to good incut flakes protected by bolts.  The step slightly right into a Flared crack with good jams in the back of it.  Exit the crack left at the top on good edges.
Location: Left of the dental bill and right of the the Blue Roof.
Protection: 14 draws and two cams (#1, #2, or #3 BD) if you do it as one pitch.  Otherwise the 1st pitch is 7 QD + anchor.

Description: This climbs the left of the twin cracks under a roof with a perfect handsized slot.  Pull the roof using the slot and pull into a left facing dihedral.  At the top traverse right and take the path of least resistance.  Use caution on the traverse (5.9) as a fall here could get ugly quick.  This is probably why it is named Genuine Risk.  The 11 crux is very well protected by mid-sized cams
Location: past the 3rd class gully found past The Bloody Nose.  This is on State Land and climbing is not legal here.
Protection: Doubles in the 0.5 - 1 BD single #2 BD and one #3 BD some small stoppers.

Description: This climbs the V chimney/dihedral to a roof.  The roof is a hand/fist crack that is set deep in a flared chimney of sorts; but, the jams are solid.  Pull through on jams into an easy 5.7ish chimney that leads to a two bolt chain anchor.
Location: Farthest side of Draper's near the fence.
Protection: Stoppers and a single rack to 3".  Some might like an extra 3" and a 3.5" for the top.

Description: The Crux is between 2nd - 3rd bolt and another b/t 4 and 5.  The route is very sustained so pace yourself.  The second pitch is a bit scary getting to the first bolt.  You will hit a ledge if you blow the move.
Location: Look for eye bolts right of Sidewinder, the popular 3 bolt 5.6.
Protection: Bring a small cam to supplement b/t the 1st and 2nd bolt on the 1st pitch and small - mid cams to protect from the ledge to the first bolt on the second.  Some like a mid sized cam to protect the final moves...but it is much easier climbing high on the pitch.

Description: This is a seldom done trad line at Draper's, but it is fantastic.  The crux short 15'..but burly.  The top is a little scary and one move is protected by a manky rusted piton.
Location: Right of Shame.  Look for a left facing dihedral with a roof.  Often wet ground at the base.  The route still has the remains of a large honey bee hive.

Description: This route is fantastic!  Esp. if you do it as one long pitch!    P1:  The crux is getting to the first bolt.  Bouldery and technical.  Then things ease up.    P2:  Crux is the b/t 1st and 2nd bolt.  A bit difficult clipping 2nd bolt may want to commit past the clip to the jug...then clip it.
Location: Just right of Dust Doctors.
Protection: mainly bolts.  But you will need some stoppers and small to mid cams for the 1st pitch.  The 2nd pitch is bolted however, you can place a green alien in a pod b/t clips 3 and 4.

Description: Take a right when main trail runs into wall,about 75 feet up small hill right before left facing dihedral.
Protection: 4 bolts, anchor little runout on easy climbing after 3rd bolt

Description: P1: Follow a broken crack system to a 2 tier roof to a sustained traverse into an alcove dihedral.    P2: Airy but easy traverse to a spactacular and bolt protected face.
Protection: P1:  Trad medium cams and stoppers.  P2: 1 large cam and 3 QD  Has 2-bolt anchor

Description: Fantastic 5.9 Dihedral Crack.  P2 not as classic.
Protection: Trad: Stoppers will do you fine and a few small to medium cams.

Description: P1  Chimney up to a slab.   P2 Airy and fun travers to a perch.  Continue to traverse left around the arete.
Protection: Trad:  Small to mid-sized cams and some stoppers

Description: Go up the easy crack system until you hit a roof.  Either continue up the roof for the direct variation, or as I recomend, head right on the horizontal, near footless, hand crack traverse.  Finish on the antkiller belay ledge.
Location: Just around the bulge to the left of Ant Killer.
Protection: small to medium cams and nuts.

Description: Start as C-Crack, the at the traverse rip up the overhanging hand crack.
Location: just as C-crack, but to come down you must downclimb the dead tree to the right to get to the lower anchors. Yikes!
Protection: Small to Medium cams and nuts

Description: Fingery route down low with a triangular roof (that one can cop a nice sit down rest on) halfway up.  Difficulties ease once you surmount the roof.
Location: 30 feet to the left of Geppetto, around the corner

Description: 5.8 climbing that is separated by a crux off of two somewhat thin crimps through a slight bulge (this can be dynoed through though if you wish for a more fun variation)
Location: The left side of the cliff, maybe four minutes down the trail.

Description: Located in a pile of boulders before the 45 degree wall, and behind two trees. Sit start with left hand on crimp, and right in pocket. Send from there.
Location: Refer to Sandstone Warrior

Description: Sit start with matched hands on a big sloppy pinch pocket. Throw out to a pinch on the arete. Pull yourself around the arete. The problem ends when you stand up on the face to the left of the arete. Good problem.
Location: Follow the directions posted on the mountain project page and they will lead you directly to this problem.

Description: Begin with your hands matched on small edges. Once set, throw out big to the right for a blocky pinch. Top out from there.
Location: To the right of Desperado in near the center of the boulder.

Description: low start to Smitty’s House that add one HARD move.begin on your choice of the 2 obvious iron edges under the low roof. The “potato chip” and the “L”.the First Ascentionist began matched on the “L” shaped edge and only used the “potato chip” as a high foot. But it’s fair game to start hands on both if you want.    Bring ample torque...
Location: The low start to Smitty’s House. Adds one nails hard move to Smitty’s House.  Described as a “sit start on iron edges” in the Sandsone Warrior Guidebook.In reality it’s not a true Sit start, merely a crouched low start since the ground is too low to actually sit (unless your torso is 5 feet long).There are 2 obvious iron edges under the low roof a couple feet right of the start of Smitty’s House. The one farther back is like a potato chip, the one farther out is shaped like an “L”.I began matched on the “L” shaped edge and only used the “potato chip” as a high foot. But if any suitors want to start hands on both iron edges, then I consider that fair game. It’s a hard move either way...

Description: Start with left hand on side pull, right on slopy edge. fire to the crimp, then shoot for the jug.
Location: Right of Smitty's House

Description: Start on 2 crimps about 4 feet left of the start of Touch Of Nature.Start crimps are below the LEFT side of the cool slopey pinch rail feature (and they are bomber, unlike the flexing start holds on Touch Of Nature)Move up into the cool slopey pinch rail and continue rightwards to finish the same as Touch Of Nature.
Location: 2 crimps 4 feet left of the start of Touch Of Nature.
Protection: 4 at least. There’s a bit of a talus landing. I had 4 pads and no spot and it was a very heady trip.

Description: From crimps at face level, move out to the cool slopey pinch feature, then continue out right on seam crimps to the obvious incut pocket, then up to the finish rail. Hang & drop.
Location: To the right of bass assassin on the face described as the "hang and drop" project wall in the guidebook. The start crimps are directly below the right side of the pinch feature.

Description: Begin on the lowest jug. Classic Southern Illinois sloppy topout.
Location: Refer to Sandstone Warrior

Description: Start 3ish feet left of the left flake and climb straight up.    Dedicated by friends to Southern Illinois Climber Margy Roth who died in August of 1995 following a long battle with cancer.
Location: On the Short Wall. The Short Wall is located 20 feet left of Cracked Heart. The wall is not very featured and is a high angle slab about 25 feet tall.

Description: Locate the two iron flakes 5ish feet from the ground on the wall. Climb up between them and go straight up.    Dedicated by friends to Southern Illinois Climber Margy Roth who died in August of 1995 following a long battle with cancer.
Location: On the Short Wall. The Short Wall is located 20 feet left of Cracked Heart. The wall is not very featured and is a high angle slab about 25 feet tall.

Description: Look at the wall and locate two plate sized iron flakes 5ish feet off the ground. Begin right of the flakes and climb up and rightward. While climbing, work towards a black streak.    Dedicated by friends to Southern Illinois Climber Margy Roth who died in August of 1995 following a long battle with cancer.
Location: On the Short Wall. The Short Wall is located 20 feet left of Cracked Heart. The wall is not very featured and is a high angle slab about 25 feet tall.

Description: It starts on the right side of the Short Wall. Go straight up the face towards a cedar tree. The route is named for Ferne Clyffe's Ranger Sam.
Location: On the Short Wall. The Short Wall is located 20 feet left of Cracked Heart. The wall is not very featured and is a high angle slab about 25 feet tall.

Description: Climb the hand crack. Takes gear well for the leader
Location: 18ish feet left of Divine Intervention

Description: Climb the thin flake until you top out onto a shelf. Top out straight above
Location: 40 feet left of Miles From Nowhere. Walk through a corridor formed by boulders on your left. After you pass the first boulder look to your right and spot a thin flake. The route begins here

Description: Clim up the dihedral crack
Location: 6 feet left of First Born. The dihedral crack

Description: Start at the base of the overhung, rightward angling arete. Go straight up the face, staying out of the dihedral.     Note: If desiring to lead First Born a rehearsal is recommended. The dihedral offers the only protection for gear. First Born in recent times is usually top roped
Location: About 80 feet left of Under The Influence.

Description: Climb the face on the inside of the dihedral. Continue up, angling to the right, and move towards an overhanging point. Pull over the point, and follow the aerie to the top.
Location: 40 feet left of Gangster. Its an overhung dihedral with an aerie on the right
FirstAscent: Scott Mueller, Dan Caldwell, & Pat Flynn 1995

Description: Climb up the face
Location: Climb the face a few feet to the right of Under The Influence

Description: Climb the dihedral crack, crux is midway up.
Location: First dihedral crack left of the blunt corner inside the woods.

Description: Begin up the crack until it ends halfway up the wall. Traverse left along a rounded shelf. Pull through an overhang and climb up through a "V" shaped groove.
Location: The crack 35 feet left of Rusty Pin

Description: Climb up the wandering crack. For a better challenge, start in the hand crack and work your way through the roof.
Location: Climb the meandering crack 30 feet to the left of Goreville Eating Society
FirstAscent: Gary Schaecher, Craig Barnes, Gary Frazier, Bruce Cyganowski, Bob Bennecke. FFA Adam Growowsky 1970's

Description: Work your way up and through big pockets while angling leftward as you ascend
Location: 20 feet left of Missouri Breaks. Go up through big pockets
FirstAscent: Jim Schneider, Jeff Allison, & Dan See 1994

Description: Begin by climbing through a small overhang on good holds. Continue through the continuous crack that angles to the right.
Location: About 30 feet left of Hawks Beak.
Protection: Standard traditional rack, takes small gear well.

Description: Work up right facing dihedral around to right-face, up through split in rock to large sloping ledge. move into large water groove/chimney for about 10 ft of crux climbing to slight overhang and "cedar" tree   at top.
Location: the approach trail ends at the cliffline.Cross stream to the right and approach the base of cliff which is a overhang/cave. the route starts at right dihedral in overhang. Fashion anchor with slings to trees.
Protection: The finger crack in back of water groove protects well with varied sizes and it has good stances to clip from.

Description: Supposed to go up and left. Hard line. Follow the path of least resistance
Location: Starts six feet left of Jennifer Goes To Hollywood

Description: Climb the face and avoid using the crack
Location: Starts three feet left of I Don't Care

Description: Climb the well protectable dihedral.
Location: 90 degree dihedral to the right of Hawks Beak
Protection: Standard traditional rack, larger sized pieces

Description: Face climb with large pockets
Location: Go around the corner left of Ditch Pitch and climb the face. Start about 10 feet right of Open Book crack.

Description: Climb the chimney left of Quasimodo
Location: Its the chimney left of Quasimodo.
Protection: TR from trees on top of cliff, might be possible to lead with standard trad rack

Description: Another straightforward climb straight up the center of the crack
Location: About 20 feet left of First Climb.
Protection: TR from sturdy trees on top of cliff

Description: A fun romp up a groove with a crack in the bottom.    Solid rock.  Easy cruisin'.
Location: 3rd gully from the right end of the crag.
Protection: Traditional route which might take gear in the first third is all.  Usually TR'd or soloed.

Description: Straightforward climb straight up the center of the gully
Location: Its the second gully from the right side of the start of the cliff.

Description: This is a tricky, balance dependent route. Climb no handed through the farthest gully /crack
Location: Farthest gully/crack on the right side of the wall where the cliff basically ends

Description: Single short pillar pitch.
Location: Follow the Waterfall Trail (Big Falls Trail) to the obvious waterfall.

Description: Good little warm up. Sit start.
Location: Further left and down from Tempest, look for the iron canvas.

Description: A matter of fight. Start on the high juggy side pull in the middle of the face.
Location: To the climbers left of the high roller, look for the giant fin.

Description: What it lacks in height it gains in movement. Start on the incuts on the left side of the slopey ledge.
Location: Right of the Canvas.

Description: The Orb looking rock left of Fly Mode. Start on the center of the ledge and top out the center of the Orb.
Location: Left of Fly Mode, the center line.

Description: First problem that went up at The Forge, for obvious reason. Finish left of the tree, on top of the boulder. Start on the undercling pocket on the far right side of the boulder, see picture.
Location: If you approach correctly, the is should be the first overhang you see.

Description: A fun start leads to a well defined crux move and a good finish. This boulder might be v5 with a spotter, who knows.
Location: On the Mode block, right of the start of Fly Mode

Description: Definitely an area classic. Start left hand low on underling and right in the first divot jug on the right side.
Location: Down a tier from the high roller, to the climbers right. if you stick close to the cliff there is a little rock step to get down, behind and to the right of the boulder in the picture.
Protection: Pads, a little cord helps but is not necessary

Description: Climb through the fractured crack system, eventually working you way through the pocketed upper face to the anchor.     Note: make sure you find the horizontal gear placement before leaving the wide upper crack.
Location: This is the obvious crack up the hill and left of George's. Refer to photo.

Description: Climb the slabby face finding good holds along the way, then when the face goes vertical, stay right of the crack feature. This route shares anchors with Easy Crack. Note: once you have this route set up, take a fun top rope lap on Easy Crack.
Location: Farthest left bolted route on the wall. Directly left of Barnes Overhang.

Description: Climb up the slab to reach the wide gully at the base of the crack. Pull the tricky move and enjoy casual climbing to the anchor.
Location: Directly right of Easy Crack
Protection: Cams .3-3 and a set of small stoppers to help protect the face.

Description: Work your way up the slab and through pocketed holds in the overhang.
Location: First route to the right of Easy Crack. Refer to photo

Description: While performing a ballet of sorts, use some creative footwork to stem and smear your way up the wide gulley. Pull on good face holds to crank through the bulge and reach the top.
Location: First sport route to the the Barne's Overhang

Description: Clip the bolt before pulling pulling the first bulge. Tricky is putting it mildly. Get your feet set, use the left hand side pull at the top of the seam almost directly below the first bolt. Reach up, grab the crimp with your right hand, and slap your way up the big sloper feature on the left. Climb the face and reach the bulge. Use a right handed, 2 finger pocket and perform a hard sidepull while getting your feet high to reach a decent left handed edge. Crank through and climb a short face to reach an anchor.
Location: First sport route to the right of Tiny Dancer/first route to the left of Nowhere

Description: Begin with the short, overhung start. Pull up and stand on iron-band ledge. Pull up and to the "pentagonal" hand pocket. Continue up the slab to a 3-finger pocket. Pull the move and follow good holds to the finish.
Location: First sport route to the left of Joe's Variation

Description: Beginning a few feet left of Joe's. Locate the large pinch hold and crank up the face. Use a series of side pulls, edges, and underclings to reach the bulge. Reach out right, stick the pocket and work your way over the bulge using pockets and a life saving edge. Easier moves to the anchor from here.
Location: Begins a few feet left of Joe's Variation, refer to photo for specifics.

Description: Originally, you were to ascend the left facing crack system continuing straight above. Now, you begin just right of the original crack and climb the face.
Location: A few feet left of The Bulge, refer to photo for specifics.

Description: Start on the short rightward tieback. Pull the mantel shelf about 10 feet up. Then go straight up to the top while staying 6 feet left of George's chimney.
Location: Starts a few feet left of George's direct, refer to the photo for specifics.

Description: Start directly below on the right side and make you way towards the chimney, plug your way through the gully crack.
Location: The next large gully crack to the left of Chimney.
Protection: You can clip three bolts as you climb up the face, then use catalogs 1-3 to protect crack, and now has a bolted anchor at the top.

Description: Start on George's Direct but avoid the gully/crack system. Continue stright up, pulling directly throught the "nose" on the right side of the gully/crack. Follow path of least resistance.    Note: not recommended without trad rehersal.
Location: Refer to photo. Begins to the right of George's

Description: Begin up the ramp that leads to the Chimney. Refer to photo for specifics. Climb up the face, trick side pulls, work into the large undercling feature, then out through pockets and face holds. Stay left of the Shake N Back crack system, and right of Geroges Nose.
Location: Refer to photo.

Description: Climb the leftward angling crack system that juts off of the Chimney. Place cams until the angling flake feature meets the bolt line. Clip bolts from here to safely protect.
Location: Directly left of the Chimney. Refer to photo
Protection: Lead the first half with gear, as the rock quality decreases above the half way point, begin clipping bolts on the left of the crack. Follow the three bolts to an anchor.

Description: Start at the bottom left, follow the crack up to the chimney, pull through the chimney.
Location: First large chimney in the woods left of Poison Ivy.
Protection: Standard traditional rack primarily on the larger side. There is now a bolted anchor at the top.

Description: Starting just to the right of the tree, climb up for about 20 feet. Then continue up and right for 30 more feet, crossing back onto Dead Dog.  Continue by climbing through iron bands and finish by Cedar tree.
Location: Start about 8 feet left of Dead Dog. Refer to photo.

Description: Layback the crack that comes out of the right side of the cave feature. Follow the first crack system until a horizontal, iron-banded ledge, clip the bolt and traverse right into the other crack system. Follow the crack and place gear as you climb. NOTE! As you near the end of the crack, excellent horizontal gear placements emerge. Pull the face moved under the upper bulge of the climb and clip a bolt. Face moves up and right lead to the anchor.  Note: this is an excellent route that leads very well with gear. Bolts are exactly where you need them.
Location: The route begins on the small crack on the leftside of the small cave to the left of Shotgun.
Protection: NOTE: It is highly recommended to stick clip the first bolt!  2 bolts, cams No. .5-3 (doubles in No. 1 & 2), + an anchor

Description: Climb to the small cave feature then work through the overhung crack feature until it ends. Step up on a slabby face and work through face holds and pockets and eventually reach the anchor.
Location: A few feet left of Walk Up. Refer to Photo.

Description: Start by laying back the flake. Continue up and pull through the weakness in the overhang and continue to a narrow "S" shaped stripe. Continue laying back and move up and right to top out.
Location: 18ish feet to the left of Shotgun
Protection: 5 bolts + an anchor.  NOTE: It is recommended to stick clip the first bolt.

Description: Begin on Walk Up and make your way to the iron band jug at the first bolt. From here work right an up through a huge hueco to eventually reach the fourth bolt on Shotgun. Climb up to Shotgun's anchor to finish
Location: Begin on Walk Up and end on Shotgun

Description: Climb the layback crack system through the overhang. When the crack ends, continue on small pockets while following the straightest paths.    Note: Not recommended without trad rehersal.
Location: In between Walk Up and Double Barrel. Locate the short crack that goes through an overhang to the left of Shotgun. Follow a straight path up from the crack.

Description: After locating to two large pockets (the end of the double barrel), climb up following the straightest path. One of the more contiguous vertical routes on the bluff.    Note: gear placements are limited in the lower section, but improve as you continue higher. Not recommended without trad rehersal.
Location: Begin on Poison Ivy Left and continue straight up through two large pockets while avoiding the gully.
Protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, nuts, alpine draws

Description: Beginning on Double Barrel, climb up and only use the left of the large hueco's that make the "double barrel". Basically continue to the top from here. This is an eliminate version of Double Barrel.
Location: Shares the same start as Double Barrel

Description: Pull through the short moderate boulder problem to the base of the gully crack, mantle into the gully and enjoy.
Location: Directly under the gully crack.
Protection: Standard trad rack plus nut placements

Description: Climb through the dihedral layback leftward to the base of the gully crack.
Location: Obvious gully to the middle left of the Shelter 1 bluff.
Protection: Standard traditional rack plus some nut placements.

Description: One of the first 5.12's in the country. Starting on good holds, climb the overhanging pocketed face. Rest on the slab about midway up, then pull your way up the next overhang. The pocket pulling was futuristic for its time.    The initial crux has been soloed by Adam Grosowsky, Alan Carrier, and Jim Thurmond. Also has been led by Jim Thurmond through the upper section overhang in the late 1980's
Location: Nestled between Jill's and Poison Ivy Right, climb through the pocketed face while avoiding both crack systems.
Protection: Stick Clip The First Bolt!    4 bolts + anchor

Description: PLEASE NOTE: Jill's is difficult from the start. If you are not sure about the gear either stick clip or rappel down from the three eye bolts placed on top of the bluff and preplace you gear before attempting. This route is extremely fun, but unless you know the gear, you may be running serious risk.     Send the leftward leaning dihedral crack using pocketed holds on the left for feet "kinda hard to place gear", climb over the first bulge and look for gear placements, continue straight up looking for traditional placements, climb past the jug chair and reach the top for a good place to clip in.
Location: It's the obvious leftward leaning zig-zagging crack to the right of Poison Ivy.
Protection: Stick Clip The First Bolt.     5 bolts + an anchor

Description: PLEASE NOTE: If unfamiliar, it is recommended to stick clip the first bolt. Dim View is not as straight forward as it may seem. Also, due to the span between bolts 1 and 2, make sure your belayer is on their "A Game", to keep you off the ground if a fall were to occur.     Start on the small boulder in the ground for Return To Forever, from there climb up and left, when you reach the first big horizontal go straight up from there, eventually pulling through the jug chair, pick the path of least resistance to top out to Jill's anchor.
Location: Locate the small boulder in the ground that is used to start Return To Forever, from there climb up and left while paralleling Jill's
FirstAscent: Doug Drews, Joe Healy, Jim Foster 1970's

Description: Climb Dim View on trad gear. Boulder through crux sequence about 20 ft to good stance and some good but small gear( .75 and blue or purple Metolius TCU). Pull through the next pumpy sequence to reach another break which will take a #1 or #2 BD Cam.   Climb through the upper crux, sling the horn if you'd like then on to the anchors.
Protection: C4's- .75, 1, 2.   Metolius TCU- Blue or Purple   Slings

Description: Beginning on Graves, climb up and left about 4 feet. continue directly up and avoid Grave's horizontal hand slot. Top out through the overhang of Dim View.   Note, this is a top rope variation.
Location: Begin on Graves, refer to photo

Description: PLEASE NOTE: If unfamiliar with the beginning sequence, it is highly recommended to stick clip the first bolt.     (Pronounced GROVZ) "not recommended to be led without rehearsal" With small cave located climb through pockets, face holds, and side pulls to eventually reach the infamous cave of Graves, from there traverse left until you reach the small gully above the main crack of Jill's, plug and chug your way to the "jug chair", clip the old safety piece and top out.
Location: Locate the small cave in-between Jill's and Crackpot, climb through holds directly below it, and top out above Jill's
FirstAscent: Joe Healy, Doug Drewes, Adam Grosowsky

Description: PLEASE NOTE: If unfamiliar with the route, it is recommended to stick clip the first bolt.     Beginning on Graves, head up and right to a 2 foot "peanut" shaped hueco. From there work left for about a move, then back right and up through a honeycomb section into the cave of Crackpot. Work out and up the face to the anchor.
Location: Shares the same start as Graves.
FirstAscent: Doug Drewes & Joe Healy circa 1970's. Leo Kottke fans

Description: Start up Crackpot until you get to third bolt then cut left all the way to City Limits. You will pass through the cave on Graves on the way. Keep traversing until you reach the rest after City Limits crux. Finish the upper wall on City Limits. Long draw on the third bolt of crackpot eliminates any rope drag.
Location: Start on Crackpot

Description: Climb the overhanging crack system into the little cave straight above, continue above it and top out.
Location: Locate the cave about midway up and left of the Open Book Gully, follow the crack system leading up to it and top out.
FirstAscent: Jim Foster (during snowfall) 1970's, first free lead Chris Ecklund with worthless gear 1988

Description: From the two stacked pockets climb through the upside down V formation and stay to the right of crackpot cave.
Location: Starts on the two baseball sized stacked pockets about 15 feet left of Makanda Layback. Go up through the upside down V formation to the left of Open Book's bowling ball pocket.
Protection: 6 bolts + an anchor whichever way you chose to finish.

Description: Begin at the base of the Makanda Layback, climb up and left to the bowling ball pocket, climb out through the Open Book gully.   Variation: Begin by climbing through the gully of Makanda Layback after climbing through its gully, traverse left into the open book formation and go up it.
Location: Base of the Makanda Layback

Description: Begin at the base of Makanda Layback and climb up and left of M.L. setting yourself to climb up through the blank face
Location: Start on Makanda Layback, angle leftward and ascend the blank face. Stay left of the crack on Makanda Layback and right of Open Book's bowling ball pocket.

Description: Tempura Tour Complete is the full route that extends Tempura Tour from the belay chair above Jills, moves down Poison Ivy, and traverses the rest of the way towards George's.     This route offers some fun exposure and is well protected, especially at the cruxes. It is a true tour of Shelter 1.
Location: Begin on the Makanda Layback, traverse all the way to George's
Protection: Total Route Gear (Well Protected): two .2's three.3's, four .4's, four .5's, three .75's, three 1's, two 2's, two 3's    Pitch 1: single rack .2-2 (Double .4)     Pitch 2: single rack .2-2 (Double 2)     Pitch 3: single rack .2-1 (Double .2, .75, and 1, Triple .4)    Pitch 4: double rack .3-3 (Triple .3, .5) (The best/crux)    Pitch 5: single rack .2-2 (Double .75 and 2)    Pitch 6: single rack .2-3 (Double 1 and 2)

Description: This is the grand traverse that lets one venture across the Shelter 1 Bluff line. This route allows you to climb high above the grassy field below and avoids the harder sections underneath the overhang. A must for anyone desiring to explore the vertical sphere of the bluff. Absolute Classic!
Location: Pitch 1: Climb the Makanda Layback to the safety bolt, "give the old bolt a spin for good luck" and rig a belay backed up with a small nut.     Pitch 2: Traverse left through the Open Book gully and continue to the "jug chair" above Dim View and Jills. Than rig a belay.    Pitch 3: From here many options appear. Currently due to vegetation, most people climb straight up and finish from here, but depending on the time of year other variations may seem possible.    First Option: go either up or down 10-15 feet and traverse        leftward into the Poison Ivy gully. From there climb nearly to the top and traverse leftward all the way to the Chimney in the woods. From there rig a hanging belay, followed by toping out.    Scary Option: (5.9) From the chimney traverse all the way to Georges as a 4th pitch. John Payne had to blindly place a Friend at his feet for the only "worthy" gear.
Protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, stoppers, slings.

Description: Pull on small jugs to enter the gully crack, layback to the right and pull moves to eventually reach up left to nice horizontal edges, from there proceed to climb to the safety bolt "place a nut in the crack to the right to beef up the anchor point", then continue to the top through a rather blank section eventually meeting the last face, angle up and left eventually toping out and reaching the anchor. Fairly Committing Lead...
Location: gully crack to the left of the camels hump
Protection: Smaller trad gear down low then work into 5 bolts + anchor

Description: This climb is similar to Drunkards in the way of how it angles to the right and is well protected. This is a great climb for those learning trad. Crux is either the crux of Makanda Layback or getting off the ground for The Gully
Location: Begin at the base of Makanda Layback, climb up to the bolt, clip in and follow the crack at your feet as it angles to the right, top out on  Camel's Hump and use the anchors to belay partners up. (Easier Variation: climb up The Gully, go to the bolt, and then traverse right)

Description: Climb over the small hump using a few ticks moves. Work up the apex of that feature and continue to the top.
Location: To the right of the Makanda Layback and left of The Gully.

Description: Either choose to move a picnic table to the juggy ledge to aid in starting the route, or begin directly under the Camel's Hump and traverse left into the gully. Either way, stay left of Camel's Hump and work up through the slab towards jugs.
Location: Its the wash left of Camel's Hump

Description: This popular TR goes up the huge hump in the wall. By placing a picnic table at the base of the climb, you can make the start easier. Begin at the bottom-right of the hump and climb up toward the center. Top out through vertical bucket climbing. According to the 1972 guide Sandstone Climber, "every inch of the Camels Hump has been climbed."
Location: Goes up the huge hump in the wall to the left of Drunkard's Crack.

Description: This is the no-hands version of Drunkards Crack.
Location: It started a bit to the left (to the right of the direct start to Camels Back), but I suspect by now the ground under the original start has probably long since eroded away making what was an already a super challenging, if not utterly desperate, sticking of the first move all but impossible (improvise).
Protection: If I recall correctly the last high step off the top is R/Xish as you really have to lean forward and commit or you'll for sure launch off and go flying backwards off the damn thing.

Description: Staying to the right of Camel's Hump, climb the smooth face and skip the larger holds on the left.
Location: Refer to photo. First route to the left of Standing On Air.

Description: This is a short but sweet route. Standing On Air truly begins when the featured slab of Drunkard's Crack meets the wall just left of the small wash. Climb up the face using small nubblets.
Location: From the base of Drunkard's Crack, locate a small wash. Climb up and left of it.

Description: Beginning with a unique high stepping mantle, balance over on your feet using shallow divots. Layback, high step, and slab climb your way to the anchor.
Location: About 10 feet to the right of Standing On Air

Description: This route traverses almost the entire length of the cliff. From the anchors of "Drunkards Crack" all the way across the bluff to the anchors of "Easy Crack". The climbing isn't that difficult, there are some tricky down climbing sections as well as a couple of run out spots. It's a fun way to get some easy mileage in and to touch some holds you probably haven't touched before. I belayed the second at the anchors for Gráves and the anchors for The Chimney.
FirstAscent: May 9, 2020. Andrew Staff and Dave Hug

Description: Its the obvious wide crack that leads to the top. Commonly soloed to set more difficult routes. Great route for teaching traditional placements.
Location: Located on the far right of shelter 1 bluff. It is the obvious rightward leaning crack. Two smaller trees are rooted in the crack in the lower section. Refer to photo.
Protection: Single rack and an anchor at the top.

Description: Climb the sloping face and work your way to the anchor of Drunkard's Crack.
Location: Face directly right of Drunkard's Crack

Description: High angle step climbing. Follow the water groove
Location: First sport route to the right of Diagonal Direct

Description: Another high angle staircase of a climb. Easy goes it. Good first lead.
Location: First route to the right of Right Side Route

Description: Follow the broken crack system to the top, place gear when necessary
Location: 6 feet left of 1,2,3

Description: Climb the bulging arete feature 6 feet left of 1,2,3.
Location: 6 feet left of 1,2,3

Description: Climb through the triple overhanging system. Protects well on lead
Location: Located about 60 feet to the left of Jack's Crack.
Protection: Rack of cams .3-4, Long Runners, +Bolted Anchor

Description: Climb the angling, featured ramping face until you reach a steep wall at the top. Find the key holds to make the clip. Call it good from there, or very burly moves lead you to the top out. (top out variation 5.12-?)
Location: First route to the right of 1,2,3.

Description: Climb the featured face up the angling wall.
Location: First route to the right of Bittersweet

Description: Climb the crack on the left edge of the Gill Roof.
Location: The crack on the left side of the gill roof that extends to the top.

Description: Beginning a few feet left of Scales of Iron, climb up using slopey edges eventually gaining access to unique iron banded holds. Follow the path of lease resistance to reach the top.
Location: A few feet to the left of Scales Of Iron

Description: Climb the face left of Unknown
Location: 7 feet left of Unknown

Description: Climb the crack left of Slip. Crux is low
Location: The crack that starts 15 feet to the left of Slip
Protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, nuts, alpine draws

Description: From the foot trail, eye up the path of least resistance and go from there. The crux is in the lower section.
Location: From the parking area hike up to the bluff line. As you approach you will notice a gradual sloping face almost directly in front of you.  The route climbs on the face.

Description: Climb the clean extremely features slab.
Location: About 100 feet to the right of Slip

Description: Climb the featured slab, using an assortment of holds to reach the top
Location: Begins a couple feet to the right of Scout

Description: Begin up a featured slabby face utilizing creative moves. When it becomes more difficult, turn off your tunnel vision, and let yourself lean back
Location: Directly left of A Fissure of Green
FirstAscent: Bailey Bunyan, Molly Gabel, Dave Hug, Max Walsh April 2nd 2019

Description: Climb up the crack system that divides the slabby face. Follow the crack, protecting as needed, until the crack ends. At the end of the crack, work up and left to a bolt, then stem your way out the top. Refer to photo for anchor location.
Location: Far left side of the Amphitheater.

Description: Climb the Canyoneering Route or Fissure Of Green and upon reaching the anchors, continue climbing through two more bolts to an even higher 1/2 inch eyebolt anchor setup. A fun continuance of an already creative route.
Location: Begin on the Canyoneering Route or Fissure of Green
FirstAscent: Dave Hug, Molly Gabel, Bailey Bunyan

Description: Pitch 1: Beginning in Fissure of Green or the Canyoneering Route, climb up and build and anchor at the anchor behind the Super Slab Boulder.  Pitch 2: Walk right along the ledge and over to a bolted route that goes up an angled slab to the left of a roof formation.  Descent: A 60 meter rope can get you to the ground from the anchor of pitch 2. It will be easier to get to the ground by a pitch 2 rappel  Fun Note: This route lies almost directly on the border of Union and Jackson County.
Location: Refer to description.
FirstAscent: Max Walsh, Molly Gabel, and Dave Hug

Description: Pitch 1 (5.8+): Begin on either the Canyoneering Route or Fissure of Green and climb up the the anchor on the backside of the Superslab Boulder. Belay your party up to the ledge.  Pitch 2 (5.8): Traverse to the right, leaving the ledge for the exposed upper wall of the amphitheater. Work your way to the large bench formation and clip into the anchor. Bring your party to this ledge. Note, for parties of 3 or more, they will have to tuck themselves under the small roof feature.  Pitch 3 (5.9): Traverse right for one bolt, Then begin cranking straight up through a dihedral. Utilize good holds while protecting the crack to reach the cracks end just below a large ledge. Climb out right and up to top out the ledge and reach the anchor. Belay you party up from here.  Descent: Do Not Rappel! Walk off climbers left and out of the amphitheater.
Location: Refer to photos
Protection: Each pitch require no more than 6 quickdraws, belay station are bolted, but bring cordalette to build equalized anchor.     NOTE: If a partner falls on the traverse, it may be extremely difficult to get back on route, so make sure to have plenty of rope to lower them to the ground if need be.

Description: Pitch 1 (5.8+): Begin on either the Canyoneering Route or Fissure of Green and climb up the the anchor on the backside of the Superslab Boulder. Belay your party up to the ledge.  Pitch 2 (5.8): Traverse to the right, leaving the ledge for the exposed upper wall of the amphitheater. Work your way to the large bench formation and clip into the anchor. Bring your party to this ledge. Note, for parties of 3 or more, they will have to tuck themselves under the small roof feature.  Pitch 3 (5.10d): Traverse right for two bolts, Then begin cranking straight up through a bulge. Perform some classic Giant City bulge moves and gain access to a ledge. Pull one more buldge and reach the anchor. Belay you party up from here.  Descent: Either rappel down or walk climbers left and out of the amphitheater.
Location: Refer to photos
Protection: Each pitch require no more than 6 quickdraws (plus anchor), belay stations are bolted including equalized hardware, but bring cordalette to build equalized anchor.  NOTE: If a partner falls on the traverse, it may be extremely difficult to get back on route, so make sure to have plenty of rope to lower them to the ground if need be.  Pitch 1: 4. Bolts + Anchor  Pitch 2: 6 Bolts + Anchor  Pitch 3: 4 Bolts + Anchor
FirstAscent: Dave Hug, Bailey Bunyan, Max Walsh, Molly Gabel, Chris Nevell

Description: Beginning on a juggy sidepull, work through a series of pinches, pockets, and underclings to eventually get stood up in the large heuco. From here, work through a series of sloper and edge holds to the final crimpy rail of the lower section. Power through, and enjoy grabbing the victory jug. Fun climbing awaits you from above as you work towards the anchor, but its not over until its over.
Location: Far left side of the Amphitheatre, accross the cave from the Canyoneering Route.

Description: Make you way up some low angle boulders, and climb on top of a ledge. Pull on good holds that aren't easy to find and make your way to the top. A fun addition to the Amphitheater
Location: Directly below the Devils Standtable

Description: Climb the face to a small overhang. Very positive holds. Fun route.    Note: not recommended for lead but has been done. Gear is limited and not the best.
Location: Climbs directly to the right of the Northwestward facing arete
Protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, nuts, slings

Description: Climb up and pull the steeper side of the roof. Throw up and catch yourself on the lower edge of the table. Let your feet cut loose and pull the moves to the top. It is recommended that you belay the route from the top.
Location: The exact opposite side of the tower from Chris's Climb. Start in the narrow hallway
Protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, nuts, slings

Description: Distinct & awkward lowball on the short boulder next to the Gill wall. Hands follow the lip from left to right on good slopers.
Location: Begin on good holds in the middle of the small boulder to the left of the Gill Roof

Description: Start in corner on left of Leashless Angel. Go right and traverse around roof till you are past the corner then topout. Save some strength, top out is probably the crux.
Location: Sit start on low ledge left of Leashless Angel
Protection: Crash pads and spotter for top out

Description: Follow long moves on small holds out the roof
Location: First boulder problem to the left of Devil on a Leash

Description: Start with a huge move to small holds, continue out through jug eventually to right hand side pull, stick the swing at the end and top out.
Location: This is the boulder line that goes out the middle of the Gill Roof.

Description: The obvious jug line on the roof. Start on the jugs at the bottom and work your way from monster jug to monster jug. Top out is crux. Either pull hard up to the horn or move out to the left to pull over the top.
Location: The right most of the three really classic lines on this roof

Description: Begin with a sit start, throw left hand to obvious fat sloppy pinch, stick the match and climb out the roof
Location: First problem to the right of The Standard

Description: Sit start right facing crack to the right of Pinch Me. Move out to the obvious shelf then traverse left. Same top out at Pinch Me.
Location: Begins at the crack to the right of Pinch Me

Description: Sit start and climb the arete using gastons and pockets, feet like to cut...

Description: Sit start and layback the arete, climb through apex and top out. Super slopey and cool. People call this problem V3 but is more likely V4.
Location: Down past the little stream and up by the actual standtable. Before the sign turn left and follow a noticable path down by the bluff. On the backside of a boulder facing the bluff is a left leaning arete, this is Buzz Arete. Its directly across from Jah Arete

Description: Match hands on good edge with bad feet, make big moves and go up and left.

Description: Use the high start and climb up the right side of the arete

Description: Begin with right hand on side pull in the seam, and left hand in shallow pocket. Throw to the fish head “open mouth” hold and work up and left, then top out.

Description: Beginning with a left hand on a crimp, and your right hand with fingers stacked in a flaring groove, plant your feet and fire up to the chicken heads. Pull through good holds and exit left or right.
Location: 3 feet right of Goldfish

Description: Begin very low in the good undercling hueco. Throw up to some crimpy holds and work through slopers and edges to finish. A burly move awaits
Location: 5 feet right of Cluck Catcher

Description: Beginning low in the seam, utilize crimps and slopers and side pulls to eventually top out. The struggle is real.

Description: Sit start in obvious pockets work up to crack feature, heel hook the overhung roof and top out.

Description: Sit start. Intermediate jugs exist.

Description: Starts in buckets at eye level, continues through a softball-sized pocket to a highball top-out.

Description: This is the highball problem just left of The Streak. Starts in sidepull crimps and climbs through the biggest feature on the wall, a large hueco.

Location: This is on the short boulder in front of The Center Line.

Description: Starts 8 ft right of Higher Education, sit start on low slopers.

Description: Sit start on the side pull, and throw for the Hueco. Work through the Hueco and climb up and left to top out

Description: This is the infamous bouldering traverse problem that lines the lower edge of Shelter 1. This traverse holds three different crux sections. If you can find them, there are no hand rests along the way. This is truly a world class climb.
Location: This classic variation is located between the Jill's and Camel's Hump. Start on the rock protruding out of the ground  at the base of Jill's, proceed by following path of lease resistance, and end by standing up at the base of Camel's Hump.

Description: Start on the back obvious feature. Climb out and left to long move.

There are some loose holds, but they seem locked in there for the most part. Top is basically covered by a growing sapling, which leads to a less-than-attractive topout. Hence the name...

Description: Start on the side pull/rail around chest level. Finish by matching on the underside of the roof (there are no holds, press into it).     Move up using crimps and jugs/rails. Crux is the first sequence of moves on the route. After the initial sequence of crimps it is nothing but jugs/rails.
Location: On the cliff face behind Zach's Graduation and to the right. Has a small triangular roof over the dihedral.    Walk down the trail along the cliff face and stay to the left. There should be a small clearing after the second or third trail to the right. Route is off the trail on the cliff face from this clearing on the trail.    Nearly all choss has been cleared from the route, the bottom is cleaner than the top. Top of the route will be thoroughly cleaned before the end of May (2017) once I bring my ropes along.

Description: Start on the marked hand holds and traverse across don't use the lip until you reach the section that starts moving up to top out. If you use the lip it probably is substantially easierDid not see this on the page if there's an earlier ascent please enter it. We were a bunch of gym climbers looking for a real V0 if that's you then this is a good route for you hahaha.
Location: This route is directly to the left of El Jefe

Location: Directly left to I Once Knew A Boy From Ogelsby.

Location: Left of "Once Knew A Girl From Oglesby"

RouteName: Once Knew A Girl From Oglesby

Description: Great roof problem with potential for extending a hard sit start and other variations. Work the obvious line out to the right.

Take that trail up the hill and cut left. This boulder, along with boneyard are on the bluff. NOT in the swamp area.

Description: Hard starting holds making this problem tough right from the start. Start at bottom left of the boulder and work your way right to the right side top. Top out is a little tricky also. A good lowball with a few power moves
Location: From the right of "swamp ass season" and left of the slab boulder.
Protection: Pad. Cleared a nice wide landing and choss.

Description: A little unnecessary but hey it's fun to spin around!
This is just to the LEFT of the Mushroom Slab, it's a traverse, not super hard but has a couple less then great crimps.
Location: Just to the left of mushroom slab.
Protection: Pads on the rock right next to it was all we used

Description: Start the problem on the jug rail under the slab and throw for the lip. Then follow the ladder of holds up the left to the top.
Location: Follow the trail all the way until you come to an open and clear trail going straight up the hill to your left and on your right are pillars from an old bridge. Go left up the trail until you reach the cliff line on your right, then go into the woods and you should see the boulders.
Protection: Pads and spotter. Made a good landing area already.

Description: Crux is the first move.  Sit start on the shallow pinch block, getting as much opposition as possible off the good foot hold.  Power up to the shelf, keeping core tension to avoid dabbing the other boulder.  There are several ways to to the slab.  I make a somewhat big move up to the good sloper in the middle of the lip, but there are various smaller crimps near the base of the slab or immediately below the lip to use as well.  Maintain tension to cross over your right hand to the good jug crimps above the sloper, match, then bump right hand up to another good jug crimp, and come into another good incut jug crimp to the left of your right hand.  Do what you need to to rock up on a foot and lean forward onto the slab, then walk up.  This route is technically an eliminate, since you cannot use the good jug shelves to the right or left of the slab on this line, however, it still works well because the slab is so large.  More like avoiding temptation to use them than actually avoid them.  The stand start begins on the jug shelf and goes at V5 or so.
Location: Sit start on the roof of the main boulder, right in the middle.

Description: Great feet throughout. Start on the far left with two good handholds move to the right to a big jug match then over to a decent crimp  match crimp (the Crux) then a couple good hand holds to the top!
Start underneath the boulder on marked holds & traverse left using toe and heel hooks. Throw blind around the lip and finish on Turtle Head traverse.

Start all the way to the left underside the boulder. Traverse right on the rail using heel and toe hooks until there are no more good holds. The main crux is a long reach into a small crimp with the right hand - using a bad bicycle, cross underneath and match with the left hand. Then reach around the lip with the right to link up with Reach Around and finish.
Location: Starts directly underneath the Mushroom Slab, all the way to the left. Yellow marks the starting holds + traverse, green circles are the crux holds

Description: Starting with both hands on the pocket rail underneath. Work out right and then up the rail on top of the boulder's face.
Location: On the right side of the slab boulder.

Description: Start on the same holds as Reach Around, but go straight up the face without using any holds on the arete.  The crux involves rocking over your foot on a good foothold at the base of the head wall and balancing to stand up.  There is alot of growth on the face, but all the necessary holds are clean and not lost within the greenery.
Location: Same start as Reach Around
Protection: 1-2 pads.  Boulder is low to the ground but the landing is at 45 degrees or so.

Description: Start on an left undercling and a right sidepull. Pull through using bad holds and solid feet. The crux is going around the corner. Finish on Trashcan.
Location: Up the hill a few steps past "Reach Around". It's on the left face of the Trashcan boulder. Both of which are on the boulder directly behind Mushroom Slab.

Description: fun compression start into a one move dyno to the lip of the boulder. The feet make this boulder the challenging part. Brownie points if you lap this right after you send the mushroom slab.
Location: Right behind the mushroom slab.

Description: Sit start matching on crimp just left of the blast hole, work slightly right on crimps to center lip top out of the boulder.
Location: Left starting holds of "Main Street Blues."

Description: Awkward low sit start with both hands in the blast hole. Move straight up. Can fire directly for the lip of the boulder or use small intermediate crimps in between blast hole and lip.
Location: After the mushroom slab and slightly more uphill.

Description: Sit start on the low right side of the rail and work left toward center top out.
Location: Just to the right and slightly below "Main Street Blues."

Description: Low sit start work left up a series of crimps.
Location: Right of and up the hill from "Tinkering Toward Utopia."

Description: Very fun highball! Start on face left of the crack for decent holds. Move up and right into crack. - V2 Go straight up the crack. - V3 Avoid the jutting forehead on the right. Finish up the top nose for a slightly sketchy highball topout ;)  Rock is very secure here. Landing isn't the best. If you plan on topping out, go round n check out the top first.
Location: This is in the NEW & developing Blue Elephant Area! From the entrance, travel allll the way down past the waterfall, past the bridge ruins, past the mushroom slab, until you come to an old concrete shelter ruin. The Blue Elephant area is past the shelter ruin, up the hill on the left. This crack is one of the first features you'll see on the left side of the east bluff. It's in front of the concrete pier blocks.

Description: BEWARE THE PIKE! This is a real bad boy. You can identify by the pike shaped impression on the left of the route, and by the spike of doom below... Moderately easy; a few little slopey holds/ insecure crimps. Crux is a few committing moves leading to a scary and insecure topout. Avoid choss to left and right of route. rock is solid in the middle.  BE ADVISED There is a broken wooden post threatening to impale any would-be senders who happen to fall far enough to land on it. Fr tho stick a crash pad on it (or chop it down :). Pro tip - go round and brush the top before topping out.
Location: In Blue Elephant area (see Connor's Crack / Keaney's Wall for directions). From the crack, go around the north corner of the bluff until you come across a wall with a pike shaped impression on the wall, and a broken post in front of it. Route is on the right of the impression.

Description: This is a good ol' verticle line up the wall. it features a solid landing and some fun moves. a good route for a beginner trying to get out of their comfort zone. Top out!!!  Start left with right hand on side pull and left hand on edge. Move right and up the line.  Avoid choss on the left and ledge on the right.
Location: In Blue Elephant area (see Connor's Crack / Keaney's Wall for directions). Its located on the west bluff right next to Pike.
Protection: Pad(s) and a spotter. Landing area is a ledge.

RouteName: North Chimney (Flat on Your Back Crack)
Description: Crack / chimney in the middle of the north side of Twin Sisters tower formation. Belayer is best at the very bottom near the trail - the climbing is 4th class / 5.easy at the beginning as you work your way up the ledges. Starts getting dicier as you approach the crack / chimney. Crux is when you first pull up into the chimney area and you're left to decide whether to try and wedge your way up the chimney or climb out onto the face. The hand holds are decent - the feet are a little trickier. Once you get over the chimney area its nice holds to pull yourself on top with some feet in the chimney to step up on.
Location: Twin sisters tower formation nearest the road, on the north face. From South park entrance - it's easiest to walk across the bridge and head right towards the bottom of the sentinel, then get on the road and walk until there's a dirt road access point (blocked by gate) to walk up to the road. Follow that down past the gulley, then turn left up the trail which will turn into stepping stones that will lead you up to the area.    From the south you can park and walk up a trail heading north which will bring you on the back-side of Twin Sisters.    Once on top - run rope through the rappel rings and rap / lower (rope will be bent over the edge of the tower).
Protection: No bolts on face, trad only. 3 Bolts with rap chains on top for setting up anchors in all directions.    after the first ledge there's some spots for tri-cams, or perhaps a smaller SLCD. At the second ledge there's a good wide crack to wedge things into - a Yellow BD Cam worked, as did a Blue DMM Torque Nut. The protection at the crux is a little tricky - you can get a tri-cam (.25 / Black) underneath the block wedged in the chimney, and a #6 / Green BD nut in a little split up left near the face. After that it's up and over to the top.

Description: The route called "Twin Cracks" is located slightly to the left (north) of "Difficult Crack," which climbs the NW arete of Brother's Buttress.  Source: Collett, Bill. "River Rock: A Climber's Guide to Mississippi Palisades State Park." Granite Pub, 1991
Location: In Twin Sisters Area

Description: This route is a challenge right from the start.  The crux is at the bottom where a short 7ft crack turns horizontal to meet up with the rest of the crack just to the right of it.  Using a nice jug that's deep in the crack and some clever smearing you can set yourself up nicely to make the transition between the two cracks.  After the crux is below you a series of well placed hand jams will give you success.
Location: The route is in the brother's buttress and twin sisters area and is just to the right at you pass the lower wall of the twin sisters on the trail that comes up from the road, parking lot, and outhouses below.
Protection: There is one large boulder and one 3ft round boulder on top of the bluff that make for great top rope anchors but if your short on gear there are some good living trees that will do the trick if set up properly. Available casual scramble to the top.

Description: Begin on the block and follow a tiny seam up and to the right.
Location: See topo. Begin on the block at the level of the horizontal crack 6 feet off the ground.
Protection: Thin pro, if at all. Available casual scramble to the top to build a TR anchor.

Location: See topo. Southwest corner of the buttress.

Description: start at center of face, easy classic climb

Description: Crack to the right of Java on the south face of Brother Buttress
Location: Twin Sisters area Brother Buttress south face
Protection: Top rope slings around boulders or a couple of cams and nuts. Available casual scramble to the top to build the anchor.

Location: Access to this area is from the top of Indian Head Buttress.  YOu can get to it from a moderate hike up the north side of hill.
Protection: Could use some traditional pro.  Has 2 anchors with chains at the top of this climb on the ledge just above access climb

Description: This is a short route from the access area between the tower and main face of Indian Head climbing area.
Location: Center access from the top of the Indian Head face.  there is an access route from the center face area wrapping around from the north side down into the chasm between the face and tower of Indian Head.

Description: Short route on the south corner of the Indian Head main face.  Nice holds and simple to belay from top or bottom.
Location: This route is on the main face behind the tower. It faces South West on the corner.
Protection: No bolts.  Plenty of trees on top.

Description: North face climb up the Indian Head tower.  Starts in the center of the north side and follows straight up the center crack the angles right.  Leads to a grassy ledge before finishing the remaining 15' to top out.
Location: Location is at the Indian Head Buttress area.  Top Rope anchoring is accessable from side access approach from the northside.
Protection: TP Anchors to the main buttress area across a 12' chasm which makes this route a PG for TR anchoring.  There are no bolts in route or on top.  There is a few large rock notches to redirect anchors.

Description: This route starts at the west-northwest edge of the Indian Head Buttress and wraps around the south edge.
Location: This is the west facing front edge of Indian Head Bluff, one of the most notable images of the Mississippi Palisade Park.  You will be climbing right up the nose!
Protection: Trad protection can be used. However lower in the route, the rock is more flaky.  This does not have fixed top anchors and will tyoically be anchored off the tree line across a 12' chasm.  Bring static rope for TR anchor for 30-35' span.

Description: Double-shallow-roof route at the north end of the wall.
Location: See picture. Just along the rail from Indian Head is a tall, crumbly monolith. Directly behind this outcrop is Bee Wall, and the Bee Line is the prominent double roof on the upper wall. The lower roof iw about 2 feet deep, and the upper roof is about a foot deep. There's a cedar at the top.

Description: A slightly overhanging face with several fine, roomy pockets. The only problem is that the pockets are just far enough apart to be brutal.
Location: 30 feet north of diabolical dihedral, and a few feet left of the gravel-filled off-width.

Description: Another hard face climb. The face overhangs, the pockets are small, and the footwork is dubious at best.
Location: 8 Feet left of Diabolical Dihedral.

Description: Generous pockets and a few strategic face holds are spaced just right to stay on the "fun" side of the line.
Location: This climb stays on the left face of Diabolical Dihedral all the way to the top.

Description: Climb 15 feet to the crumbly ledge. Follow the dihedral to the top.
Location: See picture. The large, blocky dihedral.

Description: Follow a small double-crack dihedral for 25 feet to an overhang. Dodge around the bulge on the left, and climb up 10 feet to a ledge. From the ledge, follow a seam directly above the lower crack to the top.
Location: See picture. Roughly in the center of the face.

Description: It starts with pockets and works left slightly up into the overhang. The overhang about halfway up requires interesting maneuvers and a little bit of power. great face climbing on good pockets and crimps. Quite a bit of pump near the top as you traverse to the same end as Nutcracker.
Location: Just to the left of Buzz Off and right of Nutcracker on the mostly blank face.

Description: Climb 10 feet into a seam, that opens up into a dihedral. When that gets too tough, step right around the corner.
Location: See Picture. The whitest nose on the buttress, at the right edge of Bee Wall.

Description: Follow the dihedral to the top. Surprisingly solid rock. The route passes behind a cedar tree halfway up.
Location: The blocky dihedral just right of Buzz Off

Description: Climb up the blocky cleft to the find hand crack that starts 30 feet off the ground. Follow the crack for 15 feet and finish beneath the cedar branch.
Location: 10 feet right of Shady Lane.

Description: Climb up and left on a ramp. When you reach the dead end in the yellow, overhanging dihedral, traverse right on a small horizontal ledge to the center of a smooth face. Using and undercling and a very long reach, continue up the face to ledge holds and pockets with a mantel to the top.
Location: See picture. 5 feet left of Decapitator.

Description: Stay out of the depths of the chimney by stemming across the opening. Avoid the huge hanging blade that gives the climb its name.
Location: The large, block-filled chimney near the right edge of the wall.

Description: In the center of the wall is a yellow nose pointing Southwest. Climb the face just below this nose, and then tackle the nose itself.
Location: the left climb on the small wall just south and uphill from the main wall.

Description: Climb up to the lone bush on this ramp, and then take the hand crack up to the cedar.
Location: In between the prominent roofs of Six Hairy Legs and Four Wings and Fly, is a rubble-covered, low-angle nose.

Description: Climb straight up the center of the face.

Description: This climb follows the rotten 6th dihedral to the right from waterfall access. (Second dihedral North of Wide Glide.) Thrash your way up the dirty, loose, gnarly crack and claim the ascent!

Learn to climb hanging upside-down for about 15 feet and this wild line could be yours.

Location: South-facing "Domes" area with a 45 degree wall.

Description: P1: Begin on The Tallest Man and climb to the second bolt. Continue left clipping bolts as you continue to the Rapp Crack. Protect the crack with gear and work onto the traverse ledge of Dietsche Legacy Ladder. Continue up to the 4th bolt and then traverse left on good/large holds and continue to the anchor of Dan's Dihedral. Belay your party to you from this point.     P2: Climb left using the anchors of the Lucky Strike Pillar for protection. Continue by using all of the anchors from Hornbein's Wall until you reach the anchor of Great Green Chute. Belay your party to you from here.     P3: Climb left and protect the corner of Horbein's Wall with a cam. Continue protecting yourself by clipping the anchors of the Community Effort Wall. Stop on the ledge at the anchor of Feeding the Hungry for a comfortable belay and bring your party across.      P4: Due to a large precarious rock (the has potential to eventually fall) down-climb to the ground and walk left along the actual balcony of Ryan's Balcony. Build an anchor using the two bolts of 50 Shades of Grey to bring your partners across.     P5: From the above stated belay, continue left clipping bolts from Vista and The Father Gift to climb into the dihedral corner of Spicy Guacamole. Climb up the face and work left at bolt three onto RIver Night & Flashlights. Continue left protecting with the anchors and build a belay at the anchor of the Hespen Arete.     P6: Climb left protecting with the anchors of the routes on the Wall of Wild Things. Build an anchor on the anchor of Sleeping Indian. Bring your party across, and once together. Rappell off the anchor to the ground.
Location: Begin on The Tallest Man and refer to photos for directions
Protection: Standard rack of cams, quickdraws, and runners to extend/protect corners.
FirstAscent: Thaddeus & Ashley Portz & Dave Hug September 2017

Protection: Pads. Walk off climbers left easy 5th class

Location: Down the cliff 50 yards from seamless, the smaller boulder with the orange ish overhang.

Description: A real shame this one isn't longer. Start on the in-cut crimps at mid height. Proceed. Pretty sure the easiest way down is to down climb the problem.
Location: Just off of the main cliff, look for the short sharp arete.

Description: Grades? Pretty darn cool one. Left hand on the slopey crimp, right on the shallow pocket/ divot under the right facing rail. Top out onto ledge. Down climb or traverse left until you can WALK to the top of the block. Walk off near the wide entrance of the hallway.  This route could possibly go starting left hand lower on the hollow sounding edge, much harder.
Location: Just left of Dingus, First overhung section on your way to the main cliff.
Protection: pads. Down climb or traverse left until you can WALK to the top of the block. Easy down climb near the wide entrance of the hallway.

Description: Start right hand on the low sculpted pinch and left around the arete. get no hands on the ledge above and down climb.
Location: First overhung problems seen on the way to the main cliff. On the not hallway side of the block.

Description: Try to climb the huge awesome overhang. Supurb movement. Top outs loose mud, but a possible escape ledge exists..
Location: On the second section of cliff around the corner from the grateful fin. 50 yards left of The Fool's Progress, left of the crack/ break in the middle of the cliff.

Description: Start on the kind of sandy block in the back of the overhang. The rock quality immediately gets better. Make a big move to the lip, and a few more moves to top out onto the ledge. Also not sure about the grade of this one.
Location: This lies about half way between the Grateful Fin and the Solitaire area. Spot the tiered roof section of cliff line, this problem lies on the rightish side of it.
Protection: Pads. Downclimb and drop from the ledge.

Description: The first problem I climbed out here and one of the best problems so far, even being a drop off. Start right hand in the scoop, left on the crimp. Fire to the pinch. a few more moves will take you to the jug above the overhang. Drop. Kind of left right and center variations to get to the finish, all around the same grade. This would be a four star boulder problem if the to-be top out wasn't certain death by mud. Unfortunately I am discovering this to often be wet.
Location: This problem marks the beginning of the solitaire area, and lies on the left side on the cliff.

Description: As fun as it looks. left hand in pocket under the rail, right in the undercling pinch. Grab the jug on the top to finish, or test your odds with the mud and leaves that lie above...
Location: Far right end of the solitaire area.

Description: No idea about the grade.. Start low on two pockets in the middle of the wall, climb up then left, topping out the center of the prow. Scoot right asap on the top out to avoid mud and leaves. Walk off right.
Location: Just right of the fridge.

Description: Start right hand on the slopey arete pinch at mid height, left way down low on the in cut left facing crimp. Top out, a fun one.
